var PASSAGES={
p1:{text:"A researcher investigates enzyme X. She measures initial velocity at varying [S] with and without 10mM inhibitor I. With inhibitor: Vmax decreases from 100 to 50 umol/min, and Km decreases from 8mM to 4mM. A Lineweaver-Burk plot shows two parallel lines."},
p2:{text:"A patient presents with fatigue and jaundice. Labs show elevated unconjugated bilirubin, low haptoglobin, elevated LDH, and reticulocyte count of 8% (normal <2%). Peripheral blood smear reveals spherocytes. Direct antiglobulin test (Coombs) is positive."},
p3:{text:"Researchers isolate an enzyme from an extremophilic bacterium. It maintains >90% activity between pH 2-10. When they mutate histidine-57 to alanine, the enzyme loses all catalytic activity despite maintaining its tertiary structure."},
p4:{text:"An experiment measures O2 consumption in isolated mitochondria. With NADH as electron donor, O2 consumption is robust. Adding rotenone completely stops O2 consumption. When succinate is then added, O2 consumption resumes at a reduced rate."},
p5:{text:"A genetics study examines a rare autosomal recessive disorder in a population of 10,000. Twenty-five individuals are affected. Researchers want to determine carrier frequency."},
p6:{text:"A neuroscience lab measures action potentials in myelinated neurons. They apply tetrodotoxin (TTX, blocks voltage-gated Na+ channels) to one node of Ranvier and tetraethylammonium (TEA, blocks voltage-gated K+ channels) to a different node."},
p7:{text:"Participants are placed in a room with 7 confederates who unanimously give an obviously wrong answer to a simple line-length comparison. Researchers measure how often the real participant conforms across 18 trials."},
p8:{text:"Fibroblasts are exposed to increasing UV radiation. After 24h, flow cytometry shows: at low UV doses, cells arrest at G1/S boundary. At high UV doses, widespread apoptosis with caspase-3 activation occurs."},
p9:{text:"Drug A structurally resembles the substrate of enzyme Z. Drug B binds a regulatory site on enzyme Z that only appears when substrate is already bound. With Drug A, increasing [S] restores normal activity. With Drug B, increasing [S] does NOT restore activity."},
c1:{text:"Structural violence, first described by Galtung in 1969, refers to social structures that systematically disadvantage certain groups. Unlike direct violence, it is embedded in political and economic systems, producing inequality without any single actor intending harm. Paul Farmer showed that TB outcomes in Haiti were shaped by poverty rather than biology, demonstrating that 'personal health choices' are constrained by social position. Critics argue the concept dilutes 'violence' beyond usefulness by conflating poverty with assault."},
c2:{text:"Patient autonomy holds that competent individuals may make their own medical decisions, even against medical advice. This emerged as a reaction to historical paternalism. Yet autonomy is not absolute: emergency medicine overrides wishes when consent is impossible, and psychiatric commitment restricts autonomy to prevent harm. In collectivist cultures, medical decisions are made by families, and insisting on individual autonomy may itself be a form of cultural imposition."},
c3:{text:"Durkheim argued deviance serves essential social functions: clarifying moral boundaries, reinforcing norms, and driving social change. Merton extended this with strain theory, arguing deviance results from a disconnect between culturally valued goals and legitimate means to achieve them. When paths to success are blocked, people adapt -- some innovate through crime, others retreat into substance abuse, and still others rebel by rejecting both goals and means."},
p11:{text:"A patient with a thyroid nodule undergoes blood work. Results show: TSH is very low (0.1 mIU/L, normal 0.4-4.0), free T4 is elevated (4.2 ng/dL, normal 0.8-1.8), and free T3 is elevated. The patient reports weight loss, heat intolerance, tremors, and palpitations. Physical exam reveals exophthalmos (bulging eyes)."},
p12:{text:"Researchers study a membrane protein that transports glucose into intestinal epithelial cells. On the apical (lumen-facing) side, glucose enters via SGLT1, a sodium-glucose cotransporter that moves glucose against its concentration gradient by coupling it to Na+ influx. On the basolateral side, glucose exits via GLUT2, a facilitated diffusion transporter. The Na+/K+ ATPase on the basolateral membrane maintains the Na+ gradient that drives SGLT1."},
c4:{text:"The biomedical model of health defines disease as a deviation from measurable biological norms -- a broken machine to be fixed through medical intervention. This model has produced remarkable advances: antibiotics, surgical techniques, and diagnostic imaging have transformed medicine. Yet the biomedical model has been criticized for neglecting psychological and social dimensions of illness. A patient with chronic pain may have no identifiable tissue damage. A person with controlled HIV may face greater suffering from stigma than from the virus itself. The biopsychosocial model, proposed by George Engel in 1977, argues that health and illness emerge from the interaction of biological factors (genetics, physiology), psychological factors (mood, personality, coping), and social factors (family, SES, culture). This model does not reject biology but embeds it within a broader context."},
p20:{text:"Researchers investigate the effect of a novel drug on cholesterol synthesis. They treat hepatocytes with Drug X and measure HMG-CoA reductase activity. Results show Drug X reduces enzyme activity by 85% without affecting HMG-CoA reductase mRNA levels or protein concentration. When the researchers add excess mevalonate (the product of HMG-CoA reductase) to untreated cells, cholesterol synthesis proceeds normally. In a separate experiment, they find that Drug X binds reversibly to HMG-CoA reductase and that its inhibition can be overcome by increasing substrate (HMG-CoA) concentration."},
p21:{text:"A clinical study examines a patient with suspected McArdle disease (glycogen storage disease type V). During an exercise test, the patient experiences severe muscle cramps and fatigue within 2 minutes. Blood lactate levels fail to rise during exercise (normal response: 3-5 fold increase). However, blood ammonia levels increase normally. A muscle biopsy shows excess glycogen accumulation. The enzyme deficient in McArdle disease is myophosphorylase, the muscle-specific form of glycogen phosphorylase."},
p22:{text:"Scientists study a bacterial operon that controls tryptophan biosynthesis. When tryptophan is abundant in the growth medium, the operon is repressed and the biosynthetic enzymes are not produced. When tryptophan is scarce, the operon is active and all five biosynthetic enzymes are expressed. The researchers create a mutant strain in which the repressor protein cannot bind tryptophan. They also create a second mutant in which the operator sequence is altered so no protein can bind to it."},
p23:{text:"Researchers measure membrane potential changes in cardiac pacemaker cells of the SA node. Unlike typical neurons, these cells do not have a stable resting potential. Instead, they exhibit a slow, spontaneous depolarization during diastole (phase 4) due to funny current (If) -- a mixed Na+/K+ inward current through HCN channels. When the membrane reaches threshold (~-40mV), voltage-gated Ca2+ channels (L-type) open, producing the upstroke. Repolarization occurs through K+ efflux. The parasympathetic neurotransmitter acetylcholine slows phase 4 depolarization, while sympathetic norepinephrine accelerates it."},
p24:{text:"A biochemistry experiment compares two patients with jaundice. Patient A has elevated unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin, normal conjugated (direct) bilirubin, and normal liver enzymes (AST, ALT). Patient B has elevated conjugated (direct) bilirubin, dark urine, pale stools, and markedly elevated alkaline phosphatase. Both patients have yellowish sclera. Bilirubin is produced from heme degradation: heme -> biliverdin -> unconjugated bilirubin (carried by albumin) -> conjugated in liver by UDP-glucuronosyltransferase -> excreted in bile."},
p25:{text:"A chemistry lab performs a titration of 50 mL of 0.1 M acetic acid (pKa = 4.76) with 0.1 M NaOH. They record pH at several points: initial pH = 2.88, after 25 mL NaOH = pH 4.76, after 50 mL NaOH = pH 8.72, after 75 mL NaOH = pH 12.30. The students note that the buffering region (where pH changes least per mL NaOH added) occurs between approximately 15-35 mL of NaOH added."},
p26:{text:"A physics experiment measures the behavior of light passing through different media. A beam of light travels from air (n=1.00) into glass (n=1.50) at an angle of incidence of 45 degrees. Using Snell's law, the researchers calculate the angle of refraction. They then direct light from glass into air and gradually increase the angle of incidence until total internal reflection occurs. They also observe that the wavelength of light decreases inside the glass while the frequency remains unchanged."},
p27:{text:"An electrochemistry experiment constructs a galvanic cell using a zinc electrode (E-standard = -0.76V) and a copper electrode (E-standard = +0.34V). The cell produces a measured voltage of 1.10V under standard conditions. When the concentration of Cu2+ is increased from 1M to 2M while Zn2+ remains at 1M, the cell voltage increases slightly. The salt bridge contains KNO3 solution."},
p28:{text:"A calorimetry experiment measures the specific heat of an unknown metal. A 150g sample of the metal is heated to 100C in boiling water, then transferred to 200g of water at 25C in an insulated calorimeter. The final equilibrium temperature is 28.5C. The specific heat of water is 4.184 J/g-C. The students assume no heat is lost to the surroundings and apply the principle that heat lost by the metal equals heat gained by the water."},
p29:{text:"A developmental psychology study examines theory of mind in children ages 3-5 using the Sally-Anne false belief test. Sally places a marble in a basket and leaves the room. Anne moves the marble to a box while Sally is away. When Sally returns, children are asked where Sally will look for her marble. Results: 85% of 3-year-olds say Sally will look in the box (where the marble actually is), while 75% of 5-year-olds correctly say Sally will look in the basket (where she left it)."},
p30:{text:"Researchers conduct a study on stereotype threat. They give a standardized math test to male and female college students under two conditions. In Condition A, students are told the test has shown gender differences in the past. In Condition B, students are told the test has never shown gender differences. Results: In Condition A, women scored significantly lower than men (mean 65 vs 78, p<0.01). In Condition B, women and men scored equally (mean 76 vs 77, p=0.82). The test content was identical in both conditions."},
p31:{text:"A social psychology experiment examines the effects of cognitive load on decision-making. Participants are divided into two groups. The high-load group must memorize a 7-digit number while making food choices. The low-load group memorizes a 2-digit number. Both groups are then offered a choice between fruit salad and chocolate cake. Results: 63% of the high-load group chose cake versus 41% of the low-load group (p<0.05). Researchers also measured response time, finding the high-load group made faster decisions."},
c5:{text:"The concept of wilderness as pristine, untouched nature is itself a cultural construction. William Cronon argues that the wilderness ideal emerged from 19th-century Romanticism and the frontier myth, not from ecological reality. Indigenous peoples had shaped North American landscapes for thousands of years through controlled burning, selective cultivation, and wildlife management. What European colonists encountered was not virgin wilderness but a carefully managed environment whose stewards had been decimated by disease and displacement. The irony, Cronon suggests, is that preserving wilderness as untouched often requires removing the very human communities whose practices created and maintained it. Conservation that fetishizes pristine nature may paradoxically harm both ecosystems and indigenous rights."},
c6:{text:"Thomas Kuhn's The Structure of Scientific Revolutions challenged the view that science progresses through steady accumulation of knowledge. Kuhn argued instead that science alternates between periods of normal science -- puzzle-solving within an accepted paradigm -- and revolutionary science, when accumulated anomalies trigger a paradigm shift. During normal science, scientists do not question foundational assumptions; they solve puzzles defined by the paradigm. Anomalies are initially dismissed or accommodated. Only when anomalies become overwhelming does a crisis occur, opening space for a new paradigm. Crucially, Kuhn argued that successive paradigms are incommensurable -- they define different problems, use different standards, and cannot be fully translated into each other's terms."},
c7:{text:"The trolley problem has dominated moral philosophy for decades, yet its relevance to real ethical dilemmas has been questioned. Critics argue that trolley-style thought experiments strip away the contextual richness that characterizes actual moral decisions. In reality, we rarely face choices between clearly defined outcomes with known probabilities. Moreover, the utilitarian framing -- maximize lives saved -- assumes a consequentialist framework that many ethical traditions reject. Virtue ethicists ask not 'what should I do?' but 'what kind of person should I be?' Care ethicists emphasize relationships and responsibilities over abstract calculations. By narrowing moral reasoning to a single calculus, the trolley problem may distort rather than illuminate how people actually navigate ethical complexity."},
};

