var QS=[
// ============ ENZYME KINETICS (16) ============
{id:"ek1",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Kinetics Parameters"],diff:2,q:"In uncompetitive inhibition, what happens to Km and Vmax?",o:["Both decrease","Km increases, Vmax decreases","Both increase","Km decreases, Vmax unchanged"],a:0,ex:"The inhibitor only binds the enzyme-substrate (ES) complex, creating a dead-end ESI complex. This traps ES, and by Le Chatelier's principle, the equilibrium E + S <-> ES shifts right to compensate -- the enzyme appears to have higher affinity (lower Km). Meanwhile, locked-up ESI reduces the effective enzyme pool, lowering Vmax. The signature: both Km and Vmax decrease together. No other inhibition type does this. Competitive raises Km only. Noncompetitive lowers Vmax only. Mixed changes both but not in parallel.",mn:"UN-competitive = everything goes UN-der (both down together)"},
{id:"ek2",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Kinetics Parameters"],diff:2,q:"Noncompetitive inhibition changes which parameter?",o:["Only Vmax decreases","Only Km increases","Both decrease","Only Km decreases"],a:0,ex:"Noncompetitive inhibitors bind an allosteric site on the enzyme regardless of whether substrate is bound. Since the inhibitor does not interfere with substrate binding, Km stays the same. But the enzyme-inhibitor complex has reduced or zero catalytic activity -- like permanently removing some machines from a factory. Fewer working enzymes means lower maximum rate (Vmax drops). This is the defining feature: unchanged Km, decreased Vmax.",mn:"NON-competitive = NO Km change. Only Vmax drops."},
{id:"ek3",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:2,q:"Lineweaver-Burk plot for uncompetitive inhibition shows:",o:["Parallel lines","Lines crossing on y-axis","Lines crossing on x-axis","Same line"],a:0,ex:"On the double-reciprocal (1/V vs 1/[S]) Lineweaver-Burk plot: the slope = Km/Vmax. In uncompetitive inhibition, both Km and Vmax decrease by the same factor, so the slope stays constant -- producing PARALLEL lines. This is the most distinctive pattern. Quick reference: Competitive = y-axis intersection (same Vmax). Noncompetitive = x-axis intersection (same Km). Uncompetitive = parallel (unique).",mn:"Parallel lines = uncompetitive. The ONLY type with this LB pattern."},
{id:"ek4",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:2,q:"Competitive inhibitor LB lines intersect on the:",o:["Y-axis","X-axis","Origin","They are parallel"],a:0,ex:"Competitive inhibitors compete for the active site. More substrate can always outcompete them, so Vmax is unchanged (same y-intercept = 1/Vmax). But apparent Km increases (different x-intercept = -1/Km). All lines share the y-intercept and fan outward.",mn:"Competitive = same y-intercept (Vmax unchanged)"},
{id:"ek5",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Equilibrium"],diff:3,q:"Why does Km decrease in uncompetitive inhibition?",o:["Inhibitor traps ES, shifting equilibrium toward more ES","Inhibitor directly increases affinity","Substrate concentration increases","Enzyme shape changes permanently"],a:0,ex:"The uncompetitive inhibitor binds ES to form dead-end ESI, removing ES from the equilibrium E + S <-> ES. By Le Chatelier's principle, the system shifts right to replace the lost ES, making it appear that the enzyme has higher substrate affinity (lower apparent Km). The enzyme does not actually bind substrate better -- it is an equilibrium effect, not a real affinity change.",mn:"Le Chatelier: trapping ES forces equilibrium to make more ES = apparent higher affinity"},
{id:"ek6",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:1,q:"An uncompetitive inhibitor binds to:",o:["Only the ES complex","Only free enzyme","Both E and ES","Substrate directly"],a:0,ex:"Each inhibition type is defined by where it binds: Competitive = free enzyme only (active site). Noncompetitive = both E and ES equally (allosteric). Uncompetitive = ES complex only (site revealed by substrate binding). Mixed = both E and ES with different affinities.",mn:"UN-able to bind alone -- needs substrate there first"},
{id:"ek7",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Kinetics Parameters"],diff:1,q:"Km represents:",o:["[S] at half-Vmax","Maximum rate","Binding energy","Turnover number"],a:0,ex:"Km is the substrate concentration at which V = Vmax/2. Low Km = high apparent affinity (enzyme reaches half-speed at low [S]). High Km = low affinity (needs lots of substrate). Km = (k-1 + k2)/k1 from Michaelis-Menten. Not identical to Kd but related when catalysis is slow.",mn:"Low Km = hungry enzyme (high affinity)"},
{id:"ek8",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Kinetics Parameters"],diff:2,q:"Catalytic efficiency is measured by:",o:["kcat/Km","Vmax/Km","Km/Vmax","kcat x Km"],a:0,ex:"kcat/Km (the specificity constant) captures both speed (kcat = Vmax/[E]total) and affinity (Km). 'Perfect' diffusion-limited enzymes: kcat/Km around 10^8 to 10^9 /M/s. Examples: carbonic anhydrase, acetylcholinesterase, triose phosphate isomerase.",mn:"Efficiency = speed (kcat) / appetite (Km)"},
{id:"ek9",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:2,q:"Noncompetitive LB lines intersect on the:",o:["X-axis","Y-axis","Parallel","Origin"],a:0,ex:"Same Km = same x-intercept (-1/Km). Different Vmax = different y-intercept. Lines fan from x-axis. Summary: competitive = y-axis, noncompetitive = x-axis, uncompetitive = parallel.",mn:"NON-competitive = X-axis (Km unchanged)"},
{id:"ek10",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:3,q:"Mixed inhibition differs from noncompetitive because:",o:["It changes both Km AND Vmax","It only changes Km","It only changes Vmax","It binds the active site"],a:0,ex:"Mixed inhibition is the general case -- inhibitor binds allosterically with DIFFERENT affinities for E vs ES. If it prefers E, Km increases; if it prefers ES, Km decreases. Vmax always drops. Pure noncompetitive = special case where E and ES affinity are equal, so Km does not change.",mn:"Mixed = both change. Noncompetitive = special case (only Vmax)"},
{id:"ek11",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Allosteric Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Allosteric enzymes display:",o:["Sigmoidal kinetics","Hyperbolic kinetics","Linear kinetics","No saturation"],a:0,ex:"Multiple subunits with cooperative binding produce an S-shaped (sigmoidal) V vs [S] curve. Cannot use Michaelis-Menten equation -- use Hill equation instead. Hill coefficient n > 1 = positive cooperativity. Classic example: hemoglobin O2 binding. Allosteric enzymes can be shifted by activators (left shift) and inhibitors (right shift).",mn:"Allosteric = S-curve (sigmoidal), NOT hyperbolic"},
{id:"ek12",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:2,q:"Which inhibition preserves Vmax?",o:["Competitive","Noncompetitive","Uncompetitive","Mixed"],a:0,ex:"Only competitive. At high [S], substrate outcompetes the inhibitor for the active site, so Vmax is still reachable. All other types create dead-end complexes that cannot be overcome by adding more substrate.",mn:"Competitive = only type where more substrate fixes the problem"},
{id:"pek1",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p1",q:"Based on the passage, inhibitor I is:",o:["Uncompetitive","Competitive","Noncompetitive","Mixed"],a:0,ex:"Three converging clues: (1) Vmax decreased (100 to 50), (2) Km decreased (8 to 4), (3) parallel LB lines. All point to uncompetitive. Competitive would increase Km. Noncompetitive would leave Km unchanged.",mn:"Both down + parallel = uncompetitive (three confirming clues)"},
{id:"pek2",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:3,pass:"p9",q:"Drug A (resembles substrate, overcome by more [S]) is:",o:["Competitive","Uncompetitive","Noncompetitive","Irreversible"],a:0,ex:"Drug A looks like substrate (structural mimic) and can be overcome by adding more substrate. Both are hallmarks of competitive inhibition -- it sits in the active site but can be outcompeted.",mn:"Looks like substrate + overcome by more [S] = competitive"},
{id:"pek3",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:3,pass:"p9",q:"Drug B (binds site that appears only when substrate is bound, NOT overcome by [S]) is:",o:["Uncompetitive","Competitive","Noncompetitive","Allosteric activator"],a:0,ex:"Drug B's binding site only exists after substrate binds (= binds ES complex only) and cannot be overcome by substrate. This is uncompetitive inhibition. Adding more substrate actually makes it worse -- more ES = more targets for Drug B.",mn:"Binds only with substrate present + not overcome = uncompetitive"},
{id:"ek13",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Allosteric Regulation"],diff:3,q:"Positive cooperativity in an enzyme means:",o:["First substrate binding increases affinity of remaining subunits","The enzyme is activated by its product","Km increases with [S]","The enzyme has only one subunit"],a:0,ex:"In positive cooperativity, binding of the first substrate molecule causes a conformational change (T-state to R-state) that increases affinity of neighboring subunits -- each subsequent substrate binds more easily. Hill coefficient n > 1. This creates the sigmoidal curve. Hemoglobin: first O2 is hardest to bind; subsequent ones are easier.",mn:"More the merrier -- each binding makes the next easier"},
// ============ METABOLISM (18) ============
{id:"met1",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Aerobic Respiration","ATP Yield"],diff:1,q:"Net ATP from one glucose (aerobic):",o:["30-32","36-38","2","4"],a:0,ex:"Modern answer: 30-32 ATP. The old 36-38 used incorrect P/O ratios. Breakdown: Glycolysis = 2 ATP + 2 NADH. PDH = 2 NADH. Krebs = 2 GTP + 6 NADH + 2 FADH2. Each NADH yields ~2.5 ATP, each FADH2 ~1.5 ATP in oxidative phosphorylation. If you see 36-38, it is almost certainly a trap answer.",mn:"30-32 is correct. 36-38 is the MCAT trap."},
{id:"met2",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Enzyme Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Rate-limiting enzyme of glycolysis:",o:["PFK-1","Hexokinase","Pyruvate kinase","Aldolase"],a:0,ex:"PFK-1 catalyzes the committed step (F6P to F1,6BP). Activated by AMP, ADP, fructose-2,6-bisphosphate. Inhibited by ATP, citrate. Hexokinase is the first step but G6P has other possible fates (PPP, glycogen).",mn:"PFK-1 = gatekeeper of glycolysis. Low energy turns it ON."},
{id:"met3",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Fatty Acid Metabolism","Beta-Oxidation"],diff:2,q:"Beta-oxidation occurs in the:",o:["Mitochondrial matrix","Cytoplasm","Smooth ER","Peroxisomes only"],a:0,ex:"Fatty acids enter the matrix via the carnitine shuttle (CPT-I on outer membrane, CPT-II on inner). Each beta-oxidation cycle removes one 2C acetyl-CoA and produces 1 FADH2 + 1 NADH. CPT-I is rate-limiting and inhibited by malonyl-CoA (first step of FA synthesis) to prevent simultaneous synthesis and breakdown.",mn:"Carnitine shuttle is the gatekeeper. Malonyl-CoA blocks entry."},
{id:"met4",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Anaerobic Metabolism","Glycolysis"],diff:2,q:"Pyruvate is converted to lactate primarily to:",o:["Regenerate NAD+ for glycolysis","Produce extra ATP","Feed the Krebs cycle","Store energy"],a:0,ex:"Without O2, the ETC stalls and NAD+ is depleted. Glycolysis requires NAD+ at the GAPDH step. LDH converts pyruvate to lactate while recycling NADH back to NAD+, allowing glycolysis to continue producing 2 ATP/glucose. The lactate is exported to blood and recycled in the liver (Cori cycle).",mn:"No O2 = no ETC = NAD+ runs out. LDH recycles it."},
{id:"met5",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Krebs Cycle","Electron Carriers"],diff:2,q:"Products per turn of the Krebs cycle:",o:["3 NADH, 1 FADH2, 1 GTP","2 NADH, 2 FADH2, 1 GTP","4 NADH, 1 FADH2","1 NADH, 1 FADH2, 2 GTP"],a:0,ex:"Per turn: 3 NADH (at isocitrate DH, alpha-KG DH, malate DH), 1 FADH2 (at succinate DH = Complex II of ETC), 1 GTP (at succinyl-CoA synthetase). Per glucose: multiply by 2 since each glucose yields 2 acetyl-CoA. The Krebs cycle occurs in the mitochondrial matrix.",mn:"Per turn: 3N, 1F, 1G. Per glucose: double everything."},
{id:"met6",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Hormonal Regulation","Insulin"],diff:2,q:"Insulin promotes:",o:["Glycolysis and glycogen synthesis","Gluconeogenesis","Beta-oxidation","Ketogenesis"],a:0,ex:"Insulin = fed state hormone (beta-cells). Activates: glycolysis, glycogen synthase, lipogenesis, protein synthesis, GLUT4 translocation. Inhibits: gluconeogenesis, glycogenolysis, lipolysis, ketogenesis. Glucagon does the opposite (fasting state, alpha-cells).",mn:"Insulin = fed = STORE. Glucagon = fasting = MOBILIZE."},
{id:"met7",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Hormonal Regulation","Glucagon"],diff:2,q:"Glucagon primarily targets the:",o:["Liver","Skeletal muscle","Brain","Adipose tissue"],a:0,ex:"Glucagon targets the LIVER for glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis. Critical fact: muscle has NO glucagon receptors. Muscle uses epinephrine (not glucagon) to activate glycogenolysis during fight-or-flight. Muscle also lacks glucose-6-phosphatase, so it cannot export glucose to blood.",mn:"Glucagon = liver ONLY. No muscle receptors."},
{id:"met8",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,q:"FADH2 enters the ETC at:",o:["Complex II","Complex I","Complex III","Complex IV"],a:0,ex:"FADH2 donates electrons to Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase), bypassing Complex I. Since Complexes I, III, and IV are the three proton pumps, FADH2 uses only two pumps (III and IV), producing ~1.5 ATP vs ~2.5 for NADH (which enters at Complex I and uses all three). Flow: NADH -> I -> CoQ -> III -> CytC -> IV -> O2. FADH2 -> II -> CoQ -> III -> CytC -> IV -> O2.",mn:"FADH2 enters at Complex II, skips I = fewer protons = 1.5 ATP"},
{id:"met9",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Ketogenesis","Fatty Acid Metabolism"],diff:3,q:"Ketone bodies are produced from:",o:["Excess acetyl-CoA in the liver","Pyruvate in muscle","Glucose in the brain","Fatty acids in adipose"],a:0,ex:"During fasting, the liver produces excess acetyl-CoA from beta-oxidation that overwhelms the Krebs cycle (OAA is diverted to gluconeogenesis). Excess acetyl-CoA becomes ketone bodies: acetoacetate, beta-hydroxybutyrate, acetone. The liver CANNOT use ketones (lacks thiophorase). Brain, heart, and muscle can. Brain adapts to ~75% ketone use during prolonged starvation.",mn:"Liver makes ketones but cannot use them. Brain adapts."},
{id:"met10",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Pyruvate Dehydrogenase","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,q:"PDH complex produces:",o:["Acetyl-CoA + CO2 + NADH","Oxaloacetate","Lactate","Alanine"],a:0,ex:"PDH is the bridge between glycolysis and Krebs. Irreversible oxidative decarboxylation: pyruvate (3C) loses CO2, gets oxidized (NADH), and the 2C fragment joins CoA. Requires 5 cofactors: TPP (B1), FAD (B2), NAD+ (B3), CoA (B5), lipoic acid. Inhibited by its products (acetyl-CoA, NADH).",mn:"PDH = bridge reaction. 5 cofactors from B vitamins."},
{id:"met11",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Pentose Phosphate Pathway"],diff:3,q:"Pentose phosphate pathway primarily produces:",o:["NADPH and ribose-5-phosphate","ATP and NADH","FADH2","Lactate"],a:0,ex:"PPP branches from glycolysis at G6P. Two products: (1) NADPH for reductive biosynthesis (FA/cholesterol synthesis) and glutathione maintenance (antioxidant defense, critical in RBCs). (2) Ribose-5-phosphate for nucleotide synthesis. Rate-limiting: G6PD. G6PD deficiency = most common enzyme deficiency, causes hemolytic anemia on oxidative stress.",mn:"PPP = NADPH (antioxidant) + Ribose (nucleotides). G6PD deficiency = hemolysis."},
{id:"met12",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Gluconeogenesis"],diff:3,q:"Gluconeogenesis bypasses PFK-1 with:",o:["Fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase","Glucose-6-phosphatase","Pyruvate carboxylase","PEP carboxykinase"],a:0,ex:"Glycolysis has 3 irreversible steps that gluconeogenesis must bypass: (1) Pyruvate kinase -> pyruvate carboxylase + PEP carboxykinase. (2) PFK-1 -> fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase. (3) Hexokinase -> glucose-6-phosphatase (liver/kidney only). Gluconeogenesis costs 6 ATP per glucose vs 2 ATP earned from glycolysis.",mn:"3 irreversible steps -> 4 bypass enzymes"},
{id:"pmet1",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p4",q:"Why does rotenone stop O2 consumption with NADH?",o:["Blocks Complex I, stopping electron flow from NADH","Blocks Complex IV","Uncouples oxidative phosphorylation","Inhibits ATP synthase"],a:0,ex:"Rotenone specifically inhibits Complex I. With NADH as the only electron source, ALL electrons must pass through Complex I. Blocking it stops the entire chain downstream -- no electrons reach O2, so O2 consumption stops. This is different from uncoupling, which would actually INCREASE O2 consumption.",mn:"Rotenone = Complex I poison. Blocks NADH but not FADH2 pathway."},
{id:"pmet2",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p4",q:"Why does succinate restore O2 consumption after rotenone?",o:["Succinate enters at Complex II, bypassing blocked Complex I","Succinate reverses rotenone","Succinate provides NADH","Succinate reduces O2 directly"],a:0,ex:"Succinate is oxidized by Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase), feeding electrons to CoQ -> III -> IV -> O2. This entirely bypasses the rotenone-blocked Complex I. The reduced rate reflects fewer protons pumped (skipping one of three pumps). This experiment demonstrates the ETC has parallel entry points.",mn:"Complex II is downstream of Complex I. Rotenone cannot block it."},
{id:"met13",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Cori Cycle","Anaerobic Metabolism"],diff:2,q:"The Cori cycle shuttles:",o:["Muscle lactate to liver for gluconeogenesis","Liver lactate to muscle","Brain glucose to liver","Amino acids from muscle to liver"],a:0,ex:"Working muscle produces lactate (anaerobic glycolysis, 2 ATP). Lactate travels via blood to the liver, which converts it back to glucose (gluconeogenesis, costs 6 ATP). Glucose returns to muscle. Net cost: 4 ATP per cycle. The liver subsidizes muscle during intense exercise.",mn:"Muscle: glucose -> lactate (2 ATP). Liver: lactate -> glucose (-6 ATP)."},
{id:"met14",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,q:"Cyanide poisoning stops cellular respiration by inhibiting:",o:["Complex IV (cytochrome c oxidase)","Complex I","Complex II","ATP synthase"],a:0,ex:"Cyanide binds to the iron in Complex IV, preventing the final transfer of electrons to O2. Since electron flow stops completely, the proton gradient dissipates, ATP synthase halts, and the cell cannot produce ATP aerobically. Other ETC poisons: rotenone (Complex I), antimycin A (Complex III), oligomycin (ATP synthase -- blocks proton channel, not an uncoupler).",mn:"Cyanide = Complex IV. Rotenone = I. Antimycin = III. Oligomycin = ATP synthase."},
{id:"met15",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Metabolic Regulation","Enzyme Regulation"],diff:3,q:"Fructose-2,6-bisphosphate is the most potent activator of:",o:["PFK-1 (glycolysis)","PFK-2","Pyruvate kinase","Hexokinase"],a:0,ex:"F2,6BP is made by PFK-2 (a bifunctional enzyme that also has FBPase-2 activity). In the fed state, insulin activates PFK-2 (via dephosphorylation), which makes F2,6BP, which powerfully activates PFK-1, driving glycolysis forward. In fasting, glucagon activates FBPase-2 side (via phosphorylation), reducing F2,6BP levels, slowing glycolysis and favoring gluconeogenesis.",mn:"F2,6BP = most potent PFK-1 activator. Made by PFK-2. Insulin up, glucagon down."},
// ============ AMINO ACIDS & PROTEINS (22 including 4 matching) ============
// --- MATCHING QUESTIONS ---
{id:"aam1",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Amino Acid Classification"],diff:2,q:"Match each amino acid to its classification:",pairs:[["Lysine (K)","Positive charge at pH 7.4"],["Aspartate (D)","Negative charge at pH 7.4"],["Leucine (L)","Nonpolar, hydrophobic"],["Serine (S)","Polar, uncharged"],["Phenylalanine (F)","Aromatic, hydrophobic"]],ex:"At pH 7.4: Lys/Arg/His are positive (basic). Asp/Glu are negative (acidic). Leu/Ile/Val/Ala/Met/Pro/Gly/Trp/Phe are nonpolar. Ser/Thr/Asn/Gln/Tyr/Cys are polar uncharged. Phe/Trp/Tyr are aromatic (Tyr is polar aromatic due to -OH).",mn:"Charged: K,R,H (+) and D,E (-). Nonpolar: the greasy ones (L,I,V,A,M,P,G,W,F). Polar: S,T,N,Q,Y,C."},
{id:"aam2",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Amino Acid Properties"],diff:2,q:"Match each amino acid to its unique feature:",pairs:[["Cysteine (C)","Forms disulfide bonds (-S-S-)"],["Proline (P)","Helix breaker (rigid ring)"],["Glycine (G)","Smallest AA, most flexible"],["Histidine (H)","Best buffer near pH 7 (pKa ~6)"],["Tryptophan (W)","Strongest UV absorbance at 280nm"]],ex:"Each of these amino acids has a unique structural or chemical property that is commonly tested. Cys has a thiol (-SH) that can form covalent disulfide bonds. Pro has a cyclic side chain bonded to the backbone N, creating rigidity. Gly has only H as its side chain, giving maximum flexibility. His has an imidazole ring with pKa ~6. Trp has a large indole ring with the strongest UV absorption.",mn:"C=bonds, P=rigid, G=tiny, H=buffer, W=UV king"},
{id:"aam3",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Protein Structure"],diff:3,q:"Match the amino acid to its side chain pKa:",pairs:[["Aspartate (D)","pKa ~3.65"],["Glutamate (E)","pKa ~4.25"],["Histidine (H)","pKa ~6.0"],["Lysine (K)","pKa ~10.5"],["Arginine (R)","pKa ~12.5"]],ex:"These five are the charged amino acids, and knowing their pKas is high-yield. Below their pKa, the side chain is protonated; above, it is deprotonated. At pH 7.4: D and E are deprotonated (negative). K and R are protonated (positive). H is mostly deprotonated (~90%) but can accept a proton -- making it an excellent buffer and acid-base catalyst.",mn:"pKa order: D(3.65) < E(4.25) < H(6.0) < K(10.5) < R(12.5)"},
{id:"aam4",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Essential Amino Acids"],diff:2,q:"Which are essential amino acids?",pairs:[["Phenylalanine","Essential (cannot synthesize)"],["Valine","Essential (cannot synthesize)"],["Tyrosine","NOT essential (made from Phe)"],["Cysteine","NOT essential (made from Met)"],["Tryptophan","Essential (cannot synthesize)"]],ex:"Essential AAs must come from diet: PVT TIM HALL (Phe, Val, Thr, Trp, Ile, Met, His, Arg-conditional, Leu, Lys). Tyr is made from Phe by phenylalanine hydroxylase (deficient in PKU). Cys is made from Met. These 'conditionally nonessential' AAs become essential if the precursor is missing.",mn:"PVT TIM HALL. Tyr from Phe. Cys from Met."},
// --- MULTIPLE CHOICE AA QUESTIONS ---
{id:"aa1",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Classification"],diff:1,q:"Positively charged amino acids at pH 7.4:",o:["Lys, Arg, His","Asp, Glu","Ser, Thr, Tyr","Phe, Trp, Tyr"],a:0,ex:"The basic (positively charged) AAs: Lysine (K, pKa ~10.5), Arginine (R, pKa ~12.5), Histidine (H, pKa ~6.0). At pH 7.4, Lys and Arg are fully protonated and positive. His is mostly deprotonated but still classified as basic since its imidazole ring can accept a proton. Arg has the highest pKa due to resonance stabilization of its guanidinium group across three nitrogen atoms.",mn:"K, R, H = positive. Remember: Kings Rule History."},
{id:"aa2",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"Best biological buffer amino acid:",o:["Histidine","Tryptophan","Proline","Phenylalanine"],a:0,ex:"Buffers work best within +/-1 pH of their pKa. His pKa ~6.0 is closest to physiological pH (7.4) of any amino acid side chain. This allows His to both donate and accept protons near physiological pH. His is critical in enzyme active sites (acid-base catalysis, like chymotrypsin His-57) and in hemoglobin (Bohr effect -- His residues buffer H+ in active tissues, promoting O2 release).",mn:"His pKa ~6 = closest to 7.4 = best buffer. Used in enzymes and Hb."},
{id:"aa3",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Disulfide Bonds"],diff:1,q:"Disulfide bonds form between:",o:["Two cysteines","Two methionines","Serine and threonine","Any two amino acids"],a:0,ex:"Cysteine's thiol (-SH) groups undergo oxidation to form a covalent -S-S- disulfide bond. This is the ONLY covalent bond in tertiary/quaternary structure. All other stabilizing forces (H-bonds, ionic interactions, hydrophobic interactions, van der Waals) are non-covalent. Disulfide bonds form in the oxidizing environment of the ER lumen and extracellular space. The reducing cytoplasm prevents them.",mn:"Cys-Cys = only covalent bond in protein folding. Oxidizing environment only."},
{id:"aa4",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Classification"],diff:1,q:"Negatively charged amino acids at pH 7.4:",o:["Asp and Glu","Lys and Arg","Ser and Thr","Trp and Phe"],a:0,ex:"Aspartate (D, pKa ~3.65) and Glutamate (E, pKa ~4.25) have carboxyl (-COOH) side chains. At pH 7.4 (well above their pKas), they are fully deprotonated to -COO- and carry a -1 charge. Glu is Asp with one extra CH2. Both participate in enzyme active sites, salt bridges with basic AAs, and metal ion coordination.",mn:"D and E = acidic = negative. Dangerously nEgative."},
{id:"aa5",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure"],diff:2,q:"Which amino acid is a 'helix breaker'?",o:["Proline","Glycine","Alanine","Leucine"],a:0,ex:"Proline's cyclic side chain connects to the backbone nitrogen, creating a rigid pyrrolidine ring. This prevents: (1) donation of the backbone N-H hydrogen bond needed for alpha-helix stability, and (2) the backbone phi angle flexibility needed for helical geometry. Proline introduces kinks and is found in turns. Glycine is also a helix destabilizer but for the opposite reason -- too much flexibility (smallest side chain = H).",mn:"Pro = rigid ring = can't H-bond in helix. Gly = too flexible."},
{id:"aa6",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Isoelectric Point","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"At its isoelectric point (pI), an amino acid has:",o:["Zero net charge","Maximum positive charge","Maximum negative charge","No charge anywhere on the molecule"],a:0,ex:"pI is the pH at which the molecule has zero NET charge -- it still has charges, but they balance out (zwitterion: NH3+ and COO-). At pI, the molecule will NOT migrate in an electric field (key for electrophoresis and isoelectric focusing). Calculation: for simple AAs, pI = average of the two pKas flanking the zwitterion. For acidic AAs: average of the two LOWEST pKas. For basic AAs: average of the two HIGHEST pKas.",mn:"pI = zero net charge = no migration in electric field"},
{id:"aa7",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties"],diff:2,q:"Which amino acids absorb UV light at 280nm?",o:["Trp, Tyr, Phe (aromatic)","Lys, Arg, His","Asp, Glu","Ser, Thr"],a:0,ex:"Only AROMATIC amino acids absorb UV at 280nm due to their conjugated ring systems. Tryptophan (W) has the strongest absorption (large indole ring), then Tyrosine (Y, phenol ring), then Phenylalanine (F, benzyl ring, very weak). This is used for protein quantification: measure A280 and apply Beer-Lambert law (A = epsilon * l * c). If a protein lacks Trp/Tyr, A280 is unreliable.",mn:"280nm = aromatic AAs only. Trp >> Tyr > Phe."},
{id:"aa8",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure"],diff:2,q:"The primary structure of a protein is its:",o:["Linear amino acid sequence","Alpha-helices and beta-sheets","3D folding","Multi-subunit assembly"],a:0,ex:"Four levels of protein structure: PRIMARY = linear sequence of amino acids connected by peptide bonds (determined by gene). SECONDARY = local folding into alpha-helices and beta-sheets (stabilized by backbone H-bonds). TERTIARY = overall 3D shape of a single polypeptide (stabilized by R-group interactions: hydrophobic, ionic, H-bonds, disulfide). QUATERNARY = assembly of multiple polypeptide subunits (e.g., hemoglobin has 4 subunits). Not all proteins have quaternary structure.",mn:"1=sequence, 2=local folds (helix/sheet), 3=3D shape, 4=multi-subunit"},
{id:"aa9",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Amino Acid Properties"],diff:2,q:"Hydrophobic amino acids are typically found:",o:["In the protein interior, away from water","On the protein surface","In disulfide bonds","In the active site only"],a:0,ex:"The hydrophobic effect is the primary driving force of protein folding. Nonpolar amino acids (Leu, Ile, Val, Ala, Met, Phe, Trp, Pro) cluster in the protein interior to avoid water, while polar and charged residues face outward toward the aqueous environment. This arrangement minimizes the thermodynamically unfavorable ordering of water molecules around hydrophobic groups. Exceptions: membrane proteins have hydrophobic residues on the exterior (facing the lipid bilayer).",mn:"Nonpolar = interior (away from water). Polar/charged = surface."},
{id:"aa10",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure"],diff:3,q:"Denaturation of a protein destroys:",o:["Secondary, tertiary, and quaternary structure but NOT primary","All four levels of structure","Only quaternary structure","Only the amino acid sequence"],a:0,ex:"Denaturation (by heat, extreme pH, urea, detergents) disrupts the non-covalent interactions that maintain higher-order structure: H-bonds (secondary), hydrophobic/ionic/van der Waals (tertiary), subunit interactions (quaternary). However, the PEPTIDE BONDS of the primary sequence are covalent and remain intact -- denaturation does not break them. Some proteins can refold (renature) when conditions normalize, demonstrating that the amino acid sequence contains all information needed for correct folding (Anfinsen's experiment with ribonuclease).",mn:"Denaturation = loss of shape, NOT loss of sequence. Peptide bonds survive."},
{id:"aa11",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties"],diff:1,q:"All amino acids at physiological pH exist as:",o:["Zwitterions (both + and - charges)","Only positively charged","Only negatively charged","Completely uncharged"],a:0,ex:"At pH 7.4, the alpha-amino group (pKa ~9) is protonated (NH3+) and the alpha-carboxyl group (pKa ~2) is deprotonated (COO-). This creates a zwitterion -- a molecule with both positive and negative charges that has zero net charge (for neutral AAs). The side chain may add additional charges depending on its pKa relative to the pH.",mn:"Zwitterion = NH3+ and COO- at the same time. Always at physiological pH."},
{id:"aa12",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Protein Structure"],diff:3,q:"Collagen's structure depends heavily on which amino acid?",o:["Glycine (every 3rd position)","Tryptophan","Histidine","Methionine"],a:0,ex:"Collagen has a unique triple-helix structure requiring Gly-X-Y repeating triplets. Glycine (the smallest AA) must be at every third position because only H (Gly's side chain) fits in the crowded interior of the triple helix. X is often Proline, Y is often Hydroxyproline (Pro modified by vitamin C-dependent prolyl hydroxylase). Scurvy (vitamin C deficiency) impairs hydroxyproline formation, weakening collagen and causing bleeding gums, poor wound healing, and bruising.",mn:"Collagen = Gly-X-Y repeat. Gly must be every 3rd. Vitamin C needed for hydroxyproline."},
{id:"pmb1",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Acid-Base","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p3",q:"Why does the H57A mutation abolish activity despite maintaining structure?",o:["His-57 is essential for acid-base catalysis","The protein unfolds","Substrate cannot bind","The enzyme becomes too stable"],a:0,ex:"The passage states tertiary structure is maintained, so it is not unfolding. Structure does NOT equal function. His is commonly an acid-base catalyst in enzyme active sites because its imidazole ring (pKa ~6) can both donate and accept protons near physiological pH. The catalytic triad of serine proteases (chymotrypsin) uses His-57 to shuttle protons. Replacing it with Ala removes the chemical tool while leaving the structural scaffold intact.",mn:"Structure intact but catalytic tool removed. His = proton shuttle in active sites."},
// ============ CELL BIOLOGY (14) ============
{id:"cb1",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Cell Cycle","Mitosis"],diff:1,q:"Correct order of mitosis phases:",o:["Prophase, Metaphase, Anaphase, Telophase","Metaphase, Prophase, Anaphase, Telophase","Anaphase, Metaphase, Prophase, Telophase","Telophase, Prophase, Metaphase, Anaphase"],a:0,ex:"PMAT: Prophase (chromosomes condense, nuclear envelope breaks down). Metaphase (chromosomes align at metaphase plate). Anaphase (sister chromatids pulled apart by spindle fibers). Telophase (chromosomes decondense, nuclear envelopes reform). Cytokinesis follows: cleavage furrow (animals) or cell plate (plants).",mn:"PMAT: Prophase, Metaphase, Anaphase, Telophase"},
{id:"cb2",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Cell Cycle","Tumor Suppressors"],diff:2,q:"G1/S checkpoint is regulated by:",o:["p53 and Rb","Cyclins alone","ATP levels","Cell size"],a:0,ex:"p53 (guardian of genome) detects DNA damage, activates p21 (CDK inhibitor) to halt cell cycle for repair, or triggers apoptosis if damage is irreparable. Rb (retinoblastoma protein) blocks E2F transcription factor until phosphorylated by cyclin-CDK complexes, gating S-phase entry. Loss of either = uncontrolled division = cancer.",mn:"p53 = damage sensor. Rb = S-phase gate. Both are tumor suppressors."},
{id:"cb3",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Meiosis","Genetic Diversity"],diff:2,q:"Meiosis produces:",o:["4 haploid cells","2 diploid cells","4 diploid cells","2 haploid cells"],a:0,ex:"Meiosis I: homologs separate (reductional). Meiosis II: sisters separate (equational). Result: 4 genetically unique haploid cells. Three sources of diversity: (1) crossing over in prophase I, (2) independent assortment (2^23 arrangements), (3) random fertilization. Compare mitosis: 2 identical diploid cells.",mn:"Meiosis: 1 diploid -> 4 unique haploid. Mitosis: 1 -> 2 identical diploid."},
{id:"cb4",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles"],diff:2,q:"Lysosomes function at pH:",o:["~5 (acidic)","~7 (neutral)","~9 (basic)","~2 (very acidic)"],a:0,ex:"Lysosomes contain acid hydrolases optimized for pH ~5, maintained by H+ ATPase pumps. Safety mechanism: if lysosome ruptures, enzymes inactive at cytoplasmic pH ~7.2. Lysosomal storage diseases: enzyme deficiency causes substrate accumulation (Tay-Sachs, Gaucher's, Pompe's).",mn:"Lysosomes = pH 5 recycling. Enzyme deficiency = storage disease."},
{id:"cb5",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Apoptosis","Cell Death"],diff:3,q:"Apoptosis differs from necrosis because apoptosis:",o:["Is programmed, orderly, and non-inflammatory","Is accidental and causes inflammation","Involves cell swelling","Releases cellular contents randomly"],a:0,ex:"Apoptosis: programmed cell death via caspase cascade. Cell shrinks, chromatin condenses, fragments into apoptotic bodies phagocytosed cleanly -- NO inflammation. Essential for development and immune function. Necrosis: uncontrolled death from injury -- cell swells, bursts, contents spill out, triggers inflammation.",mn:"Apoptosis = clean suicide (caspases). Necrosis = messy explosion (inflammation)."},
{id:"cb6",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles","Protein Processing"],diff:2,q:"Rough ER's primary function:",o:["Protein synthesis and modification","Lipid synthesis","Detoxification","Ca2+ storage"],a:0,ex:"Rough ER has ribosomes on its surface. Synthesizes proteins destined for secretion, membrane insertion, or lysosomes. Signal peptide recognized by SRP directs ribosome to ER. Proteins undergo folding, disulfide bond formation, and N-linked glycosylation in the ER lumen. Smooth ER: lipid synthesis, steroid hormones, detoxification (cytochrome P450), Ca2+ storage.",mn:"Rough = ribosomes = secretory/membrane proteins. Smooth = lipids + detox + Ca2+."},
{id:"cb7",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport"],diff:2,q:"Na+/K+ ATPase pumps:",o:["3 Na+ out, 2 K+ in per ATP","3 K+ out, 2 Na+ in","Equal Na+ and K+","Only Na+ out"],a:0,ex:"The Na+/K+ ATPase is an electrogenic antiporter that uses 1 ATP to pump 3 Na+ OUT and 2 K+ IN. This creates: (1) the Na+ concentration gradient (high outside, low inside), (2) the K+ gradient (high inside, low outside), (3) a net negative resting membrane potential (~-70mV in neurons). These gradients are essential for nerve impulses, muscle contraction, and secondary active transport (Na+-glucose cotransporter).",mn:"3 Na+ out, 2 K+ in. Creates resting potential and drives secondary transport."},
{id:"cb8",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport"],diff:2,q:"Facilitated diffusion differs from active transport because:",o:["It requires no ATP and moves DOWN the gradient","It requires ATP","It moves against the gradient","It uses vesicles"],a:0,ex:"Passive transport: down the concentration gradient, no energy. Includes simple diffusion (O2, CO2, steroid hormones cross membrane directly) and facilitated diffusion (needs a channel or carrier protein but still no ATP -- glucose via GLUT transporters, ions via channels). Active transport: against the gradient, requires energy. Primary active: directly uses ATP (Na+/K+ ATPase). Secondary active: uses gradient established by primary (Na+-glucose symporter).",mn:"Facilitated = protein-assisted but still passive (no ATP, downhill)."},
{id:"cb9",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction"],diff:3,q:"G-protein coupled receptors (GPCRs) activate:",o:["G-proteins that trigger second messenger cascades","Receptor tyrosine kinases","Nuclear receptors directly","Ion channels directly"],a:0,ex:"GPCRs are the largest family of cell surface receptors. When a ligand binds, the receptor activates a G-protein (exchanges GDP for GTP). Two main pathways: (1) Gs activates adenylyl cyclase -> increases cAMP -> activates PKA. (2) Gq activates phospholipase C -> cleaves PIP2 into IP3 (releases Ca2+ from ER) + DAG (activates PKC). Gi inhibits adenylyl cyclase. Key GPCR examples: beta-adrenergic receptors (epinephrine), muscarinic ACh receptors, glucagon receptor.",mn:"GPCR -> G-protein -> second messengers (cAMP or IP3/DAG)"},
{id:"pcb1",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Cell Cycle","Tumor Suppressors","Apoptosis"],diff:3,pass:"p8",q:"G1/S arrest at low UV doses is mediated by:",o:["p53 activating p21 to inhibit cyclin-CDK","Increased ATP use","Direct DNA pol inhibition","Caspase activation"],a:0,ex:"Low UV causes DNA damage (thymine dimers). This activates p53 -> p21 (CDK inhibitor) -> blocks cyclin-CDK -> halts G1/S transition for repair. At HIGH UV doses, damage is irreparable -> p53 triggers apoptosis via caspases instead. This demonstrates p53's dual role: damage cop (low damage = arrest) and executioner (high damage = death).",mn:"Low damage = p53 arrests (p21). High damage = p53 kills (caspases)."},
// ============ GENETICS (12) ============
{id:"gen1",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics"],diff:1,q:"Two carriers (Aa x Aa) -- chance offspring is affected:",o:["25%","50%","75%","100%"],a:0,ex:"Punnett square: AA(25%), Aa(50%), aa(25%). Only aa is affected = 25%. Among UNAFFECTED offspring, 2/3 are carriers. Autosomal recessive examples: cystic fibrosis, sickle cell, PKU, Tay-Sachs. For X-linked recessive: carrier mother x normal father = 50% of sons affected, 0% daughters affected.",mn:"Aa x Aa = 1:2:1 ratio. 1/4 affected, 2/4 carriers, 1/4 normal."},
{id:"gen2",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Population Genetics","Hardy-Weinberg"],diff:2,q:"If q-squared = 0.0025, carrier frequency (2pq) is:",o:["~9.5%","5%","0.5%","25%"],a:0,ex:"q^2 = 0.0025 -> q = 0.05 -> p = 0.95 -> 2pq = 2(0.95)(0.05) = 0.095 = 9.5%. Key insight: carriers (9.5%) vastly outnumber affected (0.25%). HW assumptions: large population, random mating, no selection/mutation/migration.",mn:"Carriers (2pq) always >> affected (q^2)."},
{id:"gen3",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["X-Linked Inheritance"],diff:2,q:"X-linked recessive traits are expressed more in:",o:["Males (one X, no backup)","Females","Equal in both","Depends on environment"],a:0,ex:"Males are hemizygous for X-linked genes (XY). One affected X = trait expressed. Females need two affected X's (homozygous). Examples: hemophilia A/B, color blindness, Duchenne muscular dystrophy, G6PD deficiency. Affected father passes X to ALL daughters (carriers) but NEVER to sons (sons get Y).",mn:"Males: one X, no backup. All daughters of affected father are carriers."},
{id:"gen4",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Inheritance Patterns"],diff:3,q:"Codominance vs incomplete dominance:",o:["Codominance: both fully expressed. Incomplete: blended","Both mean the same thing","Codominance is blended","Incomplete means one masks other"],a:0,ex:"Codominance: BOTH alleles fully and separately expressed in heterozygote. Example: AB blood type (both A and B antigens present), sickle cell heterozygote (both HbA and HbS produced). Incomplete dominance: heterozygote shows INTERMEDIATE phenotype. Example: red x white = pink flowers. Key difference: codominance = both visible distinctly, incomplete = blend.",mn:"Codominance = both show (AB blood). Incomplete = blend (pink flowers)."},
{id:"gen5",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Chromosomal Abnormalities"],diff:2,q:"Meiosis I nondisjunction causes:",o:["All 4 gametes to have wrong chromosome number","Only 1 abnormal gamete","Normal cells","Polyploidy"],a:0,ex:"Meiosis I: homologs fail to separate, both go to one cell. After meiosis II: 2 gametes are n+1, 2 are n-1. ALL FOUR are abnormal. Meiosis II nondisjunction: sisters fail to separate, only 2 of 4 gametes abnormal. If n+1 gamete fertilized: trisomy (Down=21, Edwards=18, Patau=13). If n-1: monosomy (Turner=45,X).",mn:"Meiosis I nondisjunction = all 4 wrong. Meiosis II = only 2 of 4."},
{id:"gen6",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics"],diff:2,q:"A testcross involves crossing an unknown genotype with:",o:["A homozygous recessive (aa)","A homozygous dominant (AA)","Another heterozygote","A different species"],a:0,ex:"A testcross determines if an organism showing the dominant phenotype is AA or Aa. Cross with aa: if ALL offspring show dominant phenotype -> unknown is AA. If ~50% show recessive -> unknown is Aa. This works because aa can only contribute a recessive allele, so the offspring phenotype reveals the unknown parent's genotype.",mn:"Testcross = cross with aa to reveal unknown genotype."},
{id:"pgen1",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Population Genetics","Hardy-Weinberg"],diff:3,pass:"p5",q:"Disease allele frequency (q) is:",o:["0.05","0.0025","0.25","0.5"],a:0,ex:"25 affected / 10,000 = q^2 = 0.0025. q = sqrt(0.0025) = 0.05. This is the ALLELE frequency, not genotype frequency. Common mistake: confusing q^2 (genotype) with q (allele).",mn:"q^2 = affected proportion. q = square root."},
{id:"pgen2",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Population Genetics","Hardy-Weinberg"],diff:3,pass:"p5",q:"Carriers in this population:",o:["~950","~25","~500","~5000"],a:0,ex:"2pq = 2(0.95)(0.05) = 0.095. In 10,000 people: 950 carriers vs only 25 affected. For rare recessive diseases, the carrier pool is always much larger than the affected pool.",mn:"2pq x population = carriers. Always >> affected."},
// ============ ORGAN SYSTEMS (22) ============
{id:"bs1",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System"],diff:1,q:"SA node is located in the:",o:["Right atrium","Left atrium","Right ventricle","Left ventricle"],a:0,ex:"SA node = pacemaker (60-100 bpm) in right atrium wall. Pathway: SA -> AV node (delay for atrial emptying) -> Bundle of His -> bundle branches -> Purkinje fibers. Vagus nerve (parasympathetic) slows; sympathetic speeds up. AV node backup: 40-60 bpm.",mn:"SA = Start Atrium (right). Pacemaker."},
{id:"bs2",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Hormones"],diff:2,q:"ADH acts primarily on the:",o:["Collecting duct","PCT","Ascending loop","Glomerulus"],a:0,ex:"ADH (vasopressin) from posterior pituitary inserts aquaporin-2 channels into collecting duct apical membrane. With ADH: water reabsorbed = concentrated urine. Without ADH: dilute urine (diabetes insipidus). Alcohol inhibits ADH -> dehydration.",mn:"ADH = aquaporins in collecting duct = water retention"},
{id:"bs3",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Autonomic"],diff:2,q:"Sympathetic postganglionic neurons release:",o:["Norepinephrine","Acetylcholine","Dopamine","Serotonin"],a:0,ex:"ALL preganglionic (both divisions) = ACh at nicotinic receptors. Postganglionic: Sympathetic = NE at adrenergic receptors (except sweat glands = ACh). Parasympathetic = ACh at muscarinic receptors. Adrenal medulla releases epi (80%) + NE (20%) into blood. Key receptors: alpha-1 = vasoconstriction. Beta-1 = heart rate up. Beta-2 = bronchodilation.",mn:"Sympathetic post = NE (except sweat = ACh). Para = always ACh."},
{id:"bs4",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System","Hemoglobin"],diff:2,q:"Hemoglobin's O2 curve is:",o:["Sigmoidal","Hyperbolic","Linear","Exponential"],a:0,ex:"Hb: 4 subunits (alpha2-beta2), cooperative binding -> sigmoidal (S-shaped) curve. Myoglobin: 1 subunit, no cooperativity -> hyperbolic. Hb's sigmoidal shape allows efficient loading in lungs (high PO2) and efficient unloading in tissues (low PO2).",mn:"Hb = S-curve (cooperative). Mb = hyperbola (single subunit)."},
{id:"bs5",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System","Hemoglobin"],diff:3,q:"Right shift of Hb O2 curve is caused by:",o:["Increased CO2, H+, temp, and 2,3-BPG","Decreased CO2","Increased pH","Carbon monoxide"],a:0,ex:"Right shift = decreased O2 affinity = release O2 to active tissues. Caused by conditions in metabolizing tissues: increased CO2 (Bohr effect), decreased pH (H+), increased temperature, increased 2,3-BPG. Left shift (hold O2 tighter): opposite conditions, fetal Hb (HbF), CO poisoning.",mn:"CADET face Right: CO2, Acid, DPG, Exercise, Temperature"},
{id:"bs6",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Hormones"],diff:3,q:"Aldosterone's main effects:",o:["Increases Na+ reabsorption and K+ secretion","Directly increases water reabsorption","Decreases Na+","Increases glucose reabsorption"],a:0,ex:"Aldosterone (adrenal cortex) acts on DCT/collecting duct principal cells. Increases Na+/K+ ATPase and ENaC channels. Na+ reabsorbed, K+ and H+ secreted. Water follows Na+ passively. Part of RAAS: low BP -> renin -> angiotensin II -> aldosterone. Hyperaldosteronism = hypertension + hypokalemia + metabolic alkalosis.",mn:"Aldosterone: Na+ IN, K+ OUT, H+ OUT. Holds onto salt."},
{id:"bs7",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System"],diff:2,q:"T cells mature in the:",o:["Thymus","Bone marrow","Spleen","Lymph nodes"],a:0,ex:"T = Thymus (positive + negative selection for self-tolerance). B = Bone marrow. CD4+ = helper (activate others via cytokines). CD8+ = cytotoxic (kill infected/cancer cells). Treg = suppress immune response. Positive selection: must recognize self-MHC. Negative selection: must NOT react to self-antigens.",mn:"T = Thymus, B = Bone marrow."},
{id:"bs8",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System"],diff:2,q:"GFR is primarily regulated by:",o:["Afferent and efferent arteriolar tone","Blood pressure alone","ADH alone","Urine volume"],a:0,ex:"GFR controlled by adjusting afferent (arriving) and efferent (exiting) arteriole diameter. Dilate afferent OR constrict efferent -> increased GFR. RAAS: angiotensin II constricts efferent -> maintains GFR when BP low. NSAIDs block prostaglandins that dilate afferent -> can dangerously reduce GFR.",mn:"Afferent = Arriving. Efferent = Exiting. Constrict efferent = more GFR."},
{id:"bs9",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Action Potential"],diff:2,q:"During an action potential, depolarization is caused by:",o:["Na+ influx through voltage-gated Na+ channels","K+ efflux","Cl- influx","Ca2+ efflux"],a:0,ex:"Resting potential: ~-70mV (maintained by Na+/K+ ATPase and K+ leak channels). When threshold (-55mV) is reached: voltage-gated Na+ channels open -> Na+ rushes IN (down its electrochemical gradient) -> rapid depolarization to ~+30mV. Then Na+ channels inactivate and K+ channels open -> K+ flows OUT -> repolarization back to negative. Refractory period prevents backward signal propagation.",mn:"Depolarization = Na+ IN. Repolarization = K+ OUT."},
{id:"bs10",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Neurotransmitters"],diff:2,q:"The neurotransmitter at the neuromuscular junction is:",o:["Acetylcholine (ACh)","Norepinephrine","Dopamine","GABA"],a:0,ex:"Motor neurons release ACh at the NMJ, which binds nicotinic receptors on skeletal muscle -> Na+ influx -> muscle contraction. ACh is rapidly degraded by acetylcholinesterase (AChE) in the synaptic cleft. Clinical relevance: myasthenia gravis = autoimmune antibodies against nicotinic ACh receptors -> muscle weakness. Organophosphates inhibit AChE -> ACh accumulates -> overstimulation.",mn:"NMJ always = ACh at nicotinic receptors. Myasthenia gravis = Ab against these receptors."},
{id:"bs11",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones"],diff:2,q:"Thyroid hormone's primary effect:",o:["Increases basal metabolic rate","Decreases heart rate","Promotes fat storage","Suppresses growth"],a:0,ex:"Thyroid hormones (T3, T4) increase basal metabolic rate, O2 consumption, and heat production in nearly all tissues. T4 is the major circulating form; T3 is the active form (converted from T4 by deiodinases). Regulation: hypothalamus (TRH) -> anterior pituitary (TSH) -> thyroid (T3/T4) -> negative feedback on hypothalamus and pituitary. Hyper = Graves' disease. Hypo = Hashimoto's (autoimmune).",mn:"Thyroid = metabolism UP. T4 is storage form, T3 is active."},
{id:"bs12",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System"],diff:2,q:"MHC Class I presents antigens to:",o:["CD8+ cytotoxic T cells","CD4+ helper T cells","B cells","Natural killer cells directly"],a:0,ex:"MHC I is on ALL nucleated cells. It presents intracellular (endogenous) antigens -- pieces of proteins being made inside the cell. If the cell is infected or cancerous, abnormal peptides appear on MHC I, flagging CD8+ T cells to kill. MHC II is on antigen-presenting cells only (dendritic cells, macrophages, B cells). It presents extracellular (exogenous) antigens to CD4+ helper T cells.",mn:"MHC I = ALL cells -> CD8 (kill). MHC II = APCs only -> CD4 (help)."},
{id:"bs13",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Digestive System"],diff:2,q:"Pepsin is active in the:",o:["Stomach (acidic pH)","Small intestine (alkaline pH)","Mouth","Large intestine"],a:0,ex:"Pepsin is a protease active at pH ~2 (the acidic stomach environment). It is secreted as inactive pepsinogen by chief cells, then activated by HCl (from parietal cells). In the small intestine, the pH is ~7-8 (neutralized by pancreatic bicarbonate), which inactivates pepsin. Pancreatic proteases (trypsin, chymotrypsin) take over protein digestion in the duodenum.",mn:"Pepsin = stomach (pH 2). Trypsin/chymotrypsin = small intestine (pH 7-8)."},
{id:"bs14",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones"],diff:3,q:"Anterior pituitary hormones include:",o:["GH, TSH, ACTH, FSH, LH, Prolactin","ADH and oxytocin","Epinephrine","Insulin"],a:0,ex:"FLAT PiG mnemonic: FSH, LH, ACTH, TSH, Prolactin, (i=ignore) GH. These are made IN the anterior pituitary. The posterior pituitary does NOT make hormones -- it only stores and releases ADH and oxytocin (made in hypothalamus). Key distinction: anterior = glandular tissue that synthesizes. Posterior = neural tissue that stores.",mn:"Anterior: FLAT PiG (FSH,LH,ACTH,TSH,Prolactin,GH). Posterior: ADH + Oxytocin."},
{id:"pbs1",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hematology","Immune System"],diff:3,pass:"p2",q:"Most likely diagnosis:",o:["Autoimmune hemolytic anemia","Iron deficiency anemia","Sickle cell disease","Aplastic anemia"],a:0,ex:"Positive Coombs = antibodies on RBCs (autoimmune). Spherocytes = partial phagocytosis by macrophages. Low haptoglobin = depleted by binding free hemoglobin from lysed RBCs. High LDH = released from cell destruction. High reticulocytes = marrow compensating. Iron deficiency would show microcytic cells. Aplastic = LOW reticulocytes.",mn:"+ Coombs + spherocytes + low haptoglobin + high LDH = autoimmune hemolysis"},
{id:"pbs2",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Action Potential"],diff:3,pass:"p6",q:"TTX at a node of Ranvier would:",o:["Block action potential at that node","Block K+ efflux","Cause continuous depolarization","Have no effect"],a:0,ex:"TTX blocks voltage-gated Na+ channels. Without Na+ influx, depolarization cannot occur at that node. In myelinated neurons, action potentials jump node to node (saltatory conduction). Blocking one node impairs or stops signal propagation beyond that point.",mn:"TTX blocks Na+ channels = no depolarization at that node."},
{id:"pbs3",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Action Potential"],diff:3,pass:"p6",q:"TEA blocking K+ channels would:",o:["Prolong the action potential (delay repolarization)","Prevent depolarization","Cause immediate hyperpolarization","Have no effect"],a:0,ex:"K+ efflux drives repolarization. TEA blocks K+ channels, trapping K+ inside, delaying return to resting potential. The AP duration is prolonged. The neuron can still fire (Na+ channels work) but takes longer to reset, potentially decreasing maximum firing frequency.",mn:"TEA blocks K+ = slow repolarization = longer AP."},
{id:"bs15",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System"],diff:1,q:"Blood flow order through the heart:",o:["Vena cava -> RA -> RV -> lungs -> LA -> LV -> aorta","Aorta -> RA -> RV -> lungs","LA -> RA -> lungs -> LV","Pulmonary vein -> RV -> lungs"],a:0,ex:"Deoxygenated blood returns via superior/inferior vena cava to RIGHT atrium -> tricuspid valve -> RIGHT ventricle -> pulmonary valve -> pulmonary arteries -> LUNGS (gas exchange) -> pulmonary veins -> LEFT atrium -> mitral (bicuspid) valve -> LEFT ventricle -> aortic valve -> aorta -> body. Remember: right side = deoxygenated to lungs. Left side = oxygenated to body. Left ventricle has thickest wall (pumps to entire body).",mn:"Right = to lungs. Left = to body. Tri before you Bi (tricuspid before bicuspid)."},
// ============ MOLECULAR BIO (12) ============
{id:"mb1",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication"],diff:1,q:"Helicase's role:",o:["Unwinds DNA double helix","Relieves supercoiling","Makes RNA primers","Synthesizes new DNA"],a:0,ex:"Replication fork team: Helicase breaks H-bonds to unwind. Topoisomerase relieves supercoiling ahead. SSBs stabilize single strands. Primase makes RNA primers. DNA Pol III (pro) or delta/epsilon (eu) synthesizes 5' to 3'.",mn:"Helicase = Helix-ase. Topoisomerase = prevents tangling."},
{id:"mb2",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication"],diff:2,q:"Okazaki fragments are on the:",o:["Lagging strand","Leading strand","Both equally","mRNA"],a:0,ex:"DNA pol only synthesizes 5' to 3'. Leading strand = continuous (toward fork, one primer). Lagging strand = discontinuous fragments (away from fork, each needs own primer). DNA Pol I removes primers and fills gaps. DNA ligase seals nicks between fragments.",mn:"Lagging = lots of fragments. Ligase = glue."},
{id:"mb3",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication"],diff:1,q:"DNA polymerase synthesizes in which direction?",o:["5' to 3' only","3' to 5' only","Both","Random"],a:0,ex:"ALL DNA polymerases build 5' to 3' only (add nucleotides to free 3'-OH). Read template 3' to 5'. Proofreading: 3' to 5' exonuclease removes mismatches. Error rate ~1/10^9. RNA polymerase also synthesizes 5' to 3' but needs no primer.",mn:"Always 5' to 3'. No exceptions ever."},
{id:"mb4",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Mutations"],diff:3,q:"A nonsense mutation produces:",o:["Premature stop codon -> truncated protein","Different amino acid","Reading frame shift","No change"],a:0,ex:"Point mutations: Silent = same AA (wobble position). Missense = different AA (sickle cell: Glu -> Val). Nonsense = STOP codon (UAA/UAG/UGA) -> truncated protein. Frameshift = insertion/deletion (not x3) -> everything downstream scrambled.",mn:"Nonsense = premature STOP. Missense = wrong AA. Silent = no effect."},
{id:"mb5",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Lac operon is fully induced when:",o:["Lactose present AND glucose absent","Glucose present","ATP is high","Tryptophan is abundant"],a:0,ex:"Two signals needed: (1) Lactose -> allolactose removes repressor from operator. (2) Low glucose -> high cAMP -> CAP activates transcription. Both = full expression. With glucose present (even with lactose), cAMP is low, CAP inactive, only basal transcription. Glucose always wins.",mn:"Lactose ON + Glucose OFF = full induction. Glucose always preferred."},
{id:"mb6",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Tumor Suppressors","Cell Cycle"],diff:3,q:"p53 responds to DNA damage by:",o:["Arresting cell cycle and/or triggering apoptosis","Promoting division","Activating telomerase","Increasing mutations"],a:0,ex:"p53 = guardian of genome. DNA damage -> p53 stabilized -> activates p21 (CDK inhibitor) -> G1/S arrest for repair. If irreparable: activates BAX/PUMA -> apoptosis via intrinsic pathway. Mutated in >50% of all cancers. Two-hit hypothesis: both alleles must be lost.",mn:"p53: damage -> STOP -> repair or self-destruct."},
{id:"mb7",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation"],diff:2,q:"Prokaryotic vs eukaryotic ribosomes:",o:["70S vs 80S","80S vs 70S","Both 80S","Both 70S"],a:0,ex:"Pro = 70S (30S + 50S). Eu = 80S (40S + 60S). Svedberg units are NOT additive. Many antibiotics target 70S: chloramphenicol/macrolides (50S subunit), tetracyclines/aminoglycosides (30S). Mitochondrial ribosomes are 70S (endosymbiotic theory).",mn:"Pro = 70S, Eu = 80S. Antibiotics target 70S."},
{id:"mb8",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation"],diff:2,q:"The 5' cap on eukaryotic mRNA is:",o:["7-methylguanosine","Poly-A tail","An intron","Methyl-cytosine"],a:0,ex:"Eukaryotic mRNA undergoes 3 processing steps: (1) 5' cap = 7-methylguanosine via unusual 5'-5' linkage. Functions: protects from exonuclease, aids ribosome recognition, assists nuclear export. (2) 3' poly-A tail = ~200 adenines. Functions: stability, export. (3) Splicing = spliceosome (snRNPs) removes introns, joins exons.",mn:"Cap = helmet (5'). Poly-A = cushion (3'). Both protect and aid export."},
{id:"mb9",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication"],diff:3,q:"Telomerase prevents:",o:["Chromosome shortening during replication","Mismatch errors","DNA unwinding","Methylation"],a:0,ex:"End replication problem: DNA pol needs a primer, so after primer removal at chromosome ends, a gap remains -> chromosomes shorten 50-200bp per division. Telomeres (TTAGGG repeats) buffer this. Telomerase is a reverse transcriptase (has own RNA template) that extends telomeres. Active in stem cells, germ cells, ~90% cancers. Somatic cells: low/no telomerase -> Hayflick limit (~50 divisions).",mn:"Telomerase = reverse transcriptase extending chromosome ends."},
{id:"pmb2",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Acid-Base"],diff:3,pass:"p3",q:"The enzyme's ability to function at pH 2-10 is unusual because most enzymes:",o:["Denature outside a narrow pH range","Function equally at all pH values","Require pH above 10","Only work in acidic conditions"],a:0,ex:"Most enzymes have a narrow optimal pH range (usually 6-8 for cytoplasmic enzymes). Outside this range, ionizable groups in the active site change protonation state, disrupting catalysis, and extreme pH can denature the protein. The passage describes an extremophilic enzyme that maintains activity across pH 2-10, which is remarkable. Extremophiles (organisms in extreme environments) have evolved proteins with unusual stability -- their enzymes are of biotechnological interest for industrial processes that require extreme conditions.",mn:"Most enzymes work in narrow pH range. Extremophilic enzymes are unusually stable."},
// ============ GEN CHEM (14) ============
{id:"gc1",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Buffers","Acid-Base"],diff:1,q:"A buffer works best at pH within +/-1 of its:",o:["pKa","7.0","pKb","14"],a:0,ex:"Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]). Maximum buffering when [A-] = [HA] (ratio = 1, log = 0), which occurs at pH = pKa. Outside +/-1, one form depleted -> poor buffering. To buffer at a target pH, choose a weak acid with pKa near that pH.",mn:"Buffer = best at pKa +/- 1. At pKa, ratio is 1:1."},
{id:"gc2",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"Spontaneous at ALL temperatures:",o:["Exothermic (H<0) and entropy increase (S>0)","H>0 and S>0","H<0 and S<0","H>0 and S<0"],a:0,ex:"delta-G = delta-H - T*delta-S. Both terms push G negative at all T when H<0 and S>0. Four combos: H-/S+ = always spontaneous. H+/S- = never. H-/S- = low T only. H+/S+ = high T only.",mn:"Exothermic + more disorder = always spontaneous"},
{id:"gc3",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Equilibrium"],diff:1,q:"Adding product to a system at equilibrium:",o:["Shifts toward reactants","Makes more product","No effect","Increases Keq"],a:0,ex:"Le Chatelier: system shifts to reduce stress. Adding product -> shifts LEFT. Only TEMPERATURE changes Keq. Concentration and pressure changes shift position but not Keq itself. For exothermic: heat is a product, so increasing T decreases Keq.",mn:"System runs away from what you add. Only T changes Keq."},
{id:"gc4",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Redox Chemistry"],diff:1,q:"Oxidation is:",o:["Loss of electrons","Gain of electrons","Loss of protons","Gain of protons"],a:0,ex:"OIL RIG: Oxidation Is Loss, Reduction Is Gain. The oxidizing agent gets reduced (accepts electrons). The reducing agent gets oxidized (donates electrons). In biology: NAD+ (oxidizing agent) + 2e- + H+ -> NADH (reducing agent).",mn:"OIL RIG. The oxidizing agent itself gets reduced."},
{id:"gc5",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"pH of 1x10^-3 M HCl:",o:["3","11","-3","0.001"],a:0,ex:"HCl is a strong acid = complete dissociation. [H+] = 10^-3. pH = -log(10^-3) = 3. Strong acids: HCl, HBr, HI, HNO3, H2SO4, HClO3, HClO4. For non-powers of 10: pH is between flanking integers.",mn:"Strong acid: pH = -log[acid] directly."},
{id:"gc6",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry"],diff:3,q:"Positive E-cell means:",o:["Spontaneous (delta-G < 0)","Non-spontaneous","Needs external voltage","delta-G > 0"],a:0,ex:"delta-G = -nFE. Positive E -> negative delta-G -> spontaneous = galvanic/voltaic cell. E-cell = E(cathode) - E(anode). Species with more positive reduction potential is reduced (cathode). Negative E-cell -> electrolytic cell (requires external power).",mn:"+E = -delta-G = spontaneous = galvanic cell"},
{id:"gc7",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Chemical Kinetics"],diff:3,q:"First-order half-life:",o:["Constant: t1/2 = 0.693/k","Doubles with [A]","Depends on initial [A]","Zero"],a:0,ex:"For first order: t1/2 = ln2/k = 0.693/k. CONSTANT regardless of starting concentration. Also governs radioactive decay and most drug elimination. Zero-order: t1/2 = [A]0/2k (depends on [A]). Second-order: t1/2 = 1/(k[A]0).",mn:"First order: t1/2 = 0.693/k. Constant like radioactive decay."},
{id:"gc8",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Intermolecular Forces"],diff:2,q:"Strongest to weakest IMFs:",o:["Ion-dipole > H-bond > dipole-dipole > London","London > H-bond > ion-dipole","All equal","H-bond > ion-ion"],a:0,ex:"Ion-ion (NaCl lattice) > ion-dipole (Na+ in water) > H-bonding (needs H on N/O/F) > dipole-dipole > London dispersion (all molecules, increases with MW/surface area). H-bonding explains water's high BP, specific heat, and surface tension.",mn:"Ion-dipole > H-bond > dipole-dipole > London"},
{id:"gc9",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Solutions"],diff:2,q:"Adding a nonvolatile solute to water:",o:["Raises boiling point and lowers freezing point","Lowers boiling point","Raises freezing point","Has no effect on BP or FP"],a:0,ex:"Colligative properties depend on NUMBER of solute particles, not identity: boiling point elevation (delta-Tb = iKb*m), freezing point depression (delta-Tf = iKf*m), osmotic pressure, vapor pressure lowering (Raoult's law). The van't Hoff factor i accounts for dissociation: NaCl i=2, glucose i=1, CaCl2 i=3. More particles = greater effect.",mn:"Solute raises BP, lowers FP. More particles = bigger effect (i factor)."},
{id:"gc10",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"A polyprotic acid like H2SO4:",o:["Donates protons in sequential steps, each with its own Ka","Donates all protons simultaneously","Has only one Ka","Cannot act as a buffer"],a:0,ex:"Polyprotic acids donate protons one at a time. Each step has its own Ka, and Ka1 >> Ka2 >> Ka3 because removing each subsequent proton from an increasingly negative species is harder. H2SO4: first proton is strong acid (complete), second is weak (Ka2 = 0.012). H3PO4: three Ka values. Each dissociation step creates its own buffer region on the titration curve.",mn:"Ka1 >> Ka2 >> Ka3. Each proton is harder to remove than the last."},
{id:"gc11",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Atomic Structure"],diff:2,q:"An element's atomic number equals its number of:",o:["Protons","Neutrons","Electrons in an ion","Mass number"],a:0,ex:"Atomic number (Z) = number of protons = defines the element. Mass number (A) = protons + neutrons. Isotopes = same element (same Z) but different number of neutrons (different A). In a neutral atom: protons = electrons. In ions: protons stay the same, electrons change. Example: Carbon-12 has Z=6 (6 protons), A=12 (6 neutrons).",mn:"Atomic number = protons = element identity. Mass number = protons + neutrons."},
// ============ ORGO (10) ============
{id:"org1",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions"],diff:2,q:"SN1 is favored by:",o:["3-degree substrate, weak nucleophile, polar protic","1-degree, strong nucleophile","2-degree, polar aprotic","Methyl, strong base"],a:0,ex:"SN1 needs a stable carbocation intermediate: 3 > 2 >> never methyl/1. Weak nucleophile (strong would push SN2). Polar protic solvent stabilizes the carbocation. Rate = k[substrate] only. Stereochemistry: racemization (planar carbocation attacked from both sides).",mn:"SN1: 3-degree, weak nuc, protic = racemic"},
{id:"org2",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions"],diff:1,q:"SN2 stereochemistry:",o:["Walden inversion","Retention","Racemization","No change"],a:0,ex:"SN2: single concerted step. Nucleophile attacks 180 degrees from leaving group (backside attack). Forces umbrella-like inversion: R -> S. Favored: methyl > 1 > 2 (never 3). Strong nucleophile, polar aprotic solvent. Rate = k[sub][nuc].",mn:"SN2 = backside attack = always inverts."},
{id:"org3",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Elimination Reactions"],diff:2,q:"Bulky base + 2-degree substrate most likely gives:",o:["E2 elimination","SN2","SN1","E1"],a:0,ex:"Base too bulky for backside attack (SN2 blocked). Instead abstracts a beta-proton. E2: concerted, anti-periplanar geometry required, Zaitsev product (more substituted alkene, unless very bulky base -> Hofmann product).",mn:"Too bulky to SN2 -> grabs a proton = E2"},
{id:"org4",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Addition Reactions"],diff:2,q:"Markovnikov's rule: H adds to carbon with:",o:["More existing H atoms","Fewer H atoms","More substituents","The leaving group"],a:0,ex:"In HX addition across a double bond, H goes to the less substituted carbon (more H's already there), placing X on the more substituted carbon. This gives the more stable carbocation intermediate. Exception: HBr + peroxides = anti-Markovnikov (radical mechanism).",mn:"Rich get richer. H goes where H's already are."},
{id:"org5",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Stereochemistry"],diff:1,q:"Enantiomers differ at:",o:["ALL stereocenters (R<->S)","One stereocenter","Connectivity","Formula"],a:0,ex:"Enantiomers = non-superimposable mirror images. All R's become S's and vice versa. Same physical properties (MP, BP, solubility, Rf) EXCEPT: (1) optical rotation (equal and opposite), (2) interactions with other chiral molecules (drug-receptor binding). Racemic mixture = 50:50, zero net rotation.",mn:"Enantiomers = mirror images. Same everything except optical rotation."},
{id:"org6",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Carbonyl Chemistry"],diff:3,q:"LiAlH4 vs NaBH4:",o:["LiAlH4 reduces everything; NaBH4 only aldehydes/ketones","Both reduce everything","NaBH4 is stronger","They are identical"],a:0,ex:"LiAlH4 = powerful, non-selective: reduces COOH -> 1-OH, esters -> 2 alcohols, amides -> amines, plus aldehydes/ketones. NaBH4 = mild, selective: ONLY reduces aldehydes and ketones to alcohols. PCC = OXIDIZER (1-OH -> aldehyde, stops there). H2/Pd = catalytic hydrogenation (reduces C=C).",mn:"LiAlH4 = sledgehammer. NaBH4 = gentle. PCC = oxidizer."},
{id:"org7",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups"],diff:1,q:"An aldehyde differs from a ketone because:",o:["Aldehyde has C=O bonded to at least one H","Ketone has C=O bonded to at least one H","They are identical","Aldehyde has C-O single bond"],a:0,ex:"Both are carbonyl compounds (C=O). Aldehyde: carbonyl C bonded to at least one H (R-CHO) -- found at the END of a carbon chain. Ketone: carbonyl C bonded to TWO carbons (R-CO-R') -- found in the MIDDLE of a chain. Aldehydes are more reactive than ketones (less steric hindrance, more electrophilic). Aldehydes can be oxidized to carboxylic acids; ketones cannot be easily oxidized.",mn:"Aldehyde = end of chain (has H). Ketone = middle (no H on C=O)."},
{id:"org8",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"Carboxylic acids are acidic because:",o:["The conjugate base is resonance-stabilized","The O-H bond is very strong","They have no resonance","They are strong acids"],a:0,ex:"When a carboxylic acid (R-COOH) donates a proton, the resulting carboxylate ion (R-COO-) has resonance stabilization: the negative charge is delocalized equally across both oxygen atoms. This stabilization of the conjugate base makes the acid more willing to donate its proton. Carboxylic acids are WEAK acids (pKa ~4-5), not strong. They are more acidic than alcohols (pKa ~16) because alcohol conjugate bases (alkoxide, R-O-) have no resonance stabilization.",mn:"COOH -> COO- with resonance = stable conjugate base = more acidic than alcohols."},
// ============ PHYSICS (12) ============
{id:"ph1",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Bernoulli's Principle"],diff:2,q:"Bernoulli: increasing fluid velocity causes:",o:["Decreased pressure","Increased pressure","No effect","Increased density"],a:0,ex:"P + 1/2*rho*v^2 + rho*g*h = constant. If v increases (narrow pipe), P must decrease. Applications: airplane wing lift, Venturi effect, vascular stenosis. This is conservation of energy for fluids.",mn:"Fast flow = low pressure. Think airplane wings."},
{id:"ph2",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Electrostatics"],diff:1,q:"Doubling distance between charges changes force to:",o:["1/4 original","1/2 original","Same","Double"],a:0,ex:"Coulomb: F = kq1q2/r^2. Inverse square: 2r -> F/4, 3r -> F/9. Same relationship for: gravity, E-field, light intensity, sound intensity.",mn:"Inverse square: 2x distance = 1/4 force"},
{id:"ph3",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Work and Energy"],diff:1,q:"Work = 0 when force is:",o:["Perpendicular to displacement","Parallel","Antiparallel","At 45 degrees"],a:0,ex:"W = Fd*cos(theta). At 90 degrees: cos90 = 0 -> W = 0. Examples: normal force, centripetal force, gravity on horizontal motion. Parallel = max work. Antiparallel = negative work (friction).",mn:"Perpendicular = zero work. Parallel = max."},
{id:"ph4",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Waves and Sound"],diff:1,q:"Sound travels fastest through:",o:["Solids","Liquids","Gases","Vacuum"],a:0,ex:"Sound = mechanical wave, needs a medium (no vacuum). Speed: solids (~5000 m/s) > liquids (~1500) > gases (~340). In gases: v proportional to sqrt(T/M). Opposite of EM waves (fastest in vacuum).",mn:"Sound: solid > liquid > gas. Cannot travel in vacuum."},
{id:"ph5",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Circuits"],diff:2,q:"Resistors in series vs parallel:",o:["Series: R adds. Parallel: total < smallest","Parallel: R adds","Both add","Series: total < smallest"],a:0,ex:"Series: same current, R_total = R1+R2 (total > each). Parallel: same voltage, 1/R_total = 1/R1+1/R2 (total < smallest). Two equal resistors in parallel: R_total = R/2.",mn:"Series: R adds up. Parallel: 1/R adds (total is less)."},
{id:"ph6",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Waves and Sound"],diff:2,q:"Source approaching observer: frequency is:",o:["Higher (compressed waves)","Lower","Same","Zero"],a:0,ex:"Doppler effect: approaching = compressed wavefronts = shorter wavelength = higher frequency. Receding = stretched = lower frequency. Applies to sound (ambulance siren), light (blueshift/redshift), ultrasound (echocardiography).",mn:"Approaching = higher pitch. Receding = lower."},
{id:"ph7",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics"],diff:2,q:"Thin lens equation:",o:["1/f = 1/do + 1/di","f = do + di","f = do x di","1/f = 1/do - 1/di"],a:0,ex:"Works for lenses and mirrors. Converging (convex) lens: f > 0. Diverging (concave) lens: f < 0. Real image: di > 0. Virtual: di < 0. Magnification: m = -di/do. Power (diopters) = 1/f(meters). Two lenses in contact: 1/f_total = 1/f1 + 1/f2.",mn:"1/f = 1/do + 1/di. Memorize sign conventions."},
{id:"ph8",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics"],diff:2,q:"Total internal reflection requires light going from:",o:["High n to low n (beyond critical angle)","Low n to high n","Same n to same n","Any direction"],a:0,ex:"TIR requires: (1) light from higher refractive index to lower (glass -> air, water -> air), AND (2) angle of incidence > critical angle (theta_c = arcsin(n2/n1)). Below critical angle: refraction + reflection. At critical angle: refracted ray at 90 degrees. Above: ALL light reflected. Applications: fiber optics, diamond brilliance (high n = low critical angle = lots of TIR).",mn:"High-to-low n + exceed critical angle = total reflection."},
{id:"ph9",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Nuclear Physics"],diff:2,q:"Beta-minus decay emits:",o:["An electron and antineutrino","A positron","An alpha particle","A gamma ray only"],a:0,ex:"Radioactive decay types: Alpha = helium nucleus (2p+2n, mass -4, Z -2). Beta-minus = neutron -> proton + electron + antineutrino (Z +1, mass same). Beta-plus = proton -> neutron + positron + neutrino (Z -1). Gamma = high-energy photon, no mass/charge change. Electron capture = inner electron captured by nucleus.",mn:"Beta-minus: n -> p + electron. Z goes UP by 1."},
{id:"ph10",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Circuits"],diff:3,q:"Capacitors in series vs parallel:",o:["Series: 1/C adds (less total). Parallel: C adds (more)","Series: C adds. Parallel: 1/C adds","Both add directly","Both use 1/C"],a:0,ex:"Capacitors follow OPPOSITE rules from resistors: Series: 1/C_total = 1/C1 + 1/C2 (total < smallest). Parallel: C_total = C1 + C2 (total = sum). C = epsilon*A/d: bigger plates or smaller gap = more capacitance. Inserting dielectric increases C by factor kappa.",mn:"Capacitors = opposite of resistors. Series: less. Parallel: more."},
// ============ PSYCH/SOC (25) ============
{id:"ps1",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology"],diff:1,q:"Object permanence develops during Piaget's:",o:["Sensorimotor (0-2)","Preoperational (2-7)","Concrete operational (7-11)","Formal operational (12+)"],a:0,ex:"Piaget's stages: Sensorimotor (0-2): senses + motor, object permanence ~8mo. Preoperational (2-7): symbolic thinking but egocentric, no conservation. Concrete operational (7-11): logic about concrete things, conservation mastered. Formal operational (12+): abstract/hypothetical thinking.",mn:"Sensorimotor = senses + object permanence"},
{id:"ps2",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:1,q:"Bystander effect is explained by:",o:["Diffusion of responsibility","Social facilitation","Groupthink","Deindividuation"],a:0,ex:"More bystanders = less individual responsibility. Also: pluralistic ignorance (everyone looks calm = must be fine) and evaluation apprehension (fear of embarrassment). Fix: single out one person for action. Kitty Genovese case inspired this research.",mn:"More watchers = less help. Single someone out to fix it."},
{id:"ps3",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Emotion Theories"],diff:2,q:"Schachter-Singer two-factor theory:",o:["Arousal + cognitive label = emotion","Body then emotion","Simultaneous and independent","Facial expression determines emotion"],a:0,ex:"Three theories: James-Lange (body -> emotion). Cannon-Bard (simultaneous). Schachter-Singer (arousal + cognitive labeling based on context = emotion). Same arousal can become different emotions depending on interpretation. Bridge study: fear arousal mislabeled as attraction.",mn:"Two factors: body buzz + brain's contextual interpretation"},
{id:"ps4",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,q:"Negative reinforcement means:",o:["Remove aversive stimulus -> behavior increases","Add punishment -> behavior decreases","Remove reward -> behavior decreases","Ignore behavior"],a:0,ex:"Four quadrants: Positive reinforcement (add pleasant -> increase). Negative reinforcement (remove unpleasant -> increase). Positive punishment (add unpleasant -> decrease). Negative punishment (remove pleasant -> decrease). Key: positive = add, negative = remove, reinforcement = increase, punishment = decrease.",mn:"Negative = REMOVE. Reinforcement = INCREASE behavior."},
{id:"ps5",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Brain Anatomy"],diff:2,q:"Damage to Broca's area causes:",o:["Inability to produce fluent speech","Inability to understand language","Visual field deficits","Memory loss"],a:0,ex:"Broca's (left inferior frontal) = speech PRODUCTION. Damage = non-fluent/expressive aphasia: understands but can't produce fluent speech (halting, telegraphic). Wernicke's (left superior temporal) = COMPREHENSION. Damage = fluent/receptive aphasia: produces fluent but meaningless 'word salad,' cannot understand.",mn:"Broca = Broken speech. Wernicke = Wordy nonsense."},
{id:"ps6",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Fundamental attribution error:",o:["Over-attribute others' behavior to personality","Over-attribute own behavior to situation","Blame victims","Believe world is just"],a:0,ex:"FAE: for OTHERS, we overemphasize disposition (personality) and underestimate situation. 'They failed because they are lazy.' For OURSELVES: we blame the situation (actor-observer bias). Self-serving bias: my success = me, my failure = circumstances.",mn:"Others = personality. Me = circumstances."},
{id:"ps7",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception"],diff:2,q:"Weber's Law states:",o:["JND is proportional to stimulus intensity","All stimuli perceived equally","Thresholds are fixed","Adaptation eliminates sensation"],a:0,ex:"Delta-I/I = constant. The just noticeable difference (JND) is a constant PROPORTION, not absolute amount. If you notice 2g added to 100g (2%), you need 4g added to 200g to notice (still 2%). This is why a $1 increase feels big on a $5 item but trivial on a $500 item.",mn:"Weber: percent change matters, not absolute."},
{id:"ps8",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Cognitive dissonance is:",o:["Discomfort from contradictory beliefs/actions","Group conformity pressure","Memory distortion","Attitude reinforcement"],a:0,ex:"Festinger: holding contradictory cognitions (e.g., 'smoking is bad' + 'I smoke') creates discomfort. Resolved by: changing behavior (quit), changing belief ('not that dangerous'), or adding justification ('I'll quit later'). Classic $1 vs $20 experiment: less payment = more dissonance = more attitude change.",mn:"Conflicting thoughts = discomfort -> change something to resolve"},
{id:"ps9",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Health Disparities"],diff:2,q:"Social determinants of health include:",o:["Income, education, neighborhood, access to care","Genetics only","Diet only","Exercise only"],a:0,ex:"SDOH explain MORE variance in health outcomes than individual behaviors or genetics. Categories: economic stability, education, social/community context, healthcare access, neighborhood/environment. Heavily tested on MCAT Psych/Soc section. Connected to health disparities, institutional racism, medical ethics.",mn:"Where you live and your resources matter more than individual choices."},
{id:"ps10",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Motivation"],diff:2,q:"Base of Maslow's hierarchy:",o:["Physiological needs","Safety","Love/belonging","Self-actualization"],a:0,ex:"Bottom to top: Physiological (food, water, sleep) -> Safety -> Love/belonging -> Esteem -> Self-actualization. Lower needs must be substantially met before higher needs motivate. Criticism: too rigid, Western-centric, hard to test.",mn:"Survival first, self-actualization last."},
{id:"ps11",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Asch conformity experiments showed:",o:["~75% conformed at least once to wrong group answer","Nobody ever conforms","Conformity needs authority figure","Group size is irrelevant"],a:0,ex:"Asch: participants judged line lengths with confederates giving wrong answers. ~75% conformed at least once. Average rate ~37%. One dissenter reduced conformity from 37% to ~5%. Unanimity matters more than group size. This is normative social influence (desire to fit in).",mn:"75% conformed once. ONE ally breaks it."},
{id:"ps12",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception"],diff:2,q:"Sensory adaptation is:",o:["Decreased response to constant stimulus","Increased sensitivity","Learning new stimuli","Cross-modal transfer"],a:0,ex:"Receptors reduce firing rate for constant stimuli. Examples: stop feeling clothes, stop smelling your house. Different from habituation (behavioral/CNS, not receptor level). Exception: pain receptors (nociceptors) show minimal adaptation -- pain signals danger.",mn:"Constant stimulus -> stop noticing. Pain is the exception."},
{id:"ps13",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Learning and Conditioning"],diff:1,q:"Classical conditioning was discovered by:",o:["Pavlov","Skinner","Bandura","Watson"],a:0,ex:"Pavlov: bell (NS->CS) paired with food (UCS) -> bell alone triggers salivation (CR). Watson: applied to human fear (Little Albert). Skinner: operant conditioning (consequences shape behavior). Bandura: observational learning (Bobo doll -- children imitate witnessed aggression).",mn:"Pavlov = bell, dog, drool. Watson = fear in humans."},
{id:"ps14",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Erikson's adolescent crisis:",o:["Identity vs Role Confusion","Intimacy vs Isolation","Initiative vs Guilt","Trust vs Mistrust"],a:0,ex:"Eight stages: Trust/Mistrust (0-1), Autonomy/Shame (1-3), Initiative/Guilt (3-6), Industry/Inferiority (6-12), Identity/Role Confusion (12-18), Intimacy/Isolation (18-40), Generativity/Stagnation (40-65), Integrity/Despair (65+).",mn:"Teens = identity. Young adults = intimacy."},
{id:"ps15",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory"],diff:2,q:"Working memory capacity is approximately:",o:["7 +/- 2 items","Unlimited","2 items","50 items"],a:0,ex:"Miller's Law: working memory holds about 7 (+/-2) items at once. Chunking can increase effective capacity (remembering 10 digits as a phone number pattern). Working memory is a component of short-term memory that actively manipulates information. Encoding into long-term memory requires rehearsal, elaboration, or emotional significance.",mn:"7 +/- 2. Chunking helps. Working memory actively processes."},
{id:"ps16",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory"],diff:2,q:"The three stages of memory:",o:["Encoding, storage, retrieval","Input, processing, output","Sensory, emotional, logical","Learning, forgetting, relearning"],a:0,ex:"Encoding = converting information into a form the brain can store. Storage = maintaining encoded information over time (sensory -> short-term -> long-term). Retrieval = accessing stored information when needed. Failures can occur at any stage: encoding failure (never properly stored), storage decay (fades over time), retrieval failure (information exists but cannot be accessed -- tip-of-tongue phenomenon).",mn:"Encode -> Store -> Retrieve. Failure at any stage = forgetting."},
{id:"ps17",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sleep"],diff:2,q:"REM sleep is characterized by:",o:["Rapid eye movement, dreaming, muscle atonia","Deep slow waves","Sleepwalking","No brain activity"],a:0,ex:"Sleep cycles ~90 min. NREM stages: N1 (light, theta), N2 (sleep spindles, K-complexes), N3 (deep/slow-wave, delta waves -- most restorative). REM: rapid eye movements, vivid dreaming, muscle paralysis (atonia -- prevents acting out dreams), EEG resembles waking. REM increases across the night. Sleep deprivation REM rebound. Memory consolidation occurs in both N3 (declarative) and REM (procedural).",mn:"REM = dreaming + paralysis + brain active. N3 = deep + restorative."},
{id:"ps18",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology"],diff:2,q:"Symbolic interactionism focuses on:",o:["Meaning created through social interactions","Large-scale social structures","Biological determinism","Unconscious drives"],a:0,ex:"Three sociological perspectives: Functionalism (Durkheim): society's parts work together for stability. Conflict theory (Marx): power struggles and inequality between groups. Symbolic interactionism (Mead, Cooley): micro-level -- people create meaning through daily interactions and shared symbols (language, gestures). Cooley's looking-glass self: our self-concept is shaped by how we think others see us.",mn:"Symbolic interactionism = micro-level + meaning from interactions"},
{id:"ps19",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Moral Development"],diff:2,q:"Kohlberg's post-conventional morality:",o:["Universal ethical principles above law","Following rules for social order","Self-interest","Avoiding punishment"],a:0,ex:"Pre-conventional (1-2): self-interest, avoid punishment. Conventional (3-4): conform to norms, maintain social order. Post-conventional (5-6): social contract (laws serve people, can change), universal principles (conscience above law -- civil disobedience). Most adults stay at conventional level.",mn:"Pre = selfish. Conventional = conformist. Post = principled."},
{id:"ps20",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Groupthink occurs when:",o:["Group prioritizes harmony over critical analysis","Individuals act alone","A leader makes all decisions","Members openly disagree"],a:0,ex:"Janis: cohesive groups suppress dissent to maintain agreement, leading to poor decisions. Examples: Bay of Pigs, Challenger disaster. Signs: illusion of invulnerability, self-censorship, illusion of unanimity. Prevention: devil's advocate role, outside experts, anonymous feedback.",mn:"Harmony over critical thinking = bad decisions"},
{id:"pps1",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:3,pass:"p7",q:"This experiment resembles:",o:["Asch conformity experiments","Milgram obedience","Stanford prison experiment","Bobo doll study"],a:0,ex:"Key feature: confederates give wrong answers, no authority figure pressuring -- pure group conformity pressure. Asch = conformity (group pressure). Milgram = obedience (authority). Stanford prison = role conformity. Bobo doll = observational learning.",mn:"Wrong group answer + no authority = Asch. Authority giving orders = Milgram."},
{id:"pps2",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology"],diff:3,pass:"p7",q:"Adding one correct-answering participant would:",o:["Dramatically decrease conformity","Increase conformity","Have no effect","Cause 100% conformity"],a:0,ex:"Asch: even ONE dissenter reduced conformity from ~37% to ~5%. Even a dissenter giving a DIFFERENT wrong answer reduces conformity. Unanimity, not group size, is the primary driver.",mn:"One ally breaks the spell. Unanimity is key."},
// ============ CARS (10) ============
{id:"cars1a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c1",q:"The author's main argument is that:",o:["Health outcomes are shaped by social structures more than biology","All violence is intentional","Poverty has no health effects","Medicine alone fixes disparities"],a:0,ex:"The passage argues structural violence (systemic inequality) shapes health more than individual biology. Evidence: Farmer's Haiti work showing poverty, not biology, determined TB outcomes. CARS strategy: the main idea is the claim the ENTIRE passage supports.",mn:"CARS: find the claim the whole passage supports, not just one detail."},
{id:"cars1b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Opposing Arguments"],diff:3,pass:"c1",q:"Critics would most likely argue:",o:["The concept broadens 'violence' too much","Poverty never harms health","Framework is universally accepted","Disparities are purely biological"],a:0,ex:"Passage explicitly states the criticism: concept 'dilutes violence beyond usefulness, conflating poverty with assault.' CARS strategy: look for 'critics argue' or 'however' language to find opposing views.",mn:"CARS opposing views: find the 'critics argue' language."},
{id:"cars1c",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken"],diff:3,pass:"c1",q:"Which finding would WEAKEN the argument?",o:["Health outcomes equal across all SES groups","Poverty correlates with worse health","TB fails in wealthy countries too","More barriers in poor areas"],a:0,ex:"The argument rests on health DISPARITIES tracking along social lines. If outcomes were EQUAL regardless of social position, there would be no disparities to explain. CARS weaken questions: find what would break the author's key assumption.",mn:"CARS weaken: what would make the conclusion FALSE?"},
{id:"cars2a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c2",q:"Patient autonomy emerged as a reaction to:",o:["Historical medical paternalism","Modern insurance","Patient medication demands","Hospital administration"],a:0,ex:"Passage states autonomy 'emerged partly as a reaction to historical paternalism.' CARS rule: answer must be DIRECTLY supported by passage text, not outside knowledge.",mn:"CARS: answer comes from the PASSAGE, not outside knowledge."},
{id:"cars2b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Tone and Attitude"],diff:3,pass:"c2",q:"Author's tone toward autonomy:",o:["Supportive but acknowledging limits","Unconditionally supportive","Dismissive","Completely neutral"],a:0,ex:"Author values autonomy (describes paternalism negatively) but presents limitations (emergencies, psychiatric holds, cultural contexts). This is NUANCED -- supportive overall but honest about complexities. CARS tip: extreme answer choices (always, never, completely) are usually wrong.",mn:"CARS tone: look for qualifiers. Extreme words usually wrong."},
{id:"cars3a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c3",q:"Durkheim's main claim about deviance:",o:["It serves essential positive social functions","It is purely destructive","It should be eliminated","It only exists in modern societies"],a:0,ex:"Counter-intuitive argument: deviance FUNCTIONS positively by clarifying boundaries, strengthening solidarity, and driving change. CARS strategy: when a passage presents a surprising claim, the questions test whether you understood it correctly.",mn:"CARS: accept the author's framework even if counter-intuitive."},
{id:"cars3b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application"],diff:3,pass:"c3",q:"Merton's 'innovation' adaptation:",o:["Accept cultural goals, use illegitimate means","Reject both goals and means","Accept goals and means","Withdraw from society"],a:0,ex:"Innovation: accept goals (wealth) + reject legitimate means (crime, fraud). Drug dealing = pursuing money through illegal channels. Retreatism = reject both (withdrawal). Rebellion = replace both. Conformity = accept both.",mn:"Innovation = right goal, wrong method."},
// ============ ADDITIONAL QUESTIONS (50+) ============
// --- MORE BIO SYSTEMS (7) ---
{id:"bs16",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones"],diff:2,q:"Cortisol is released from the:",o:["Adrenal cortex (zona fasciculata)","Adrenal medulla","Anterior pituitary","Thyroid"],a:0,ex:"Cortisol is a glucocorticoid released by the zona fasciculata of the adrenal cortex. It is the primary 'stress hormone' with widespread effects: raises blood glucose (stimulates gluconeogenesis, inhibits insulin), suppresses immune system and inflammation (basis for corticosteroid drugs), promotes protein and fat breakdown. Regulated by the HPA axis: hypothalamus (CRH) -> anterior pituitary (ACTH) -> adrenal cortex (cortisol) -> negative feedback. Chronic elevation causes Cushing syndrome; deficiency causes Addison disease.",mn:"Cortisol = stress glucocorticoid. Zona fasciculata. HPA axis. Cushing = excess, Addison = deficient."},
{id:"bs17",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Digestive System"],diff:2,q:"Most nutrient absorption occurs in the:",o:["Small intestine (especially jejunum)","Stomach","Large intestine","Esophagus"],a:0,ex:"The small intestine (especially the jejunum) is the primary site for nutrient absorption. Its surface area is massively increased by three structural features: circular folds (plicae circulares), villi (finger-like projections), and microvilli (brush border on each epithelial cell). The duodenum receives bile (from liver/gallbladder for fat emulsification) and pancreatic enzymes. The ileum specializes in absorbing vitamin B12 (with intrinsic factor) and bile salts. The large intestine primarily absorbs water and electrolytes.",mn:"Small intestine = absorption (folds + villi + microvilli). Duodenum = bile + enzymes. Ileum = B12."},
{id:"bs18",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System"],diff:2,q:"Gas exchange occurs in the:",o:["Alveoli","Bronchi","Trachea","Bronchioles"],a:0,ex:"The alveoli are tiny thin-walled air sacs (one cell thick, type I pneumocytes) surrounded by capillaries. O2 diffuses from alveolar air into blood (down its partial pressure gradient), and CO2 diffuses from blood into alveolar air. This exchange follows Fick's law: rate of diffusion is proportional to surface area and partial pressure difference, and inversely proportional to membrane thickness. Type II pneumocytes secrete surfactant, which reduces surface tension and prevents alveolar collapse. Total alveolar surface area is approximately 70 m-squared (tennis court size).",mn:"Alveoli = gas exchange (Type I). Surfactant = Type II. Surface area = tennis court."},
{id:"bs19",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Renal System","Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"The kidney compensates for respiratory acidosis by:",o:["Increasing HCO3- reabsorption and H+ secretion","Decreasing HCO3- reabsorption","Increasing ventilation rate","Producing more CO2"],a:0,ex:"Acid-base compensation: respiratory problems are compensated by the kidneys (metabolic), and metabolic problems are compensated by the lungs (respiratory). Respiratory acidosis = CO2 retention (hypoventilation) -> pH drops. The kidney compensates over days by: (1) reabsorbing more HCO3- (bicarbonate buffer) from filtrate, (2) secreting more H+ into urine, (3) generating new HCO3-. This gradually raises blood pH back toward normal. The compensation takes 2-3 days (slower than respiratory compensation, which takes minutes).",mn:"Respiratory problem -> kidney compensates (slow, days). Metabolic problem -> lungs compensate (fast, minutes)."},
{id:"pbs4",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p11",q:"This patient most likely has:",o:["Graves disease (hyperthyroidism)","Hashimoto thyroiditis","Hypothyroidism","Thyroid cancer"],a:0,ex:"The passage shows: low TSH + high T3/T4 + symptoms of excess thyroid hormone (weight loss, heat intolerance, tremors, palpitations) + exophthalmos. Low TSH with high thyroid hormones = the pituitary is being suppressed by excessive T3/T4 (negative feedback working). Exophthalmos is specific to Graves disease (autoimmune -- TSH receptor stimulating antibodies). Hashimoto's is autoimmune hypothyroidism (high TSH, low T3/T4, fatigue, cold intolerance, weight gain).",mn:"Low TSH + high T3/T4 + exophthalmos = Graves (hyper). High TSH + low T3/T4 = Hashimoto (hypo)."},
{id:"pbs5",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones"],diff:3,pass:"p11",q:"TSH is low because:",o:["Excess T3/T4 suppresses anterior pituitary via negative feedback","TSH is being destroyed","The pituitary is producing excess TSH","The hypothalamus is overactive"],a:0,ex:"This is a classic negative feedback question. The hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid axis: TRH (hypothalamus) -> TSH (anterior pituitary) -> T3/T4 (thyroid). When T3/T4 are excessive (as in Graves), they feed back to inhibit TRH and TSH release. Result: TSH drops very low. This pattern (low TSH + high T3/T4) indicates PRIMARY hyperthyroidism (the thyroid itself is overproducing). If TSH were HIGH with high T3/T4, it would suggest a pituitary tumor making excess TSH (very rare).",mn:"High hormone -> suppresses the upstream gland. Low TSH = primary thyroid problem."},
{id:"bs20",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System"],diff:2,q:"Innate vs adaptive immunity:",o:["Innate is immediate and nonspecific; adaptive is slower but specific with memory","Innate is slow and specific","Adaptive is immediate","Both are identical"],a:0,ex:"Innate immunity: first line of defense, responds within hours. Includes physical barriers (skin, mucus), cellular components (neutrophils, macrophages, NK cells, dendritic cells), complement system, inflammation. NON-SPECIFIC -- responds the same way to every pathogen, no memory. Adaptive immunity: takes days to activate on first exposure. Uses lymphocytes (T and B cells) that recognize SPECIFIC antigens. KEY FEATURE: immunological memory -- second exposure triggers faster, stronger response (basis for vaccination). Humoral (B cells -> antibodies) and cell-mediated (T cells -> kill infected cells).",mn:"Innate = fast + general. Adaptive = slow at first + specific + memory."},
// --- MORE CELL BIO (5) ---
{id:"cb10",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Organelles"],diff:2,q:"The Golgi apparatus functions primarily to:",o:["Modify, sort, and package proteins for secretion","Synthesize proteins","Generate ATP","Store DNA"],a:0,ex:"The Golgi apparatus receives proteins from the rough ER via transport vesicles. It processes them through its cisternae (cis/medial/trans): modifying (O-linked glycosylation, phosphorylation, proteolytic cleavage), sorting (adding targeting signals like mannose-6-phosphate for lysosomal enzymes), and packaging into vesicles for their final destination (secretion, plasma membrane, lysosomes). Think of the Golgi as the 'post office' of the cell -- it receives packages, labels them with addresses, and ships them out.",mn:"Golgi = post office. Receives from ER, modifies, sorts, ships."},
{id:"cb11",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction"],diff:3,q:"Receptor tyrosine kinases (RTKs) signal by:",o:["Dimerizing and autophosphorylating tyrosine residues","Activating G-proteins","Opening ion channels directly","Entering the nucleus directly"],a:0,ex:"RTKs are single-pass transmembrane receptors. When ligand (e.g., growth factor like EGF, insulin) binds, two RTK monomers dimerize and cross-phosphorylate each other on tyrosine residues (autophosphorylation). These phosphotyrosines serve as docking sites for signaling proteins (via SH2 domains), activating cascades like Ras -> Raf -> MEK -> ERK (the MAP kinase pathway), which ultimately promotes cell growth and division. Mutations in RTKs or Ras are found in many cancers.",mn:"RTK: ligand -> dimerize -> autophosphorylate -> Ras-MAPK cascade -> growth."},
{id:"cb12",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport"],diff:2,q:"Osmosis is the movement of:",o:["Water across a semipermeable membrane toward higher solute concentration","Solute down its gradient","Water toward lower solute","Ions through channels"],a:0,ex:"Osmosis is the net movement of WATER (not solute) across a semipermeable membrane from a region of LOW solute concentration (high water concentration) to HIGH solute concentration (low water concentration). Water moves to dilute the more concentrated side. Osmotic pressure (pi = iMRT) is the pressure needed to STOP osmosis. A cell in a hypotonic solution gains water (swells/lyses). In hypertonic solution, it loses water (crenates/shrivels). Isotonic = no net water movement.",mn:"Water chases solute. Hypo = swell. Hyper = shrink. Iso = no change."},
{id:"cb13",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport"],diff:3,pass:"p12",q:"SGLT1 is an example of:",o:["Secondary active transport (sodium cotransport)","Simple diffusion","Facilitated diffusion","Primary active transport"],a:0,ex:"SGLT1 moves glucose AGAINST its concentration gradient (from low [glucose] in lumen to high [glucose] in cell) by coupling it to Na+ moving DOWN its gradient (from high [Na+] in lumen to low [Na+] in cell). The Na+ gradient is maintained by the Na+/K+ ATPase (primary active transport) on the basolateral side. So SGLT1 is secondary active transport -- it does not directly use ATP but depends on a gradient created by an ATP-using pump. GLUT2 on the basolateral side is facilitated diffusion (glucose moves DOWN its gradient, no energy needed).",mn:"SGLT1 = secondary active (uses Na+ gradient). GLUT2 = facilitated diffusion. Na+/K+ ATPase = primary active."},
{id:"cb14",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Cell Cycle","Mitosis"],diff:2,q:"Cyclins regulate the cell cycle by:",o:["Activating CDKs (cyclin-dependent kinases)","Directly replicating DNA","Breaking down the nuclear envelope","Synthesizing new histones"],a:0,ex:"The cell cycle is driven by cyclin-CDK complexes. Cyclins are regulatory proteins whose levels rise and fall at specific points in the cell cycle. When a cyclin binds its partner CDK (cyclin-dependent kinase), the CDK becomes active and phosphorylates target proteins that drive the cell to the next phase. Key complexes: Cyclin D/CDK4 (G1), Cyclin E/CDK2 (G1/S transition), Cyclin A/CDK2 (S phase), Cyclin B/CDK1 (G2/M, triggers mitosis). CDK inhibitors like p21 (activated by p53) and p27 can halt the cycle by blocking cyclin-CDK activity.",mn:"Cyclins fluctuate + bind CDKs = drive cell cycle forward. p21/p27 = brakes."},
// --- MORE GEN CHEM (4) ---
{id:"gc12",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"In an exothermic reaction, the enthalpy of products is:",o:["Lower than reactants (energy released)","Higher than reactants","Equal to reactants","Unpredictable"],a:0,ex:"Enthalpy (H) is a measure of the heat content of a system. In an exothermic reaction (delta-H < 0), energy is RELEASED to surroundings as heat, so the products have LESS enthalpy than the reactants -- the energy 'went somewhere' (into the environment). In an endothermic reaction (delta-H > 0), energy is ABSORBED from surroundings, and products have MORE enthalpy than reactants. On an energy diagram: exothermic products are lower than reactants; endothermic products are higher.",mn:"Exothermic: products lower, energy released, feels hot. Endothermic: products higher, energy absorbed, feels cold."},
{id:"gc13",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Solutions"],diff:2,q:"Molarity (M) is defined as:",o:["Moles of solute per liter of solution","Grams of solute per liter","Moles per kilogram of solvent","Mass percent"],a:0,ex:"Molarity = moles of solute / liters of SOLUTION (not solvent). This is the most commonly used concentration unit in chemistry and on the MCAT. Related units: Molality (m) = moles of solute / kg of SOLVENT (used for colligative property calculations because it does not change with temperature). Normality (N) = equivalents per liter (for acids: N = M x number of H+ donated). Dilution equation: M1V1 = M2V2 (moles stay constant when you dilute).",mn:"Molarity = mol/L of solution. Molality = mol/kg of solvent. M1V1 = M2V2 for dilutions."},
{id:"gc14",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Buffers","Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"In a titration of weak acid with strong base, the half-equivalence point is where:",o:["pH = pKa (equal amounts of HA and A-)","All acid is neutralized","pH = 7","The solution is fully buffered with no acid remaining"],a:0,ex:"At the half-equivalence point, exactly HALF the weak acid (HA) has been converted to its conjugate base (A-). This means [HA] = [A-]. By Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa + log([A-]/[HA]) = pKa + log(1) = pKa + 0 = pKa. This is one of the most important titration concepts for the MCAT. At the full equivalence point, ALL HA has been converted to A-, and pH > 7 (basic) because A- is a weak base that hydrolyzes water.",mn:"Half-equivalence: [HA]=[A-] so pH = pKa exactly. Full equivalence: pH > 7 for weak acid/strong base."},
{id:"gc15",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Redox Chemistry","Electrochemistry"],diff:2,q:"In a galvanic cell, oxidation occurs at the:",o:["Anode","Cathode","Salt bridge","Both electrodes"],a:0,ex:"In ALL electrochemical cells (both galvanic and electrolytic): Oxidation occurs at the ANODE (An Ox -- 'an ox'). Reduction occurs at the CATHODE (Red Cat -- 'red cat'). In a galvanic (voltaic) cell: the anode is negative (electrons flow FROM anode TO cathode through the external wire). In an electrolytic cell: the anode is positive (external power source forces electrons in the opposite direction). The salt bridge maintains electrical neutrality by allowing ion flow between half-cells.",mn:"AN OX (anode = oxidation) and RED CAT (cathode = reduction). Always true."},
// --- MORE GENETICS (4) ---
{id:"gen7",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics"],diff:2,q:"Epistasis is when:",o:["One gene masks the expression of another gene","Two genes are on the same chromosome","Genes are equally expressed","Alleles are codominant"],a:0,ex:"Epistasis occurs when the phenotypic expression of one gene is modified or masked by another gene at a different locus. Classic example: Labrador coat color. The E gene determines whether pigment is deposited (EE or Ee = yes, ee = no pigment = yellow lab regardless of B gene). The B gene determines color of pigment (BB/Bb = black, bb = brown/chocolate). So ee is epistatic to B -- it masks whatever B would produce. This modifies the classic 9:3:3:1 dihybrid ratio to 9:3:4 or other modified ratios.",mn:"Epistasis = one gene overrides another. Different from dominance (alleles at SAME gene)."},
{id:"gen8",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Inheritance Patterns"],diff:2,q:"Autosomal dominant disorders require how many mutant alleles?",o:["Only one (heterozygote is affected)","Two (homozygous only)","Three","None (it skips generations)"],a:0,ex:"Autosomal dominant: only ONE copy of the mutant allele is needed for the phenotype to appear. Heterozygotes (Aa) are affected. Every affected individual has at least one affected parent (does NOT skip generations, unlike recessive). Both males and females equally affected. Examples: Huntington disease (CAG repeat expansion), Marfan syndrome (fibrillin-1), achondroplasia (FGFR3), familial hypercholesterolemia (LDL receptor). Many AD disorders show variable expressivity (severity varies) and reduced penetrance (not all carriers show symptoms).",mn:"Dominant = one copy enough. Every generation affected. Recessive = two copies, can skip generations."},
{id:"gen9",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Mendelian Genetics","Inheritance Patterns"],diff:3,q:"Two heterozygous parents (AaBb) in a dihybrid cross: fraction with both dominant phenotypes?",o:["9/16","3/16","1/16","4/16"],a:0,ex:"For two independently assorting genes, multiply the individual probabilities. For each gene separately: Aa x Aa gives 3/4 dominant phenotype. For both genes simultaneously: 3/4 x 3/4 = 9/16. The full dihybrid ratio: 9 A_B_ : 3 A_bb : 3 aaB_ : 1 aabb. This 9:3:3:1 ratio requires independent assortment (genes on different chromosomes or far apart on the same chromosome). Linked genes (close together on the same chromosome) would deviate from this ratio.",mn:"Dihybrid 9:3:3:1. Both dominant = 9/16 = 3/4 x 3/4."},
{id:"gen10",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Chromosomal Abnormalities","Meiosis"],diff:2,q:"Turner syndrome karyotype is:",o:["45,X (monosomy X)","47,XXY","47,XYY","46,XX"],a:0,ex:"Turner syndrome: 45,X -- only one X chromosome, no second sex chromosome. Phenotype: female (but ovaries fail to develop), short stature, webbed neck, shield-shaped chest, coarctation of aorta. Most common monosomy compatible with life (most autosomal monosomies are lethal). Caused by nondisjunction. Compare: Klinefelter syndrome = 47,XXY (male, tall, infertile, gynecomastia). Down syndrome = 47,XX+21 or 47,XY+21 (trisomy 21).",mn:"Turner = 45,X (female, short, webbed neck). Klinefelter = 47,XXY (male, tall, infertile)."},
// --- MORE ORGO (4) ---
{id:"org9",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Stereochemistry"],diff:2,q:"A meso compound has:",o:["Stereocenters but an internal plane of symmetry (achiral)","No stereocenters","Only R configurations","Maximum optical rotation"],a:0,ex:"A meso compound has two or more stereocenters but is ACHIRAL (optically inactive) because it possesses an internal plane of symmetry -- one half of the molecule is the mirror image of the other half, so they cancel out. Example: (2R,3S)-tartaric acid has two stereocenters but the R and S cancel, making it a meso compound with zero optical rotation. Meso compounds are NOT the same as racemic mixtures (which are mixtures of two separate enantiomers). A single meso molecule is inherently achiral.",mn:"Meso = has stereocenters but internal mirror plane cancels them = achiral."},
{id:"org10",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"An ester is formed from:",o:["A carboxylic acid + an alcohol (condensation)","Two alcohols","Two ketones","An aldehyde + a ketone"],a:0,ex:"Ester formation (Fischer esterification): R-COOH + R'-OH -> R-COO-R' + H2O. This is a condensation reaction (water is lost). It is acid-catalyzed and reversible (Le Chatelier: remove water or use excess alcohol to drive it forward). Ester hydrolysis (reverse reaction) breaks the ester back into acid + alcohol. Saponification: ester + strong base (NaOH) -> carboxylate salt (soap) + alcohol -- this is irreversible. Esters are found in fats/oils (triglycerides = 3 fatty acids esterified to glycerol) and many fragrances.",mn:"Ester = acid + alcohol - water. Saponification = ester + NaOH -> soap."},
{id:"org11",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Addition Reactions","Stereochemistry"],diff:3,q:"Anti-Markovnikov addition occurs with:",o:["HBr + peroxides (radical mechanism)","HBr alone","H2O + acid catalyst","HCl + heat"],a:0,ex:"Peroxides (ROOR) initiate a radical chain mechanism. Br radical adds FIRST to the less substituted carbon (forming the more stable radical intermediate), and H ends up on the more substituted carbon -- opposite of Markovnikov. This ONLY works with HBr + peroxides. HCl and HI do not undergo this radical addition because the energetics are unfavorable for their radical chains. Without peroxides, HBr follows normal Markovnikov addition via the polar (carbocation) mechanism.",mn:"Peroxides = radicals = flip Markovnikov. ONLY works with HBr."},
{id:"org12",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions"],diff:2,q:"A good leaving group is:",o:["A weak base (stable after departure)","A strong base","A strong nucleophile","An unstable anion"],a:0,ex:"The best leaving groups are WEAK BASES -- species that are stable when they carry the negative charge or electron pair after departure. The weaker the base, the more stable it is after leaving, and the better it is as a leaving group. Ranking (best to worst): I- > Br- > Cl- >> F- (halides: larger = better, more stable). Tosylate (TsO-) and mesylate (MsO-) are excellent artificial LGs. OH- is a terrible leaving group -- which is why alcohols must be protonated (to H2O, a good LG) or converted to tosylates before SN/E reactions.",mn:"Good LG = weak base = stable anion. I > Br > Cl >> F. Protonate OH to make H2O."},
// --- MORE METABOLISM (3) ---
{id:"met16",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Enzyme Regulation"],diff:2,q:"The three irreversible enzymes of glycolysis are:",o:["Hexokinase, PFK-1, and Pyruvate kinase","Aldolase, Enolase, and PFK-1","All 10 enzymes","Hexokinase and Aldolase only"],a:0,ex:"Glycolysis has 10 enzymes, but only 3 catalyze irreversible (highly exergonic) reactions: (1) Hexokinase: glucose -> G6P (traps glucose in cell). (2) PFK-1: F6P -> F1,6BP (committed step, main regulatory point). (3) Pyruvate kinase: PEP -> pyruvate (generates ATP by substrate-level phosphorylation). Gluconeogenesis must bypass these 3 steps with 4 different enzymes because they cannot be run in reverse.",mn:"3 irreversible glycolysis steps: Hexokinase, PFK-1, Pyruvate kinase. Gluconeogenesis bypasses all 3."},
{id:"met17",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,q:"An uncoupler of oxidative phosphorylation would:",o:["Increase O2 consumption but decrease ATP production","Stop O2 consumption","Increase ATP production","Have no effect"],a:0,ex:"Uncouplers (like 2,4-DNP, thermogenin/UCP1 in brown fat) make the inner mitochondrial membrane permeable to protons, allowing H+ to flow back into the matrix WITHOUT passing through ATP synthase. The proton gradient dissipates as HEAT instead of driving ATP synthesis. Since the gradient is constantly being dissipated, the ETC runs FASTER (increased O2 consumption) trying to rebuild it, but ATP production DECREASES because the energy is lost as heat. This is different from ETC inhibitors (which stop electron flow and decrease O2 consumption).",mn:"Uncoupler = proton leak = more O2 consumed, less ATP, more heat. Different from inhibitors."},
{id:"met18",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Metabolism"],diff:3,q:"Transamination reactions require which cofactor?",o:["Pyridoxal phosphate (PLP, from vitamin B6)","TPP (from B1)","FAD (from B2)","Coenzyme A (from B5)"],a:0,ex:"Transamination transfers an amino group from an amino acid to an alpha-keto acid, converting one amino acid into another. This is how the body interconverts non-essential amino acids. The cofactor is pyridoxal phosphate (PLP), derived from vitamin B6 (pyridoxine). PLP is required by aminotransferases (transaminases like ALT and AST -- clinically important liver enzymes). B6 deficiency can cause anemia (PLP also needed for heme synthesis) and neurological symptoms. PLP is also required for decarboxylation reactions (making neurotransmitters like serotonin, dopamine, GABA from amino acid precursors).",mn:"PLP (B6) = transamination cofactor. Also needed for decarboxylation (neurotransmitter synthesis)."},
// --- MORE AMINO ACIDS (3 including 1 matching) ---
{id:"aam5",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",type:"match",tags:["Amino Acid Classification","Protein Structure"],diff:2,q:"Match amino acid to its single-letter code:",pairs:[["Tryptophan","W"],["Glutamate","E"],["Aspartate","D"],["Lysine","K"],["Phenylalanine","F"]],ex:"The single-letter codes are not always intuitive. Some make sense: G=Glycine, A=Alanine, V=Valine, L=Leucine, I=Isoleucine, S=Serine, T=Threonine, C=Cysteine, M=Methionine, P=Proline, H=Histidine. Others are less obvious: W=Tryptophan (looks like a double-ring), F=Phenylalanine, Y=Tyrosine, D=Aspartate, E=Glutamate, N=Asparagine, Q=Glutamine, K=Lysine, R=Arginine. These codes appear in research papers and occasionally on the MCAT.",mn:"Tricky codes: W=Trp, F=Phe, D=Asp, E=Glu, K=Lys, R=Arg, N=Asn, Q=Gln"},
{id:"aa13",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties"],diff:2,q:"Tryptophan is the precursor for which important molecule?",o:["Serotonin (and melatonin)","Dopamine","Histamine","Acetylcholine"],a:0,ex:"Amino acids serve as precursors for many important biomolecules. Tryptophan -> serotonin (via tryptophan hydroxylase + DOPA decarboxylase, both need PLP/B6) -> melatonin (pineal gland, regulates sleep). Tyrosine -> dopamine -> norepinephrine -> epinephrine (catecholamine pathway). Histidine -> histamine (by histidine decarboxylase). Glutamate -> GABA (by glutamic acid decarboxylase). Knowing these amino acid to neurotransmitter conversions is high-yield.",mn:"Trp->serotonin->melatonin. Tyr->dopa->NE->epi. His->histamine. Glu->GABA."},
{id:"aa14",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Disulfide Bonds"],diff:2,q:"Which amino acid has the only sulfur-containing side chain that forms covalent crosslinks?",o:["Cysteine","Methionine","Serine","Threonine"],a:0,ex:"Both cysteine and methionine contain sulfur, but only CYSTEINE can form disulfide bonds. Cysteine has a thiol (-SH) group that can be oxidized to form -S-S- links with another cysteine. Methionine has a thioether (S bonded to two carbons) that does NOT form crosslinks. This distinction is commonly tested. Cysteine's ability to form disulfide bonds is exploited by the body to stabilize extracellular proteins (antibodies, insulin) and by labs to study protein structure (breaking disulfide bonds with DTT or beta-mercaptoethanol denatures proteins).",mn:"Cys = -SH = forms disulfide bonds. Met = thioether = no crosslinks. Both have sulfur."},
// --- MORE PSYCH/SOC (3) ---
{id:"ps21",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sleep"],diff:2,q:"Slow-wave sleep (N3/NREM stage 3) is characterized by:",o:["Delta waves and is the most physically restorative stage","Rapid eye movements and vivid dreaming","Sleep spindles and K-complexes","Light sleep with theta waves"],a:0,ex:"NREM sleep has 3 stages: N1 (light, theta waves, hypnagogic hallucinations), N2 (sleep spindles and K-complexes, most time spent here), N3 (slow-wave/deep sleep, delta waves, most physically restorative -- growth hormone peaks here, memory consolidation for declarative/factual memories). REM sleep: rapid eye movements, vivid dreaming, muscle atonia (paralysis), EEG resembles waking, procedural memory consolidation. Sleep cycles last ~90 min. N3 is predominant early in the night, REM increases later.",mn:"N3 = delta waves = deep = restorative = GH release. REM = dreaming + paralysis."},
{id:"ps22",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology","Health Disparities"],diff:2,q:"The biopsychosocial model proposes that health is determined by:",o:["Biological, psychological, AND social factors interacting","Biology alone","Psychology alone","Social factors alone"],a:0,ex:"George Engel (1977) proposed the biopsychosocial model as an alternative to the purely biomedical model. It argues that health and illness result from the interaction of: BIOLOGICAL factors (genetics, physiology, pathogens), PSYCHOLOGICAL factors (mood, coping, personality, stress, health beliefs), and SOCIAL factors (family support, SES, culture, discrimination, healthcare access). Example: two patients with the same cancer diagnosis may have vastly different outcomes based on their psychological coping, social support networks, and access to quality care.",mn:"Bio + Psycho + Social = health. Not just biology alone."},
{id:"cars4a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c4",q:"The author's main argument is that:",o:["The biopsychosocial model provides a more complete understanding of health than the biomedical model alone","The biomedical model should be abandoned","Biology is irrelevant to health","Engel's model has been disproven"],a:0,ex:"The passage presents the biomedical model's strengths (antibiotics, surgery, imaging) but argues it neglects psychological and social dimensions. It does NOT say to abandon biology -- it says to EMBED biology within a broader context. The biopsychosocial model is presented as an expansion, not a replacement. CARS strategy: look for the author's balanced position -- rarely do MCAT passages argue for total rejection of established approaches.",mn:"CARS: authors usually argue for expansion or nuance, not total rejection."},
{id:"cars4b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application"],diff:3,pass:"c4",q:"Which scenario best illustrates the biopsychosocial model?",o:["A diabetic patient whose outcomes depend on genetics, depression, and neighborhood food access","A patient treated only with medication","A patient whose illness is explained entirely by genes","A healthy patient with no risk factors"],a:0,ex:"The biopsychosocial model requires ALL THREE factors to be present: biological (genetics of diabetes), psychological (depression affecting self-care, motivation, adherence), and social (neighborhood food access determining diet quality). The other options address only one dimension. CARS application questions ask you to find the scenario that matches ALL elements of the passage's framework.",mn:"CARS application: every element of the framework must be present in the correct answer."},
// --- MORE MOLECULAR BIO (2) ---
{id:"mb10",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation"],diff:2,q:"The wobble position in codons is the:",o:["3rd position (allows non-standard base pairing)","1st position","2nd position","All positions"],a:0,ex:"The genetic code has 64 codons for 20 amino acids + 3 stops -- it is degenerate (redundant). Most redundancy occurs at the 3rd codon position (wobble position). The 1st position of the tRNA anticodon (which pairs with the 3rd codon position) can form non-standard base pairs: G can pair with U, and inosine (I) in the anticodon can pair with U, C, or A. This means a single tRNA can recognize multiple codons that differ only at position 3, reducing the number of tRNAs needed.",mn:"Position 3 = wobble = flexible pairing = why the code is degenerate."},
{id:"mb11",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation"],diff:3,q:"Epigenetic modifications include:",o:["DNA methylation and histone acetylation","Changes to the DNA sequence","Point mutations","Chromosomal translocations"],a:0,ex:"Epigenetics: heritable changes in gene expression WITHOUT altering the DNA sequence. Two major mechanisms: (1) DNA methylation: methyl groups added to cytosines in CpG islands (promoter regions). Methylation typically SILENCES gene expression by blocking transcription factor binding. (2) Histone modification: acetylation of histones by HATs (histone acetyltransferases) LOOSENS chromatin (euchromatin) and INCREASES transcription. Deacetylation by HDACs tightens chromatin (heterochromatin) and DECREASES transcription. These modifications can be inherited through cell division and are important in development, cancer, and gene-environment interactions.",mn:"Methylation = silence. Acetylation = activate. No DNA sequence change = epigenetic."},
// --- MORE PHYSICS (2) ---
{id:"ph11",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Work and Energy"],diff:2,q:"Kinetic energy is:",o:["KE = 1/2 mv^2","KE = mgh","KE = Fd","KE = mv"],a:0,ex:"Kinetic energy (energy of motion) = 1/2 * mass * velocity^2. Note the v^2: doubling velocity QUADRUPLES KE (important for car crash physics -- twice the speed = four times the stopping distance). Potential energy (gravitational) = mgh. Conservation of energy: KE + PE = constant (in absence of non-conservative forces like friction). Work-energy theorem: net work = change in KE. At the bottom of a hill (max KE, min PE). At the top (max PE, min KE).",mn:"KE = 1/2 mv^2. Double v = 4x KE. PE = mgh. KE + PE = constant."},
{id:"ph12",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Electrostatics"],diff:2,q:"Electric field lines point:",o:["From positive to negative charges","From negative to positive","In circles","Randomly"],a:0,ex:"Electric field lines point in the direction a positive test charge would move: AWAY from positive charges (repelled) and TOWARD negative charges (attracted). Field lines never cross. Denser lines = stronger field. Inside a conductor at equilibrium, E = 0 (charges redistribute to cancel internal field). Between parallel plates, the field is uniform: E = V/d (voltage divided by plate separation). Field from a point charge: E = kQ/r^2.",mn:"Field lines: + to -. Dense = strong. E = 0 inside conductors. E = V/d between plates."},
{id:"met19",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Enzyme Regulation","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Which glycolysis enzyme is inhibited by its own product glucose-6-phosphate?",o:["Hexokinase","PFK-1","Pyruvate kinase","Aldolase"],a:0,ex:"Hexokinase is feedback-inhibited by its product G6P. This prevents the cell from trapping more glucose than it can process. Note: the liver uses glucokinase instead, which is NOT inhibited by G6P and has a higher Km -- allowing the liver to take up glucose proportionally to blood levels (glucose sensor function). Hexokinase vs glucokinase is a commonly tested distinction.",mn:"Hexokinase inhibited by G6P. Liver uses glucokinase (no product inhibition, higher Km)."},
{id:"met20",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Krebs Cycle","Metabolic Regulation","Electron Carriers"],diff:2,q:"The rate-limiting enzyme of the Krebs cycle is:",o:["Isocitrate dehydrogenase","Citrate synthase","Succinate dehydrogenase","Malate dehydrogenase"],a:0,ex:"Isocitrate dehydrogenase is the rate-limiting step of the Krebs cycle. It converts isocitrate to alpha-ketoglutarate, producing NADH and releasing CO2. Activated by ADP (low energy signal) and Ca2+. Inhibited by ATP and NADH (high energy signals). This mirrors the regulation of PFK-1 in glycolysis -- both are activated when energy is low and inhibited when energy is high.",mn:"Isocitrate DH = Krebs gatekeeper. Same logic as PFK-1: low energy activates, high energy inhibits."},
{id:"met21",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation","ATP Yield"],diff:3,q:"ATP synthase (Complex V) works by:",o:["Harnessing the proton gradient to drive rotational catalysis","Directly oxidizing NADH","Hydrolyzing ATP to pump protons","Transferring electrons to O2"],a:0,ex:"ATP synthase is a molecular motor. Protons (H+) flow DOWN their concentration gradient from the intermembrane space back into the matrix through the Fo subunit (the proton channel), which causes rotation of the c-ring. This rotation drives conformational changes in the F1 subunit that catalyze ADP + Pi -> ATP. This is called chemiosmosis (Mitchell's chemiosmotic hypothesis, Nobel Prize 1978). About 2.5 ATP per NADH and 1.5 ATP per FADH2. Oligomycin blocks the Fo channel, stopping ATP synthesis.",mn:"ATP synthase = rotary motor driven by proton gradient. Oligomycin blocks it."},
{id:"met22",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Aerobic Respiration","Electron Transport Chain","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:2,q:"The final electron acceptor in the electron transport chain is:",o:["Molecular oxygen (O2)","NAD+","FAD","Cytochrome c"],a:0,ex:"O2 accepts electrons at Complex IV (cytochrome c oxidase) and is reduced to H2O. This is why we need to breathe -- without O2 as the terminal electron acceptor, electrons back up, the ETC stops, the proton gradient dissipates, and ATP synthesis halts. Cyanide and carbon monoxide also block Complex IV. About 90% of the O2 you consume goes to Complex IV for this purpose.",mn:"O2 = final electron acceptor at Complex IV. No O2 = no ETC = no aerobic ATP."},
{id:"met23",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Gluconeogenesis","Metabolic Regulation","Hormonal Regulation"],diff:3,q:"Gluconeogenesis occurs primarily in the:",o:["Liver (and to a lesser extent, kidneys)","Skeletal muscle","Brain","Adipose tissue"],a:0,ex:"Gluconeogenesis (making new glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors) occurs mainly in the LIVER and to a lesser extent the KIDNEYS. It cannot occur in muscle because muscle lacks glucose-6-phosphatase (the enzyme that removes the phosphate so glucose can leave the cell). Precursors: lactate (from Cori cycle), glycerol (from fat breakdown), and glucogenic amino acids (most amino acids). Notably, acetyl-CoA CANNOT be converted to glucose in humans -- this is why fatty acids cannot be used for gluconeogenesis (except odd-chain FAs which yield some propionyl-CoA -> succinyl-CoA).",mn:"Liver and kidney only. Muscle cannot export glucose (no glucose-6-phosphatase). Fatty acids cannot become glucose."},
{id:"met24",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Fatty Acid Metabolism","Beta-Oxidation","Krebs Cycle"],diff:2,q:"Each cycle of beta-oxidation produces:",o:["1 FADH2 + 1 NADH + 1 acetyl-CoA","2 ATP + 1 NADH","1 ATP + 1 FADH2","2 NADH + 1 GTP"],a:0,ex:"Each beta-oxidation cycle shortens the fatty acid by 2 carbons and produces: 1 FADH2 (from acyl-CoA dehydrogenase), 1 NADH (from beta-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase), and 1 acetyl-CoA (which enters the Krebs cycle for further oxidation). A 16-carbon palmitate undergoes 7 cycles to produce 8 acetyl-CoA + 7 FADH2 + 7 NADH. Total ATP from palmitate: about 106 ATP (minus 2 ATP for activation = 104 net). This is why fats store much more energy per gram than carbohydrates.",mn:"Per cycle: 1 FADH2 + 1 NADH + 1 acetyl-CoA. Palmitate (16C) = 7 cycles = 8 acetyl-CoA."},
{id:"met25",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Ketogenesis","Fatty Acid Metabolism","Insulin"],diff:3,q:"Ketone bodies are produced when:",o:["Acetyl-CoA exceeds Krebs cycle capacity (fasting/diabetes)","Blood glucose is high","Insulin levels are high","The fed state activates lipogenesis"],a:0,ex:"Ketogenesis occurs when the liver has excess acetyl-CoA that cannot enter the Krebs cycle. Two main scenarios: (1) FASTING: beta-oxidation produces lots of acetyl-CoA, but OAA is diverted to gluconeogenesis, so Krebs cycle cannot accept it all. (2) UNCONTROLLED TYPE 1 DIABETES: without insulin, cells cannot take up glucose, so the body acts as if fasting even though blood glucose is high. Excess acetyl-CoA is converted to ketone bodies (acetoacetate, beta-hydroxybutyrate, acetone). Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is a life-threatening complication where massive ketone production drops blood pH dangerously low.",mn:"Ketogenesis = too much acetyl-CoA + not enough OAA. Fasting or uncontrolled T1 diabetes."},
{id:"met26",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Pentose Phosphate Pathway","Aerobic Respiration","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Which metabolic pathway produces NADPH for fatty acid synthesis?",o:["Pentose phosphate pathway","Glycolysis","Krebs cycle","Beta-oxidation"],a:0,ex:"The PPP (pentose phosphate pathway) is the primary source of cytoplasmic NADPH. NADPH is required for: (1) Fatty acid synthesis (each cycle of FA synthesis uses 2 NADPH), (2) Cholesterol synthesis, (3) Maintaining reduced glutathione (antioxidant defense), (4) Cytochrome P450 detoxification reactions, (5) Respiratory burst in phagocytes (NADPH oxidase generates ROS to kill pathogens). Glycolysis and Krebs produce NADH (not NADPH) -- different cofactor, different purpose. NADH is for energy (ETC), NADPH is for biosynthesis and defense.",mn:"NADPH for biosynthesis = PPP. NADH for energy = glycolysis/Krebs. Different roles!"},
{id:"met27",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Cori Cycle","Anaerobic Metabolism","Gluconeogenesis"],diff:2,q:"The Cori cycle is important during:",o:["Intense exercise (muscle sends lactate to liver)","Sleep","Fed state after a meal","During fatty acid synthesis"],a:0,ex:"During intense exercise, muscle produces lactate faster than it can be oxidized. Lactate is exported to the blood, taken up by the liver, and converted back to glucose via gluconeogenesis. This glucose returns to muscle for more glycolysis. The cycle costs a net 4 ATP (muscle gains 2, liver spends 6). It allows muscle to continue working anaerobically while the liver handles the metabolic debt. The alanine cycle is similar but uses alanine instead of lactate (transamination of pyruvate in muscle, sent to liver).",mn:"Cori: muscle lactate -> liver glucose -> muscle. Net cost 4 ATP. Alanine cycle is similar."},
{id:"aa15",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Classification","Isoelectric Point","Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"The pI of aspartate (pKa1=2.0, pKa2=3.65, pKa3=9.6) is:",o:["2.83 (average of two lowest pKas)","6.63","5.80","4.83"],a:0,ex:"For acidic amino acids (Asp, Glu), the pI is the average of the two LOWEST pKa values. These are the pKas that flank the zwitterionic form (one positive, one negative, zero net charge). For Asp: pI = (2.0 + 3.65)/2 = 2.83. For basic amino acids (Lys, Arg, His), pI = average of the two HIGHEST pKas. For neutral amino acids, pI = average of the alpha-amino and alpha-carboxyl pKas.",mn:"Acidic AA pI = average of two lowest pKas. Basic AA pI = average of two highest."},
{id:"aa16",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Amino Acid Properties","Protein Structure","Amino Acid Classification"],diff:2,q:"Which amino acid can be both polar and participate in hydrophobic interactions?",o:["Tyrosine (aromatic ring + hydroxyl group)","Alanine","Glycine","Aspartate"],a:0,ex:"Tyrosine has a phenol ring (hydrophobic, aromatic) with a hydroxyl group (-OH, polar). This dual nature means Tyr can be found at protein surfaces where it straddles the water-lipid interface. The -OH can hydrogen bond and can be phosphorylated (key in signal transduction -- receptor tyrosine kinases). Tyr can also be iodinated to form thyroid hormones (T3 and T4). It absorbs UV at 280nm (second strongest after Trp).",mn:"Tyr = aromatic + hydroxyl = both hydrophobic and polar. Phosphorylation site. Makes thyroid hormones."},
{id:"aa17",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Essential Amino Acids","Amino Acid Properties","Metabolism"],diff:2,q:"Phenylketonuria (PKU) is caused by deficiency of:",o:["Phenylalanine hydroxylase","Tyrosine hydroxylase","Tryptophan hydroxylase","Histidine decarboxylase"],a:0,ex:"PKU is an autosomal recessive disorder caused by deficiency of phenylalanine hydroxylase, which converts Phe to Tyr. Without this enzyme, Phe accumulates to toxic levels causing intellectual disability, seizures, and musty body odor. Tyr becomes conditionally essential (must be obtained from diet). Treatment: low-Phe diet started at birth. This is why Tyr is NOT classified as essential in healthy individuals -- it can be made from Phe. PKU is detected by newborn screening.",mn:"PKU = no Phe hydroxylase = Phe builds up = brain damage. Tyr becomes essential. Diet treatment."},
{id:"aa18",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Protein Structure","Disulfide Bonds","Amino Acid Properties"],diff:3,q:"Denaturation by urea works by:",o:["Disrupting hydrophobic interactions and hydrogen bonds","Breaking peptide bonds","Cleaving disulfide bonds","Changing the amino acid sequence"],a:0,ex:"Urea is a chaotropic agent that disrupts the NON-COVALENT interactions holding a protein in its folded state: hydrogen bonds, hydrophobic interactions, and van der Waals forces. It does NOT break covalent bonds (peptide bonds or disulfide bonds remain intact). To also break disulfide bonds, you need a reducing agent like DTT or beta-mercaptoethanol. Complete denaturation requires both urea (for non-covalent) and a reducing agent (for disulfide bonds). SDS-PAGE uses SDS (denatures + adds uniform negative charge) and BME (breaks disulfides).",mn:"Urea breaks non-covalent forces. DTT/BME breaks disulfide bonds. Both needed for complete denaturation."},
{id:"cb15",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction","Cell Cycle","Tumor Suppressors"],diff:3,q:"Ras is an oncogene that when mutated:",o:["Is constitutively active, driving uncontrolled cell growth","Becomes a tumor suppressor","Stops all signaling","Promotes apoptosis"],a:0,ex:"Ras is a GTPase that acts as a molecular switch in the RTK signaling pathway. Normal Ras: cycles between active (GTP-bound) and inactive (GDP-bound) states. GTPase-activating proteins (GAPs) turn Ras OFF by stimulating GTP hydrolysis. Mutant Ras (found in ~30% of cancers): cannot hydrolyze GTP, so it is PERMANENTLY STUCK in the ON position, continuously activating the Raf-MEK-ERK (MAPK) cascade, driving cell proliferation. Ras is a proto-oncogene; the mutated version is an oncogene. Oncogenes = gain-of-function mutations (one allele sufficient). Tumor suppressors = loss-of-function (need both alleles lost).",mn:"Ras = molecular switch stuck ON in cancer. Oncogene = gain-of-function (1 allele). TSG = loss-of-function (2 alleles)."},
{id:"cb16",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Membrane Transport","Signal Transduction","Organelles"],diff:2,q:"The endoplasmic reticulum stores which important signaling ion?",o:["Calcium (Ca2+)","Sodium (Na+)","Potassium (K+)","Chloride (Cl-)"],a:0,ex:"The ER (especially smooth ER and sarcoplasmic reticulum in muscle) stores Ca2+ at concentrations 10,000x higher than cytoplasm. When IP3 (from PLC/GPCR signaling) binds IP3 receptors on the ER, Ca2+ is released into the cytoplasm, triggering downstream effects: muscle contraction (binds troponin C), secretion (exocytosis), enzyme activation (calmodulin-dependent kinases), and apoptosis (when sustained). Ca2+ is pumped back into the ER by SERCA pumps (Ca2+-ATPase).",mn:"ER stores Ca2+. IP3 releases it. Ca2+ triggers contraction, secretion, enzymes. SERCA pumps it back."},
{id:"gen11",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Meiosis","Genetic Diversity","Chromosomal Abnormalities"],diff:2,q:"Crossing over during meiosis occurs in:",o:["Prophase I (between homologous chromosomes)","Metaphase I","Anaphase II","Prophase II"],a:0,ex:"Crossing over (recombination) occurs during PROPHASE I of meiosis when homologous chromosomes pair up (synapsis) to form tetrads (bivalents). Segments of DNA are exchanged between non-sister chromatids of homologous chromosomes at points called chiasmata. This produces recombinant chromosomes with new allele combinations that did not exist in either parent. Along with independent assortment (2^23 possible arrangements in humans) and random fertilization, crossing over is one of three sources of genetic diversity from sexual reproduction.",mn:"Crossing over = Prophase I. Exchange DNA between homologs. Creates new allele combinations."},
{id:"gen12",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Population Genetics","Hardy-Weinberg","Mendelian Genetics"],diff:3,q:"Which would violate Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium?",o:["Natural selection favoring one genotype","Large population size","Random mating","No migration"],a:0,ex:"Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium (p^2 + 2pq + q^2 = 1) requires FIVE conditions: (1) Large population (no genetic drift), (2) No mutation, (3) No migration (no gene flow), (4) Random mating, (5) No natural selection. Violating ANY condition changes allele frequencies. Natural selection = differential survival/reproduction based on genotype, which directly changes allele frequencies. The MCAT commonly asks you to identify which factor violates HW or to calculate expected frequencies and compare to observed data.",mn:"HW needs: large pop, no mutation, no migration, random mating, no selection. Violate any = allele frequencies change."},
{id:"gen13",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Inheritance Patterns","X-Linked Inheritance","Mendelian Genetics"],diff:2,q:"A carrier mother (X^A X^a) and normal father (X^A Y) have a son. What is the chance he is affected?",o:["50%","25%","100%","0%"],a:0,ex:"Sons get their X from mom and Y from dad. The carrier mother has a 50% chance of passing on her affected X^a to each son. So each son has a 50% chance of being affected (X^a Y). Daughters get X from both parents: 50% chance of being a carrier (X^A X^a), 50% chance of being normal (X^A X^A), 0% chance of being affected (would need X^a X^a, but father only contributes X^A). Key principle: fathers NEVER pass X-linked traits to sons (sons get Y from dad).",mn:"Sons get X from mom only. Carrier mom = 50% sons affected. Fathers never pass X-linked to sons."},
{id:"gen14",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Inheritance Patterns","Mendelian Genetics","Population Genetics"],diff:2,q:"Incomplete penetrance means:",o:["Not all individuals with the genotype show the phenotype","The phenotype varies in severity","Multiple genes contribute","The trait skips every other generation"],a:0,ex:"Penetrance = the proportion of individuals with a particular genotype who actually express the expected phenotype. Incomplete/reduced penetrance means some individuals carry the allele but do NOT show the trait. Example: BRCA1 mutations have ~70% penetrance for breast cancer -- 70% of carriers develop cancer, 30% do not. Expressivity is different: it refers to the SEVERITY of the phenotype varying among those who do express it. Example: neurofibromatosis -- some patients have mild cafe-au-lait spots, others have severe tumors.",mn:"Penetrance = do you show it? Expressivity = how severely? Both can vary independently."},
{id:"bs21",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Hormones","Renal System"],diff:2,q:"Renin is released from the kidney in response to:",o:["Low blood pressure / low Na+ delivery to macula densa","High blood pressure","High blood glucose","Low potassium"],a:0,ex:"Renin is released by juxtaglomerular cells in the kidney when: (1) BP is low (detected by baroreceptors in afferent arteriole), (2) Na+/Cl- delivery to the macula densa is low, (3) Sympathetic stimulation (beta-1 receptors). Renin cleaves angiotensinogen (from liver) to angiotensin I. ACE (in lungs) converts ang I to ang II. Ang II: vasoconstriction, stimulates aldosterone, stimulates ADH, stimulates thirst. This is the RAAS system. ACE inhibitors and ARBs are major antihypertensive drugs.",mn:"Low BP -> renin -> ang I -> ACE -> ang II -> vasoconstriction + aldosterone. ACE inhibitors block this."},
{id:"bs22",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Nervous System","Action Potential","Neurotransmitters"],diff:2,q:"Saltatory conduction in myelinated neurons means:",o:["Action potentials jump between nodes of Ranvier","Signals travel through the myelin sheath","Conduction is slower than unmyelinated","Myelin generates action potentials"],a:0,ex:"Myelin (produced by Schwann cells in PNS, oligodendrocytes in CNS) insulates the axon, preventing ion leakage. Action potentials can only be generated at the gaps between myelin segments (nodes of Ranvier), where ion channels are concentrated. The signal effectively jumps from node to node, which is MUCH faster than continuous conduction in unmyelinated neurons. Speed: myelinated ~120 m/s vs unmyelinated ~1 m/s. Demyelinating diseases (multiple sclerosis, Guillain-Barre) slow or block signal transmission.",mn:"Myelin insulates. Signal jumps node to node. Much faster. MS/Guillain-Barre = demyelination."},
{id:"bs23",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System","Hormones","Endocrine System"],diff:3,q:"Antibodies (immunoglobulins) are produced by:",o:["Plasma cells (differentiated B cells)","T cells","Macrophages","NK cells"],a:0,ex:"The humoral immune response: B cells recognize antigen via their B cell receptor (surface antibody) -> with T helper cell help (CD4+), B cells activate and differentiate into: (1) PLASMA CELLS that secrete large amounts of antibody, and (2) MEMORY B CELLS for long-lasting immunity. Antibody classes: IgM (first response, pentamer), IgG (most abundant, crosses placenta), IgA (mucous membranes, breast milk), IgE (allergies, parasites, mast cell degranulation), IgD (B cell surface receptor). Antibodies neutralize, opsonize, activate complement, and mediate ADCC.",mn:"B cells -> plasma cells -> antibodies. IgM first, IgG most. IgA = mucosa. IgE = allergy."},
{id:"bs24",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Respiratory System","Hemoglobin","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"How is most CO2 transported in blood?",o:["As bicarbonate (HCO3-) in plasma (~70%)","Dissolved in plasma","Bound to hemoglobin","As carbonic acid"],a:0,ex:"CO2 transport: ~70% as bicarbonate (CO2 + H2O -> H2CO3 -> HCO3- + H+, catalyzed by carbonic anhydrase in RBCs), ~23% bound to hemoglobin (as carbaminohemoglobin -- binds amino groups, not heme iron), ~7% dissolved in plasma. The HCO3- exits RBCs via the chloride shift (HCO3-/Cl- antiporter). In the lungs, the reaction reverses: HCO3- -> CO2 exhaled. The H+ generated from CO2 loading in tissues is buffered by deoxyhemoglobin (Bohr effect) -- this is why deoxyhemoglobin is a better buffer than oxyhemoglobin.",mn:"70% as HCO3- (bicarbonate), 23% bound to Hb, 7% dissolved. Chloride shift moves HCO3- out of RBCs."},
{id:"bs25",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Digestive System","Hormones","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Cholecystokinin (CCK) is released in response to:",o:["Fats and proteins in the duodenum","Carbohydrates in the stomach","Low blood glucose","High blood pH"],a:0,ex:"Major GI hormones: CCK: released from I cells of duodenum in response to fats and proteins. Stimulates gallbladder contraction (bile release for fat emulsification), pancreatic enzyme secretion, and slows gastric emptying. Secretin: released from S cells when acidic chyme enters duodenum. Stimulates pancreatic bicarbonate secretion (neutralizes acid) and inhibits gastric acid. Gastrin: released from G cells of stomach in response to distension and peptides. Stimulates HCl secretion from parietal cells.",mn:"CCK = fats/proteins -> bile + pancreatic enzymes. Secretin = acid -> bicarb. Gastrin = stimulates HCl."},
{id:"bs26",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Endocrine System","Hormones","Cardiovascular System"],diff:2,q:"Parathyroid hormone (PTH) increases blood calcium by:",o:["Stimulating osteoclast bone resorption + renal Ca2+ reabsorption + vitamin D activation","Inhibiting osteoclasts","Promoting calcium excretion","Decreasing vitamin D"],a:0,ex:"PTH is released when blood Ca2+ is LOW. Three actions to raise Ca2+: (1) Stimulates osteoclast activity -> releases Ca2+ and phosphate from bone. (2) Increases renal Ca2+ reabsorption in the DCT (and promotes phosphate excretion). (3) Stimulates 1-alpha-hydroxylase in the kidney to convert 25-OH vitamin D to active 1,25-(OH)2 vitamin D (calcitriol), which increases intestinal Ca2+ absorption. Calcitonin (from thyroid C cells) opposes PTH by inhibiting osteoclasts (lowers Ca2+). PTH and calcitonin form a negative feedback loop.",mn:"PTH raises Ca2+: bone resorption + kidney reabsorption + vitamin D activation. Calcitonin lowers Ca2+."},
{id:"bs27",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Autonomic","Nervous System","Neurotransmitters"],diff:2,q:"The parasympathetic nervous system is associated with:",o:["Rest and digest responses (decreased heart rate, increased digestion)","Fight or flight","Increased heart rate","Bronchodilation"],a:0,ex:"The autonomic nervous system has two divisions: SYMPATHETIC (fight or flight): increased HR, BP, bronchodilation, pupil dilation, glycogenolysis, decreased digestion. Uses NE at most targets. PARASYMPATHETIC (rest and digest): decreased HR, increased digestion/secretion, pupil constriction, bronchoconstriction. Uses ACh at all targets. Key parasympathetic nerve: vagus nerve (CN X) -- innervates heart, lungs, GI tract. Parasympathetic effects dominate at rest; sympathetic during stress/exercise.",mn:"Para = rest and digest = slow heart, increase digestion. Symp = fight or flight. Vagus = main para nerve."},
{id:"gc16",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Buffers","Acid-Base","Solutions"],diff:2,q:"A buffer made from acetic acid (pKa 4.76) and sodium acetate would work best at pH:",o:["~4.76","~7.0","~2.0","~10.0"],a:0,ex:"A buffer works best within +/-1 pH unit of the weak acid's pKa. Acetic acid pKa = 4.76, so this buffer is effective from about pH 3.76 to 5.76. At pH = pKa, the ratio [A-]/[HA] = 1:1 (maximum buffering). If you need to buffer at pH 7.4 (physiological), choose a different acid -- like H2PO4-/HPO42- (pKa 7.2) or HEPES (pKa 7.5). Blood uses the bicarbonate buffer system (H2CO3/HCO3-, effective pKa 6.1, maintained by the lungs adjusting CO2).",mn:"Buffer pH should match pKa. Acetic acid pKa 4.76 = best buffer around pH 4.76."},
{id:"gc17",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics","Equilibrium","Chemical Kinetics"],diff:2,q:"A catalyst affects a reaction by:",o:["Lowering the activation energy without changing delta-G or Keq","Changing Keq","Making the reaction more exothermic","Shifting equilibrium toward products"],a:0,ex:"A catalyst provides an alternative reaction pathway with a LOWER activation energy (Ea), increasing the rate of both forward and reverse reactions equally. It does NOT change: delta-G (thermodynamics), Keq (equilibrium constant), or delta-H. It DOES change: rate of reaction (kinetics), activation energy. Enzymes are biological catalysts that can lower Ea by factors of 10^6 to 10^12. They use strategies like proximity/orientation, acid-base catalysis, covalent catalysis, and metal ion catalysis.",mn:"Catalyst lowers Ea but does not change delta-G or Keq. Speeds up BOTH directions equally."},
{id:"gc18",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Equilibrium","Thermodynamics"],diff:3,q:"At equilibrium, which statement is TRUE?",o:["Forward and reverse rates are equal; concentrations are constant","All reactions have stopped","Concentrations of products and reactants are equal","Delta-G = delta-G-standard"],a:0,ex:"At equilibrium: the forward rate equals the reverse rate (dynamic equilibrium -- reactions continue but no NET change). Concentrations are CONSTANT but NOT necessarily equal. delta-G = 0 (no free energy available to drive the reaction in either direction). Q = K (reaction quotient equals equilibrium constant). Note: delta-G-standard is NOT zero at equilibrium -- it is delta-G (actual) that is zero. delta-G-standard is a fixed value determined by the nature of the reaction at standard conditions.",mn:"At equilibrium: rates equal, delta-G = 0, Q = K. Concentrations constant but NOT equal."},
{id:"gc19",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Intermolecular Forces","Solutions","Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"Dissolving NaCl in water is favorable primarily because of:",o:["Strong ion-dipole interactions with water molecules","Covalent bonds forming","Decreased entropy","Van der Waals forces"],a:0,ex:"When NaCl dissolves, Na+ and Cl- ions separate and become surrounded by water molecules (hydration/solvation). The energetics: (1) Breaking the ionic lattice requires energy (lattice energy, unfavorable). (2) Ion-dipole interactions between Na+/Cl- and water release energy (hydration energy, favorable). (3) Entropy increases (more disorder). For NaCl, the hydration energy + entropy increase outweigh the lattice energy, so dissolution is spontaneous. Like dissolves like: ionic and polar solutes dissolve in polar solvents, nonpolar solutes in nonpolar solvents.",mn:"Ion-dipole interactions drive salt dissolution. Lattice energy vs hydration energy. Like dissolves like."},
{id:"gc20",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Redox Chemistry","Thermodynamics"],diff:3,q:"In electrolysis of water, which reaction occurs at the anode?",o:["Oxidation: 2H2O -> O2 + 4H+ + 4e-","Reduction: 2H2O -> H2 + 2OH-","No reaction","Both oxidation and reduction"],a:0,ex:"Electrolysis is a non-spontaneous process that uses external electrical energy. At the ANODE (always oxidation, AnOx): water is oxidized to produce O2 gas. At the CATHODE (always reduction, RedCat): water is reduced to produce H2 gas. In electrolytic cells, the anode is positive (connected to + terminal of power source, attracts anions). In galvanic cells, the anode is negative (electrons flow away from it). This sign flip between galvanic and electrolytic cells is commonly tested.",mn:"Electrolysis anode = oxidation = O2 produced. Cathode = reduction = H2. Anode sign flips between galvanic/electrolytic."},
{id:"gc21",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Atomic Structure","Intermolecular Forces"],diff:2,q:"Electronegativity increases:",o:["Up and to the right on the periodic table (toward fluorine)","Down and to the left","Only in metals","Randomly"],a:0,ex:"Electronegativity (EN) measures how strongly an atom attracts bonding electrons. Trend: increases going RIGHT across a period (more protons pulling electrons) and UP within a group (electrons closer to nucleus, less shielding). Fluorine is the most electronegative element (EN = 4.0). EN determines bond polarity: large EN difference = polar bond (or ionic if > 1.7). Small EN difference = nonpolar covalent. Important for predicting molecular polarity, IMFs, and reactivity.",mn:"EN increases right and up. F is most electronegative. Large EN difference = polar/ionic bond."},
{id:"gc22",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Chemical Kinetics","Enzyme Regulation"],diff:2,q:"Zero-order reaction rate:",o:["Is constant regardless of [reactant]","Doubles when [A] doubles","Depends on [A] squared","Is always zero"],a:0,ex:"Zero order: rate = k (constant, independent of concentration). The rate stays the same until reactant is depleted, then drops to zero suddenly. Graph of [A] vs time is a straight line. Half-life = [A]0/2k (depends on initial concentration). Example: enzyme-catalyzed reactions at saturating substrate (Vmax region -- rate is constant because all active sites are occupied). Alcohol metabolism by alcohol dehydrogenase follows zero-order kinetics at typical drinking levels.",mn:"Zero order: rate = k (constant). Straight line on [A] vs time. Vmax region of enzymes. Alcohol metabolism."},
{id:"org13",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Functional Groups","Carbonyl Chemistry","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"Rank acidity: carboxylic acid > phenol > alcohol. This is because:",o:["Their conjugate bases are stabilized by decreasing amounts of resonance","Molecular weight determines acidity","Electronegativity of carbon increases","They all have the same pKa"],a:0,ex:"Acidity relates to how well the conjugate base is stabilized: Carboxylic acid (pKa ~4-5): conjugate base (carboxylate, RCOO-) has resonance stabilization over TWO equivalent oxygens. Phenol (pKa ~10): conjugate base (phenoxide) has resonance with the aromatic ring but charge is delocalized less effectively. Alcohol (pKa ~16): conjugate base (alkoxide, RO-) has NO resonance stabilization, charge localized on one oxygen. More resonance = more stable conjugate base = stronger acid = lower pKa.",mn:"More resonance in conjugate base = stronger acid. RCOOH > PhOH > ROH."},
{id:"org14",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Stereochemistry","Substitution Reactions","Elimination Reactions"],diff:2,q:"What determines whether a reaction follows SN1/SN2/E1/E2?",o:["Substrate degree, nucleophile/base strength, and solvent","Temperature only","Pressure only","Molecular weight"],a:0,ex:"Decision framework: (1) SUBSTRATE: methyl/1-degree favors SN2; 3-degree favors SN1/E1/E2. 2-degree can go any way. (2) NUCLEOPHILE/BASE: strong nuc favors SN2; strong bulky base favors E2; weak nuc favors SN1; weak base + heat favors E1. (3) SOLVENT: polar protic favors SN1/E1 (stabilizes carbocation); polar aprotic favors SN2 (keeps nuc reactive). (4) TEMPERATURE: heat favors elimination over substitution. This framework is among the most tested organic chemistry concepts on the MCAT.",mn:"Substrate + nucleophile/base + solvent = determines SN1/SN2/E1/E2. MEMORIZE this framework."},
{id:"org15",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Addition Reactions","Stereochemistry","Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"Catalytic hydrogenation (H2/Pd) adds hydrogen:",o:["Syn (both H's add to same face)","Anti (H's add to opposite faces)","Randomly","Only to carbonyls"],a:0,ex:"H2/Pd (or Pt or Ni) reduces C=C double bonds to C-C single bonds. The mechanism: both H atoms are adsorbed onto the metal surface and delivered to the SAME face of the double bond simultaneously (syn addition). This has stereochemical consequences -- if the starting alkene has substituents, the product will have a specific stereochemistry based on syn addition. Compare: halogenation (Br2) is ANTI addition (Br's add to opposite faces via cyclic bromonium ion intermediate).",mn:"H2/Pd = syn addition (same face). Br2 = anti addition (opposite faces)."},
{id:"org16",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Elimination Reactions","Functional Groups"],diff:2,q:"E1 elimination is favored by:",o:["3-degree substrate, weak base, polar protic, heat","1-degree, strong base","Methyl substrate","Polar aprotic solvent"],a:0,ex:"E1 is a two-step mechanism: (1) leaving group departs forming carbocation (rate-determining), (2) base removes a beta-proton forming the double bond. Needs: stable carbocation (3-degree), weak base (strong base would push E2), polar protic solvent (stabilizes carbocation), and heat (favors elimination over substitution). E1 typically competes with SN1 (same conditions), and heat shifts the balance toward elimination. E1 follows Zaitsev's rule (more substituted alkene is major product).",mn:"E1 = carbocation + weak base + protic + heat. Competes with SN1. Heat favors elimination."},
{id:"ph13",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Waves and Sound","Optics"],diff:2,q:"The electromagnetic spectrum from lowest to highest energy:",o:["Radio, microwave, IR, visible, UV, X-ray, gamma","Gamma, X-ray, UV, visible, IR, microwave, radio","Visible, UV, IR, radio, gamma","Random order"],a:0,ex:"EM waves travel at the speed of light (c = 3 x 10^8 m/s). E = hf = hc/lambda. Low frequency = low energy = long wavelength. Order of increasing energy (decreasing wavelength): Radio < Microwave < Infrared < Visible (ROYGBIV, red lowest to violet highest) < Ultraviolet < X-ray < Gamma. Medical applications: X-rays (imaging), gamma rays (radiation therapy), UV (skin damage), IR (thermal imaging), radio (MRI). Visible light: ~400nm (violet) to ~700nm (red).",mn:"Low to high energy: Radio, Micro, IR, Visible, UV, X-ray, Gamma. E = hf = hc/lambda."},
{id:"ph14",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Bernoulli's Principle"],diff:2,q:"Pressure at depth in a fluid equals:",o:["P = P_atm + rho*g*h","P = rho*g only","P = F/A only","P = mgh"],a:0,ex:"Hydrostatic pressure increases linearly with depth: P = P_surface + rho*g*h, where rho is fluid density, g is gravitational acceleration, and h is depth below the surface. At the surface (h=0), P = P_atm. Key points: pressure depends only on depth (not container shape -- Pascal's vases), pressure acts equally in all directions at a given depth (Pascal's law), and 1 atm = 101,325 Pa = 760 mmHg. In blood pressure: hydrostatic pressure from standing creates ~90 mmHg difference between head and feet.",mn:"P = P_atm + rho*g*h. Depends on depth only, not shape. Acts equally in all directions."},
{id:"ph15",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Circuits","Electrostatics","Work and Energy"],diff:2,q:"Power dissipated by a resistor:",o:["P = IV = I^2R = V^2/R","P = IR","P = QV","P = Fd/t only"],a:0,ex:"Three equivalent forms: P = IV (general, current times voltage), P = I^2R (useful when current is known), P = V^2/R (useful when voltage is known). These come from combining P = IV with Ohm's law (V = IR). Units: watts (W = J/s). In circuits: total power from battery = sum of power dissipated by all resistors. In series: same current, so P = I^2R (larger R dissipates more power). In parallel: same voltage, so P = V^2/R (smaller R dissipates more power).",mn:"P = IV = I^2R = V^2/R. Series: larger R = more power. Parallel: smaller R = more power."},
{id:"ph16",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound"],diff:3,q:"The index of refraction n equals:",o:["c/v (speed of light in vacuum / speed in medium)","v/c","wavelength ratio","frequency ratio"],a:0,ex:"n = c/v. Since v in a medium is always less than c, n is always >= 1. Higher n means light travels SLOWER. Water n=1.33, glass n~1.5, diamond n=2.42. Snell's law: n1*sin(theta1) = n2*sin(theta2). When light enters a denser medium (higher n), it bends TOWARD the normal and slows down. Wavelength decreases in denser medium (lambda = lambda_0/n) but frequency stays the same. Total internal reflection occurs when going from high n to low n at angle > critical angle.",mn:"n = c/v. Higher n = slower light = bends toward normal. Diamond n = 2.42 (lots of TIR = sparkle)."},
{id:"ph17",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Work and Energy","Fluids"],diff:2,q:"Conservation of energy states:",o:["Total energy in an isolated system remains constant","Energy can be created","Energy can be destroyed","Entropy always decreases"],a:0,ex:"First law of thermodynamics: energy cannot be created or destroyed, only transformed. In mechanics: KE + PE = constant (when only conservative forces act). KE (1/2mv^2) converts to PE (mgh) and back -- a ball at the top of a hill has max PE, at the bottom has max KE. When non-conservative forces (friction) act, mechanical energy converts to heat. In thermodynamics: delta-U = Q - W (internal energy change = heat added minus work done by system).",mn:"Energy is conserved. KE + PE = constant (no friction). delta-U = Q - W."},
{id:"ph18",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Nuclear Physics","Atomic Structure"],diff:2,q:"Alpha decay releases:",o:["A helium nucleus (2 protons + 2 neutrons)","An electron","A positron","A gamma ray only"],a:0,ex:"Radioactive decay types: ALPHA: emits He-4 nucleus (2p+2n). Atomic number Z decreases by 2, mass number A decreases by 4. Heavy nuclei (uranium, radium). Low penetration (stopped by paper). BETA-MINUS: neutron -> proton + electron + antineutrino. Z increases by 1, A unchanged. BETA-PLUS: proton -> neutron + positron + neutrino. Z decreases by 1. GAMMA: high-energy photon, no mass/charge change, often accompanies other decay. High penetration (stopped by lead/concrete). ELECTRON CAPTURE: inner electron captured by nucleus, similar result to beta-plus.",mn:"Alpha = He nucleus (Z-2, A-4). Beta- = electron (Z+1). Beta+ = positron (Z-1). Gamma = photon (no change)."},
{id:"ps23",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Learning and Conditioning","Developmental Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Bandura's social learning theory emphasizes:",o:["Observational learning (modeling behavior seen in others)","Classical conditioning only","Operant conditioning only","Biological instincts"],a:0,ex:"Albert Bandura's Bobo doll experiment (1961): children who watched an adult behave aggressively toward an inflatable doll later imitated that behavior, even without direct reinforcement. This demonstrated observational learning (also called modeling or social learning). Four steps: ATTENTION (notice the behavior), RETENTION (remember it), REPRODUCTION (ability to perform it), MOTIVATION (reason to do it -- vicarious reinforcement helps). This theory bridges behaviorism and cognitivism by showing that learning can occur WITHOUT direct reinforcement, challenging strict operant conditioning views.",mn:"Bandura: watch others -> imitate. Bobo doll. Attention -> Retention -> Reproduction -> Motivation."},
{id:"ps24",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,q:"Long-term potentiation (LTP) is:",o:["Strengthening of synaptic connections with repeated use","Weakening of synapses over time","A type of short-term memory","Forgetting due to interference"],a:0,ex:"LTP is the cellular mechanism believed to underlie learning and memory. When a synapse is repeatedly stimulated, the postsynaptic neuron increases its response -- the connection gets stronger. Molecular mechanism: repeated stimulation activates NMDA receptors -> Ca2+ influx -> insertion of more AMPA receptors -> stronger response to future stimulation. LTP primarily occurs in the hippocampus (critical for forming new declarative memories). Long-term depression (LTD) is the opposite -- weakening of synaptic connections with low-frequency stimulation.",mn:"LTP = repeated use strengthens synapse (hippocampus). NMDA + Ca2+ + more AMPA = stronger connection."},
{id:"ps25",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception","Developmental Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Signal detection theory accounts for:",o:["Both stimulus sensitivity and response bias (criterion)","Absolute threshold only","Adaptation only","Weber's law only"],a:0,ex:"Signal detection theory recognizes that detecting a stimulus is not purely about sensory ability -- DECISION-MAKING matters too. Two factors: (1) Sensitivity (d-prime): the observer's actual ability to distinguish signal from noise. (2) Response bias/criterion: the observer's willingness to say 'yes, I detect it' (influenced by expectations, consequences, motivation). Four outcomes: Hit (signal present, say yes), Miss (signal present, say no), False alarm (no signal, say yes), Correct rejection (no signal, say no). A radiologist reading mammograms faces this: setting a liberal criterion catches more cancers but also more false alarms.",mn:"SDT: detection = sensitivity + bias. Hits, misses, false alarms, correct rejections."},
{id:"ps26",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Emotion Theories","Brain Anatomy","Nervous System"],diff:2,q:"The limbic system includes the:",o:["Amygdala (fear/emotion), hippocampus (memory), and hypothalamus","Cerebellum only","Frontal lobe only","Brainstem only"],a:0,ex:"The limbic system is a group of interconnected structures involved in emotion, memory, and motivation. Key components: AMYGDALA: processes fear and emotional memories. Damage = cannot recognize fear in faces. HIPPOCAMPUS: forms new declarative (explicit) memories. Damage = anterograde amnesia (cannot form new memories, e.g., patient HM). HYPOTHALAMUS: controls homeostasis, hunger, thirst, temperature, circadian rhythms, and links nervous to endocrine system (releases hormones to anterior pituitary). Other limbic structures: cingulate cortex (emotional regulation), fornix, mammillary bodies.",mn:"Amygdala = fear. Hippocampus = new memories. Hypothalamus = homeostasis + endocrine link."},
{id:"ps27",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology","Health Disparities","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Medicalization refers to:",o:["Defining non-medical problems as medical conditions requiring treatment","Reducing access to healthcare","Eliminating disease","Improving health outcomes only"],a:0,ex:"Medicalization is the process by which human conditions or behaviors become defined as medical problems requiring medical solutions. Examples: ADHD (childhood energy/inattention -> disorder requiring medication), obesity (body size -> disease), alcoholism (moral failing -> brain disease), childbirth (natural process -> medical event requiring hospital). Can be positive (reduces stigma, provides treatment) or negative (overdiagnosis, pharmaceutical profits, loss of agency, ignoring social causes). Sociologists argue medicalization reflects power dynamics -- who gets to define 'normal' and 'pathological'?",mn:"Medicalization = non-medical becomes medical. Can help (treatment) or harm (overdiagnosis, power dynamics)."},
{id:"ps28",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Moral Development","Developmental Psychology","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Gilligan criticized Kohlberg's theory because:",o:["It was based on male subjects and undervalued care-based morality","It was too focused on emotions","It ignored punishment","It only studied children"],a:0,ex:"Carol Gilligan argued that Kohlberg's stages were biased toward a JUSTICE orientation (rights, rules, abstract principles) that is more typical of male moral reasoning. She proposed that women tend toward a CARE orientation (relationships, responsibility, compassion). Her stages: (1) Preconventional: caring for self, (2) Conventional: caring for others (self-sacrifice), (3) Postconventional: balancing care for self AND others. Gilligan did not argue women are morally inferior -- rather that Kohlberg's scale measured one type of morality and missed another equally valid type.",mn:"Gilligan: Kohlberg was male-biased. Justice vs care orientations. Both valid, different approaches."},
{id:"ps29",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sleep","Brain Anatomy","Sensation and Perception"],diff:2,q:"The suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) regulates:",o:["Circadian rhythm (24-hour biological clock)","Hunger only","Fear responses","Language production"],a:0,ex:"The SCN in the hypothalamus is the master circadian pacemaker. It receives light input from the retina (via retinohypothalamic tract) and synchronizes the body's 24-hour rhythms: sleep-wake cycle, hormone release (cortisol peaks in morning, melatonin peaks at night), body temperature, metabolism. The SCN signals the pineal gland to produce MELATONIN in darkness (promotes sleep). Jet lag occurs when the SCN is out of sync with the external light-dark cycle. Shift workers have disrupted circadian rhythms linked to higher rates of cardiovascular disease and cancer.",mn:"SCN = master clock in hypothalamus. Light input -> melatonin at night. Disruption -> health problems."},
{id:"mb12",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation","Gene Regulation"],diff:2,q:"The start codon AUG codes for:",o:["Methionine (and initiates translation)","Stop signal","Leucine","Any amino acid"],a:0,ex:"AUG serves dual functions: (1) it is the universal START codon that initiates translation in both prokaryotes and eukaryotes, and (2) it codes for methionine (Met/M). In prokaryotes, the initiator Met is formylated (fMet). Translation begins when the small ribosomal subunit binds mRNA and scans for AUG (in eukaryotes, Kozak sequence helps; in prokaryotes, Shine-Dalgarno sequence positions ribosome). The three STOP codons (UAA, UAG, UGA) do NOT code for amino acids -- they are recognized by release factors that terminate translation.",mn:"AUG = start = methionine. UAA/UAG/UGA = stop (release factors, no amino acid)."},
{id:"mb13",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["DNA Replication","Mutations","Gene Regulation"],diff:3,q:"DNA mismatch repair fixes errors that escape:",o:["Proofreading by DNA polymerase (3' to 5' exonuclease)","Transcription errors","Translation errors","Protein folding errors"],a:0,ex:"DNA repair systems form multiple layers of defense: (1) PROOFREADING: DNA polymerase's 3'-to-5' exonuclease immediately removes mismatched nucleotides during replication (error rate: 1/10^5 -> 1/10^7). (2) MISMATCH REPAIR (MMR): MutS/MutL (in E. coli; MSH/MLH in humans) scan newly replicated DNA for mismatches and fix them (improves to 1/10^9). (3) BASE EXCISION REPAIR: glycosylases remove damaged bases (deaminated, oxidized). (4) NUCLEOTIDE EXCISION REPAIR: removes bulky lesions like thymine dimers (UV damage) -- defective in xeroderma pigmentosum. Lynch syndrome = defective MMR -> increased colon cancer risk.",mn:"Layers: proofreading -> mismatch repair -> base/nucleotide excision repair. Lynch syndrome = MMR defect."},
{id:"mb14",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Transcription/Translation","Gene Regulation"],diff:2,q:"RNA polymerase differs from DNA polymerase because RNA pol:",o:["Does not need a primer and uses ribonucleotides","Needs a primer","Uses deoxyribonucleotides","Has proofreading ability"],a:0,ex:"Key differences: RNA polymerase does NOT need a primer (can initiate de novo), uses ribonucleotides (A, U, G, C instead of A, T, G, C), synthesizes 5' to 3' (same as DNA pol), reads template 3' to 5' (same), does NOT have proofreading activity (higher error rate than DNA pol, but RNA is expendable -- errors in mRNA are temporary). In prokaryotes: one RNA polymerase for all RNA types. In eukaryotes: RNA Pol I (rRNA), RNA Pol II (mRNA -- inhibited by alpha-amanitin from death cap mushroom), RNA Pol III (tRNA, 5S rRNA).",mn:"RNA pol: no primer, uses ribonucleotides (U not T), no proofreading. Eu: Pol I=rRNA, II=mRNA, III=tRNA."},
{id:"met28",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Anaerobic Metabolism","ATP Yield"],diff:1,q:"Net ATP produced by glycolysis per glucose:",o:["2 ATP","4 ATP","36 ATP","0 ATP"],a:0,ex:"Glycolysis uses 2 ATP (hexokinase and PFK-1 steps) and produces 4 ATP (phosphoglycerate kinase and pyruvate kinase steps) by substrate-level phosphorylation. Net = 4 - 2 = 2 ATP. Also produces 2 NADH (at GAPDH step) which yield ~5 more ATP if shuttled to ETC. Glycolysis occurs in the CYTOPLASM, requires no oxygen, and is the universal pathway -- all cells use it.",mn:"Glycolysis: invest 2 ATP, earn 4 ATP, net = 2 ATP + 2 NADH. Cytoplasm. No O2 needed."},
{id:"met29",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Krebs Cycle","Aerobic Respiration","Electron Carriers"],diff:2,q:"Acetyl-CoA enters the Krebs cycle by combining with:",o:["Oxaloacetate (to form citrate)","Pyruvate","Glucose","Succinate"],a:0,ex:"Citrate synthase catalyzes: acetyl-CoA (2C) + oxaloacetate (4C) -> citrate (6C). This is the first step of the Krebs cycle. OAA is regenerated at the end of each cycle (by malate dehydrogenase). When OAA is depleted (e.g., diverted to gluconeogenesis during fasting), acetyl-CoA cannot enter the Krebs cycle and is shunted to ketogenesis instead. This is the metabolic basis for ketone body production during starvation.",mn:"Acetyl-CoA + OAA = citrate (first Krebs step). Low OAA = ketogenesis."},
{id:"met30",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Krebs Cycle","Electron Transport Chain","Aerobic Respiration"],diff:2,q:"Which Krebs cycle enzyme is also part of the ETC?",o:["Succinate dehydrogenase (Complex II)","Citrate synthase","Isocitrate dehydrogenase","Malate dehydrogenase"],a:0,ex:"Succinate dehydrogenase is unique: it is both a Krebs cycle enzyme (oxidizes succinate to fumarate, producing FADH2) and Complex II of the ETC (passes electrons from FADH2 to CoQ). It is the only Krebs enzyme embedded in the inner mitochondrial membrane rather than free in the matrix. This direct connection between Krebs and ETC makes succinate dehydrogenase a useful experimental tool for studying electron transport.",mn:"Succinate dehydrogenase = Krebs enzyme AND Complex II. Only membrane-bound Krebs enzyme."},
{id:"met31",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Hormonal Regulation","Insulin","Glucagon"],diff:2,q:"During the fed state, high insulin-to-glucagon ratio promotes:",o:["Glycolysis, glycogen synthesis, lipogenesis","Gluconeogenesis, glycogenolysis, ketogenesis","Beta-oxidation and protein degradation","Fasting metabolic pathways"],a:0,ex:"The insulin-to-glucagon ratio is the master metabolic switch. HIGH ratio (fed state, after a meal): insulin dominates, promoting ANABOLIC pathways -- glycolysis, glycogen synthesis, fatty acid synthesis (lipogenesis), protein synthesis. LOW ratio (fasting, between meals): glucagon dominates, promoting CATABOLIC pathways -- glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis, lipolysis, beta-oxidation, ketogenesis. The MCAT loves testing which pathways are active in fed vs fasting states.",mn:"High insulin/glucagon = fed = build and store. Low ratio = fasting = break down and mobilize."},
{id:"met32",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Electron Transport Chain","Aerobic Respiration","Oxidative Phosphorylation"],diff:3,q:"Antimycin A blocks which ETC complex?",o:["Complex III","Complex I","Complex II","Complex IV"],a:0,ex:"ETC inhibitors to know: Rotenone/barbiturates = Complex I. Antimycin A = Complex III (blocks electron transfer from cytochrome b to cytochrome c1). Cyanide/CO = Complex IV. Oligomycin = ATP synthase (blocks proton channel, not technically an ETC complex). All ETC inhibitors STOP electron flow and DECREASE O2 consumption. Uncouplers (DNP, thermogenin) are different -- they INCREASE O2 consumption by dissipating the gradient as heat.",mn:"Rotenone=I, Antimycin=III, Cyanide/CO=IV, Oligomycin=ATP synthase. Uncouplers are different!"},
{id:"aa19",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Isoelectric Point","Acid-Base","Amino Acid Classification"],diff:3,q:"At pH 1, the net charge on alanine (pI ~6.0) is:",o:["Positive (fully protonated)","Negative","Zero","No charge at all"],a:0,ex:"At pH well BELOW the pI, all ionizable groups are protonated. For alanine at pH 1: alpha-NH2 is protonated to NH3+ (positive), alpha-COOH is protonated (neutral, not negative). Net charge = +1. Rule: pH < pI = positive charge (molecule migrates toward cathode in electrophoresis). pH > pI = negative charge (migrates toward anode). pH = pI = zero net charge (does not migrate). This rule applies to all amino acids AND proteins.",mn:"pH < pI = positive charge. pH > pI = negative. pH = pI = zero. Works for all AAs and proteins."},
{id:"aa20",cat:"AMINO_ACIDS",tags:["Essential Amino Acids","Amino Acid Properties","Metabolism"],diff:2,q:"Branched-chain amino acids (BCAAs) are:",o:["Leucine, isoleucine, and valine","Alanine, glycine, serine","Aspartate, glutamate","Proline, histidine"],a:0,ex:"Leucine (L), Isoleucine (I), and Valine (V) have branched aliphatic side chains. All three are essential, nonpolar, and hydrophobic. Unique feature: BCAAs are metabolized primarily in SKELETAL MUSCLE (not liver like most AAs). They are used as fuel during exercise and promote protein synthesis (leucine is especially potent at activating mTOR pathway). Maple syrup urine disease is caused by deficiency of branched-chain alpha-keto acid dehydrogenase, leading to accumulation of BCAAs and their metabolites.",mn:"BCAAs = Leu, Ile, Val. All essential. Metabolized in muscle. Maple syrup urine disease = BCAA buildup."},
{id:"cb17",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Apoptosis","Cell Death","Tumor Suppressors"],diff:3,q:"The intrinsic pathway of apoptosis is triggered by:",o:["Mitochondrial release of cytochrome c","Death receptor binding (Fas ligand)","Viral infection only","Complement activation"],a:0,ex:"Two apoptosis pathways: INTRINSIC (mitochondrial): cellular stress (DNA damage, oxidative stress, growth factor withdrawal) -> pro-apoptotic proteins (BAX, BAK) form pores in mitochondrial outer membrane -> cytochrome c released -> binds Apaf-1 -> forms apoptosome -> activates caspase-9 (initiator) -> activates caspase-3 (effector) -> cell death. EXTRINSIC (death receptor): extracellular death ligands (FasL, TNF) bind death receptors (Fas, TNFR) -> FADD adaptor -> activates caspase-8 -> caspase-3 -> death. Both converge on caspase-3. p53 promotes intrinsic pathway via BAX/PUMA.",mn:"Intrinsic = mitochondria -> cytochrome c -> caspase-9 -> caspase-3. Extrinsic = death receptors -> caspase-8 -> caspase-3."},
{id:"cb18",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Mitosis","Cell Cycle","Organelles"],diff:2,q:"During which phase does DNA replication occur?",o:["S phase (synthesis)","G1 phase","G2 phase","M phase"],a:0,ex:"Cell cycle phases: G1 (Gap 1): cell grows, prepares for DNA synthesis. S (Synthesis): DNA replication (chromosomes go from 1 chromatid to 2 sister chromatids each, DNA content doubles from 2n to 4n). G2 (Gap 2): cell grows more, checks for replication errors, prepares for mitosis. M (Mitosis): nuclear division (PMAT) + cytokinesis. G0: quiescent state (non-dividing cells like neurons, muscle). G1/S is the main checkpoint. Cyclin-CDK complexes drive transitions between phases.",mn:"G1 = grow. S = DNA synthesis. G2 = prepare. M = divide. G0 = quiescent."},
{id:"cb19",cat:"CELL_BIO",tags:["Signal Transduction","Membrane Transport","Organelles"],diff:3,q:"Second messengers include:",o:["cAMP, IP3, DAG, Ca2+","Receptors, ligands","Transcription factors only","ATP only"],a:0,ex:"Second messengers are small intracellular signaling molecules produced in response to an extracellular signal (first messenger = hormone/neurotransmitter). Key second messengers: cAMP (made by adenylyl cyclase, activates PKA, degraded by phosphodiesterase), IP3 (releases Ca2+ from ER), DAG (activates PKC), Ca2+ (activates calmodulin-dependent kinases, triggers muscle contraction/secretion), cGMP (made by guanylyl cyclase, activates PKG, used in NO signaling for vasodilation). They amplify signals: one receptor -> many second messenger molecules -> huge cellular response.",mn:"cAMP, IP3, DAG, Ca2+, cGMP. They AMPLIFY signals. One receptor -> many messenger molecules."},
{id:"gen15",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Meiosis","Genetic Diversity","Inheritance Patterns"],diff:2,q:"Independent assortment occurs during:",o:["Metaphase I (homologs align randomly)","S phase","Prophase II","Cytokinesis"],a:0,ex:"Mendel's Law of Independent Assortment: genes on DIFFERENT chromosomes (or far apart on the same chromosome) sort independently during meiosis I. At metaphase I, each pair of homologous chromosomes aligns randomly at the metaphase plate -- maternal or paternal homolog can face either pole. With 23 chromosome pairs: 2^23 = 8,388,608 possible arrangements. This is one of three sources of genetic diversity (with crossing over and random fertilization). Linked genes (close together on same chromosome) do NOT assort independently -- they tend to be inherited together.",mn:"Metaphase I: random alignment of homologs. 2^23 possible arrangements. Linked genes do NOT assort independently."},
{id:"gen16",cat:"GENETICS",tags:["Chromosomal Abnormalities","Meiosis","Population Genetics"],diff:2,q:"Klinefelter syndrome karyotype is:",o:["47,XXY (male with extra X)","45,X","47,XXX","46,XY"],a:0,ex:"Common sex chromosome aneuploidies: Klinefelter (47,XXY): phenotypically male, tall, infertile (small testes, low testosterone), may have gynecomastia. Caused by nondisjunction. Turner (45,X): phenotypically female, short stature, webbed neck, infertile (streak gonads), coarctation of aorta. Only monosomy compatible with life. Triple X (47,XXX): female, usually no symptoms, may have learning difficulties. XYY (47,XYY): male, tall, usually no significant symptoms.",mn:"Klinefelter=47,XXY (male, tall, infertile). Turner=45,X (female, short). Both = nondisjunction."},
{id:"bs28",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hemoglobin","Respiratory System","Cardiovascular System"],diff:3,q:"Fetal hemoglobin (HbF) has higher O2 affinity than adult Hb because:",o:["HbF binds 2,3-BPG less strongly","HbF has more subunits","HbF is larger","HbF has higher pI"],a:0,ex:"Fetal hemoglobin has gamma chains instead of beta chains (alpha2-gamma2 vs alpha2-beta2). The gamma chain binds 2,3-BPG less effectively. Since 2,3-BPG normally decreases Hb's O2 affinity (by stabilizing T-state), less BPG binding means HbF stays more in the R-state (high affinity). On the O2 dissociation curve, HbF is LEFT-shifted relative to adult HbA. This allows the fetus to extract O2 from maternal blood across the placenta -- fetal Hb grabs O2 that maternal Hb releases.",mn:"HbF gamma chains bind less 2,3-BPG = higher affinity = left shift. Fetus pulls O2 from mother."},
{id:"bs29",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Nervous System","Autonomic"],diff:2,q:"Baroreceptors in the carotid sinus detect:",o:["Changes in blood pressure (stretch)","Blood oxygen levels","Blood glucose","Body temperature"],a:0,ex:"Baroreceptors are stretch receptors in the carotid sinus and aortic arch walls. When BP rises, vessel walls stretch more -> increased baroreceptor firing -> signals sent via glossopharyngeal (CN IX, carotid) and vagus (CN X, aortic arch) nerves to the medulla -> PARASYMPATHETIC activation (vagus slows heart) + SYMPATHETIC inhibition -> HR decreases, vasodilation -> BP returns to normal. When BP drops: less stretching -> less firing -> sympathetic activation -> HR increases, vasoconstriction -> BP rises. This is a negative feedback loop for short-term BP regulation.",mn:"Baroreceptors: high BP -> more firing -> para up, symp down -> BP drops. Negative feedback."},
{id:"bs30",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Digestive System","Hormonal Regulation","Autonomic"],diff:2,q:"Parietal cells in the stomach secrete:",o:["HCl and intrinsic factor","Pepsinogen","Mucus","Gastrin"],a:0,ex:"Gastric cell types: PARIETAL cells: secrete HCl (via H+/K+ ATPase, the proton pump) and intrinsic factor (essential for vitamin B12 absorption in the ileum). CHIEF cells: secrete pepsinogen (activated to pepsin by HCl). MUCOUS cells: secrete mucus and bicarbonate (protective barrier against self-digestion). G cells: secrete gastrin (stimulates HCl production). Clinical: PPIs (omeprazole) block the proton pump -> reduce acid. B12 deficiency can result from parietal cell loss (pernicious anemia = autoimmune destruction of parietal cells).",mn:"Parietal = HCl + intrinsic factor. Chief = pepsinogen. G cells = gastrin. PPIs block proton pump."},
{id:"bs31",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Immune System","Hematology","Cardiovascular System"],diff:2,q:"Neutrophils are the first responders to:",o:["Bacterial infection (innate immunity)","Viral infection only","Parasitic infection","Allergic reactions"],a:0,ex:"Neutrophils are the most abundant white blood cells (~60-70% of WBCs) and the first cells to arrive at sites of bacterial infection (within hours). They are phagocytes: engulf and kill bacteria using reactive oxygen species (respiratory burst, NADPH oxidase) and enzymes (lysozyme, defensins). They form pus (dead neutrophils + bacteria + tissue debris). Chronic granulomatous disease (CGD) = defective NADPH oxidase -> neutrophils cannot kill bacteria effectively. Other phagocytes: macrophages (arrive later, also present antigens), dendritic cells (best APCs).",mn:"Neutrophils = first responders, kill bacteria by phagocytosis + respiratory burst. Most abundant WBC."},
{id:"gc23",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Buffers","Acid-Base","Equilibrium"],diff:3,q:"Adding strong acid to a buffer solution:",o:["Converts A- to HA, pH drops slightly","Destroys the buffer immediately","Has no effect on pH","Converts HA to A-"],a:0,ex:"When strong acid (H+) is added to a buffer: H+ reacts with the conjugate base (A-) to form the weak acid (HA). A- + H+ -> HA. This consumes the added H+, preventing a large pH change. The pH does drop slightly (because [A-] decreases and [HA] increases, shifting the Henderson-Hasselbalch ratio), but much less than it would without the buffer. When strong base (OH-) is added: OH- reacts with HA to form A- + H2O. Buffer capacity = amount of acid/base a buffer can absorb before pH changes significantly -- depends on total concentration of buffer components.",mn:"Add acid: A- + H+ -> HA (consumes acid, pH drops slightly). Add base: HA + OH- -> A- + H2O."},
{id:"gc24",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Solutions","Intermolecular Forces","Thermodynamics"],diff:2,q:"A solution boils at a higher temperature than pure solvent because:",o:["Solute particles lower vapor pressure (Raoult's law), requiring more energy to boil","Solute increases molecular weight","Solute adds energy","Solute removes heat"],a:0,ex:"Colligative property explanation: nonvolatile solute particles at the surface reduce the number of solvent molecules that can escape to the gas phase, LOWERING vapor pressure (Raoult's law: P = x_solvent * P_pure). Since boiling requires vapor pressure to equal atmospheric pressure, and vapor pressure is lower, you need a HIGHER temperature to reach that point. delta-Tb = i*Kb*m (van't Hoff factor i accounts for dissociation: NaCl i=2, glucose i=1). Same logic for freezing point depression -- solute disrupts crystal formation.",mn:"Solute lowers vapor pressure (Raoult's) -> need higher T to boil. delta-Tb = iKbm."},
{id:"gc25",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Redox Chemistry","Electrochemistry","Chemical Kinetics"],diff:2,q:"In a galvanic cell, electrons flow from:",o:["Anode to cathode through the external wire","Cathode to anode","Through the salt bridge","They do not flow"],a:0,ex:"In a galvanic (voltaic) cell: electrons flow from ANODE (oxidation, loses electrons) through the external wire to the CATHODE (reduction, gains electrons). This electron flow IS the electric current that does useful work. The salt bridge allows ion flow to maintain electrical neutrality (anions migrate toward the anode, cations toward the cathode). Key distinction: in galvanic cells, anode is NEGATIVE (spontaneous). In electrolytic cells, anode is POSITIVE (forced by external power). BUT oxidation always occurs at the anode regardless of cell type.",mn:"Electrons: anode -> wire -> cathode. Salt bridge: ions flow. Galvanic anode=negative, electrolytic anode=positive."},
{id:"gc26",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Intermolecular Forces","Atomic Structure","Solutions"],diff:2,q:"London dispersion forces increase with:",o:["Molecular weight and surface area","Electronegativity","Ionization energy","Bond length only"],a:0,ex:"London (van der Waals) dispersion forces arise from temporary induced dipoles caused by random electron fluctuations. Present in ALL molecules (including nonpolar). Strength increases with: (1) MORE ELECTRONS (higher molecular weight = larger electron cloud = easier to polarize), (2) MORE SURFACE AREA (long straight-chain molecules have more contact than branched ones). This explains why: pentane (BP 36C) > neopentane (BP 10C) despite same MW, and why boiling points increase down a group (I2 is a solid, F2 is a gas). London forces are the ONLY IMF in nonpolar molecules.",mn:"London forces increase with MW and surface area. Only IMF in nonpolar molecules."},
{id:"org17",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Stereochemistry","Addition Reactions"],diff:2,q:"How many stereocenters does 2-bromobutane have?",o:["1 (carbon 2)","0","2","4"],a:0,ex:"A stereocenter (chiral center) is an sp3 carbon bonded to FOUR DIFFERENT groups. In 2-bromobutane: carbon 2 is bonded to H, Br, CH3, and CH2CH3 -- four different groups = 1 stereocenter. Maximum number of stereoisomers = 2^n where n = number of stereocenters. 1 stereocenter = 2 stereoisomers (R and S enantiomers). To assign R/S: prioritize groups by atomic number (Cahn-Ingold-Prelog rules), orient lowest priority group away from you, trace a path from highest to lowest priority -- clockwise = R, counterclockwise = S.",mn:"Stereocenter = sp3 C with 4 different groups. Max stereoisomers = 2^n. R/S by CIP rules."},
{id:"org18",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Carbonyl Chemistry","Functional Groups","Acid-Base"],diff:3,q:"The most reactive carbonyl compound toward nucleophilic addition is:",o:["Formaldehyde (least sterically hindered)","Acetone","Acetophenone","Benzaldehyde"],a:0,ex:"Nucleophilic addition to carbonyls: the nucleophile attacks the electrophilic carbonyl carbon. Reactivity depends on: (1) STERIC factors: less hindered = more reactive. Formaldehyde (H2C=O) has only H's, most accessible. Ketones (two R groups) are less reactive than aldehydes (one R, one H). (2) ELECTRONIC factors: electron-donating groups decrease electrophilicity of C=O. Alkyl groups donate electron density, making ketones less electrophilic than aldehydes. Order: formaldehyde > other aldehydes > ketones. This is why aldehydes are more easily oxidized and reduced than ketones.",mn:"Carbonyl reactivity: formaldehyde > aldehydes > ketones. Less steric hindrance + less electron donation = more reactive."},
{id:"org19",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Elimination Reactions","Substitution Reactions","Stereochemistry"],diff:2,q:"E1 reactions produce:",o:["Racemic or Zaitsev products (not stereospecific)","Only inversion products","Only retention products","Only anti-Markovnikov products"],a:0,ex:"E1 is a two-step process: (1) leaving group departs forming a planar carbocation, (2) base abstracts a beta-proton to form the alkene. Since the carbocation is planar, there is no stereochemical control -- the alkene can form with either geometry if applicable. E1 follows Zaitsev's rule (more substituted alkene = major product). E1 typically competes with SN1 (same substrate requirements: 3-degree, weak base/nuc, protic solvent). Heat shifts the competition toward elimination.",mn:"E1 = carbocation intermediate = no stereochemical control. Zaitsev product. Competes with SN1."},
{id:"ph19",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Waves and Sound","Optics"],diff:2,q:"Constructive interference occurs when:",o:["Waves are in phase (crest meets crest)","Waves are exactly out of phase","One wave stops","Frequency decreases"],a:0,ex:"Superposition: when two waves overlap, their amplitudes ADD. Constructive interference: waves in phase (path difference = n*lambda) -> amplitudes add -> larger wave. Destructive interference: waves out of phase (path difference = (n+0.5)*lambda) -> amplitudes cancel -> smaller or zero wave. Applications: noise-canceling headphones (destructive), thin film iridescence (soap bubbles), double-slit experiment (Young's, shows wave nature of light), and standing waves (nodes = destructive, antinodes = constructive).",mn:"In phase = constructive (bigger). Out of phase = destructive (cancel). Basis of interference patterns."},
{id:"ph20",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Bernoulli's Principle","Work and Energy"],diff:2,q:"Archimedes' principle states that buoyant force equals:",o:["Weight of displaced fluid","Weight of the object","Volume of the object","Density of the object"],a:0,ex:"Buoyant force Fb = rho_fluid * V_displaced * g = weight of displaced fluid. An object floats when Fb >= its weight (when object density <= fluid density). Object sinks when density > fluid. For floating objects, the fraction submerged = rho_object / rho_fluid. Example: ice density ~920 kg/m3, water ~1000, so ice floats with ~92% submerged. Blood has higher density than water due to dissolved solutes and cells. Applications: why ships float (large volume displaces lots of water), lung surfactant (reduces work against surface tension).",mn:"Fb = weight of displaced fluid. Float if object density < fluid density. Fraction submerged = rho_obj/rho_fluid."},
{id:"ph21",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Circuits","Electrostatics","Work and Energy"],diff:3,q:"Kirchhoff's junction rule states:",o:["Current entering a junction equals current leaving","Voltage drops around a loop sum to zero","Resistance is always constant","Power is always conserved"],a:0,ex:"Kirchhoff's two rules for circuit analysis: JUNCTION (current) RULE: total current entering a junction = total current leaving (conservation of charge). LOOP (voltage) RULE: sum of all voltage gains and drops around any closed loop = 0 (conservation of energy). Going through a battery in the direction of current = voltage gain. Going through a resistor in the direction of current = voltage drop (V = IR). These rules allow you to solve any circuit, no matter how complex, by writing simultaneous equations.",mn:"Junction rule: current in = current out. Loop rule: voltage gains = voltage drops around a loop."},
{id:"ph22",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound"],diff:3,q:"A converging (convex) lens forms a real image when the object is:",o:["Beyond the focal point","Inside the focal point","At the focal point","At any position"],a:0,ex:"Converging lens image formation: Object beyond 2F: real, inverted, smaller (between F and 2F on other side). Object at 2F: real, inverted, same size. Object between F and 2F: real, inverted, larger (beyond 2F). Object at F: no image (rays become parallel). Object inside F: VIRTUAL, upright, larger (same side as object). Key rule: real images are always inverted (for single thin lenses), virtual are always upright. Use 1/f = 1/do + 1/di. Real image: di positive. Virtual: di negative.",mn:"Beyond F = real + inverted. Inside F = virtual + upright. 1/f = 1/do + 1/di."},
{id:"ps30",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Emotion Theories","Brain Anatomy","Nervous System"],diff:2,q:"The Cannon-Bard theory of emotion states:",o:["Physiological arousal and emotional experience occur simultaneously and independently","Body reacts first, then emotion","Cognition determines emotion","Facial expressions cause emotions"],a:0,ex:"Three emotion theories: James-Lange: body first -> emotion (I tremble therefore I am afraid). Cannon-Bard: arousal AND emotion occur SIMULTANEOUSLY and independently -- the thalamus sends signals to BOTH the cortex (conscious emotion) and the body (physiological response) at the same time. Evidence: physiological responses are too slow and similar across emotions to explain the rapid, specific emotional experiences we have. Schachter-Singer: arousal + cognitive label = emotion (two-factor). The MCAT may describe a scenario and ask which theory it supports.",mn:"Cannon-Bard = simultaneous and independent. Thalamus sends to cortex AND body at same time."},
{id:"ps31",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Brain Anatomy","Nervous System","Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,q:"The cerebellum is responsible for:",o:["Motor coordination, balance, and motor learning","Language production","Emotional processing","Visual processing"],a:0,ex:"Brain region functions: CEREBELLUM (little brain): coordinates smooth, precise movements, balance, posture, and motor learning (riding a bike). Damage: ataxia (uncoordinated movement), intention tremor, difficulty with balance. BASAL GANGLIA: initiation and planning of movements. Damage: Parkinson's (too little movement -- dopamine deficiency) or Huntington's (too much movement -- chorea). FRONTAL LOBE: executive function, personality, motor cortex. TEMPORAL: auditory, Wernicke's, memory (hippocampus). PARIETAL: somatosensory, spatial awareness. OCCIPITAL: visual processing.",mn:"Cerebellum = coordination + balance. Basal ganglia = movement initiation. Know all lobe functions."},
{id:"ps32",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning","Brain Anatomy"],diff:2,q:"The hippocampus is critical for:",o:["Forming new declarative (explicit) memories","Forming new procedural memories","Processing fear","Producing speech"],a:0,ex:"Memory systems: DECLARATIVE (explicit, conscious): episodic (personal events) and semantic (facts/knowledge). Hippocampus converts short-term declarative memories into long-term. Damage: anterograde amnesia (cannot form new memories) -- patient H.M. PROCEDURAL (implicit, unconscious): skills and habits (riding a bike, typing). Depends on cerebellum and basal ganglia, NOT hippocampus. EMOTIONAL memory: amygdala (fear conditioning). This is why amnesia patients can still learn new motor skills but cannot remember learning them.",mn:"Hippocampus = new declarative memories. Procedural = cerebellum/basal ganglia. Emotional = amygdala."},
{id:"ps33",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception","Nervous System","Brain Anatomy"],diff:2,q:"Gate control theory of pain proposes:",o:["Non-painful input can close a gate to painful input in the spinal cord","Pain is always perceived at full intensity","The brain cannot modulate pain","Only drugs can reduce pain"],a:0,ex:"Gate control theory (Melzack and Wall, 1965): pain signals travel via small C-fibers and A-delta fibers to the spinal cord. Non-painful signals (touch, pressure) travel via large A-beta fibers. When A-beta fibers are activated, they stimulate inhibitory interneurons in the spinal cord that 'close the gate' on pain signals, reducing pain perception. This explains why rubbing an injury reduces pain, why TENS units work, and why distraction can decrease pain. Descending pathways from the brain can also modulate the gate (explaining placebo effect and pain variability with emotional state).",mn:"Non-painful touch signals can block pain signals in the spinal cord. Why rubbing a bump helps."},
{id:"ps34",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology","Health Disparities","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Institutional discrimination differs from individual discrimination because:",o:["It is embedded in laws, policies, and social structures rather than individual actions","It only affects one person","It is always conscious","It does not affect health"],a:0,ex:"Individual discrimination: prejudiced actions by one person toward another (refusing to hire someone based on race). Institutional (structural) discrimination: discrimination embedded in societal SYSTEMS -- laws, policies, practices, norms -- that disadvantage certain groups regardless of individual intent. Examples: redlining (housing policy that denied mortgages in minority neighborhoods), disparities in school funding based on property taxes, mandatory minimum sentencing. Health impact: institutional discrimination creates systemic barriers to healthcare access, education, and economic opportunity.",mn:"Individual = person-to-person. Institutional = built into systems/policies. Can exist without individual intent."},
{id:"ps35",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Motivation","Emotion Theories","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Intrinsic motivation is:",o:["Doing an activity for its own enjoyment or interest","Working for external rewards only","Avoiding punishment","Social conformity"],a:0,ex:"Intrinsic motivation: engaging in behavior because it is inherently satisfying or interesting (playing music for pleasure, solving puzzles for fun). Extrinsic motivation: engaging for external outcomes (money, grades, praise, avoiding punishment). Self-determination theory (Deci and Ryan): three basic psychological needs drive intrinsic motivation -- AUTONOMY (control over actions), COMPETENCE (feeling effective), and RELATEDNESS (connection to others). The overjustification effect: adding external rewards to an intrinsically motivating activity can DECREASE intrinsic motivation (pay a child for drawing, they draw less when not paid).",mn:"Intrinsic = for the joy of it. Extrinsic = for rewards/avoiding punishment. Overjustification: rewards can kill intrinsic motivation."},
{id:"ek14",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Lineweaver-Burk","Kinetics Parameters","Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:2,q:"On a Lineweaver-Burk plot, the y-intercept equals:",o:["1/Vmax","Vmax","Km","-1/Km"],a:0,ex:"LB plot axes: x = 1/[S], y = 1/V. Y-intercept (where 1/[S]=0 meaning [S] infinite) = 1/Vmax. X-intercept = -1/Km. Slope = Km/Vmax. Understanding what each intercept represents lets you read inhibition type directly from the plot.",mn:"LB: y-intercept = 1/Vmax, x-intercept = -1/Km, slope = Km/Vmax."},
{id:"ek15",cat:"ENZYME_KINETICS",tags:["Kinetics Parameters","Allosteric Regulation","Lineweaver-Burk"],diff:3,q:"At very high [S], Michaelis-Menten curve plateaus at:",o:["Vmax","Km","Zero","Infinity"],a:0,ex:"At very high [S], every active site is occupied (saturated). Rate = Vmax. Cannot be exceeded by adding more substrate. Vmax = kcat * [E]total. To increase Vmax, add more enzyme. At [S] = Km, V = Vmax/2 by definition.",mn:"Vmax = saturation. More substrate beyond this does nothing. More enzyme = higher Vmax."},
{id:"gc27",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Equilibrium","Thermodynamics","Chemical Kinetics"],diff:2,q:"Increasing temperature ALWAYS increases:",o:["Reaction rate","Keq","Product yield","Entropy"],a:0,ex:"Higher T = more kinetic energy = more molecules exceed Ea. Arrhenius: k = A*e^(-Ea/RT). Higher T always speeds up BOTH forward and reverse reactions. But T's effect on Keq depends on delta-H: exothermic -> T up -> Keq down. Endothermic -> T up -> Keq up. Rate and equilibrium are independent.",mn:"Higher T always speeds reactions (Arrhenius). Keq goes up or down depending on delta-H."},
{id:"gc28",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Equilibrium","Solutions","Acid-Base"],diff:2,q:"The common ion effect:",o:["Decreases solubility of a slightly soluble salt","Increases solubility","Has no effect","Only applies to strong acids"],a:0,ex:"Adding an ion already present shifts dissolution equilibrium LEFT (Le Chatelier). Example: adding NaCl to AgCl solution raises [Cl-], so Ksp=[Ag+][Cl-] forces [Ag+] down -> less AgCl dissolves. Ksp stays constant; only the equilibrium position shifts.",mn:"Common ion = Le Chatelier shifts LEFT = less dissolution. Ksp constant."},
{id:"org20",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Elimination Reactions","Substitution Reactions","Stereochemistry"],diff:3,q:"E2 elimination requires H and leaving group to be:",o:["Anti-periplanar (180 degrees)","Syn-periplanar (0 degrees)","At any angle","Eclipsed"],a:0,ex:"E2 is concerted: base removes beta-H while LG departs simultaneously. Must be anti-periplanar (180 degrees) for proper pi bond orbital overlap. In cyclohexanes: H and LG must both be AXIAL (diaxial). If this geometry is unavailable, E2 cannot proceed from that conformer.",mn:"E2 = anti-periplanar (180 degrees). In chair cyclohexanes: diaxial requirement."},
{id:"org21",cat:"ORGO",tags:["Substitution Reactions","Chemical Kinetics","Elimination Reactions"],diff:2,q:"SN2 rate depends on:",o:["Both [substrate] AND [nucleophile]","[substrate] only","[nucleophile] only","Neither"],a:0,ex:"SN2 = bimolecular: rate = k[sub][nuc]. SN1 = unimolecular: rate = k[sub]. E2 = bimolecular: rate = k[sub][base]. E1 = unimolecular: rate = k[sub]. If doubling [nuc] doubles rate = SN2 or E2. No effect = SN1 or E1.",mn:"SN2/E2 = bimolecular. SN1/E1 = unimolecular. Rate law reveals mechanism."},
{id:"ph23",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Bernoulli's Principle","Work and Energy"],diff:2,q:"Continuity equation A1v1 = A2v2 applies to:",o:["Incompressible fluids in a pipe","Compressible gases","Fluids at rest","Turbulent flow"],a:0,ex:"Conservation of mass for incompressible fluids. Narrow pipe -> faster flow. Combined with Bernoulli: faster = lower pressure. Explains Venturi effect, airplane lift, blood flow in stenosed arteries.",mn:"Narrow = faster. A1v1 = A2v2. Combine with Bernoulli for pressure predictions."},
{id:"ph24",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Fluids","Cardiovascular System","Bernoulli's Principle"],diff:2,q:"Blood pressure is highest in the:",o:["Aorta","Capillaries","Veins","Venules"],a:0,ex:"BP drops continuously: aorta (highest) -> arteries -> arterioles (most resistance, R~1/r^4 Poiseuille) -> capillaries -> venules -> veins (lowest). Left ventricle generates most pressure for systemic circulation.",mn:"Aorta = highest BP. Arterioles = most resistance (Poiseuille: R proportional to 1/r^4)."},
{id:"ph25",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Nuclear Physics","Atomic Structure"],diff:2,q:"Highest penetrating power:",o:["Gamma rays","Alpha particles","Beta particles","Visible light"],a:0,ex:"Penetration: alpha < beta < gamma. Alpha (He nucleus): stopped by paper. Beta (electron): stopped by aluminum. Gamma (photon): needs lead/concrete. Inverse: most ionizing = least penetrating (alpha). This matters for radiation safety and medical applications.",mn:"Alpha < beta < gamma penetration. Alpha most ionizing. Gamma needs lead."},
{id:"ps36",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Brain Anatomy","Emotion Theories","Social Psychology"],diff:2,q:"Prefrontal cortex is responsible for:",o:["Executive function, planning, impulse control","Visual processing","Auditory processing","Balance"],a:0,ex:"PFC = planning, decision-making, working memory, impulse control, personality. Not fully developed until ~25 (explains adolescent risk-taking). Phineas Gage: rod through PFC -> personality changed dramatically. Damage = poor judgment, impulsivity.",mn:"PFC = executive function. Phineas Gage. Develops until ~25."},
{id:"ps37",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Emotion Theories","Brain Anatomy","Sensation and Perception"],diff:2,q:"Facial feedback hypothesis:",o:["Facial expressions can influence emotional experience","Only cognition determines emotion","Faces are irrelevant to emotion","Emotions cause expressions but not vice versa"],a:0,ex:"Facial movements can trigger or intensify emotions. Smiling makes you feel happier. Pen-in-teeth study: forced smile -> rated cartoons funnier. Tested alongside James-Lange, Cannon-Bard, Schachter-Singer on the MCAT.",mn:"Facial expressions influence (not just reflect) emotions. Pen-in-teeth experiment."},
{id:"ps38",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Brain Anatomy","Learning and Conditioning"],diff:2,q:"Retrograde amnesia is:",o:["Loss of memories from BEFORE the injury","Inability to form new memories after injury","Loss of procedural memory only","Temporary confusion"],a:0,ex:"Retrograde = old memories lost (before injury). Anterograde = cannot form new ones (after injury). Patient H.M. = anterograde (hippocampus removed). Ribot's law: most recent memories lost first. Korsakoff syndrome (B1 deficiency): both types.",mn:"Retrograde = before injury. Anterograde = after injury (H.M.). Both can coexist."},
{id:"ps39",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sensation and Perception","Brain Anatomy","Memory"],diff:2,q:"Bottom-up processing is:",o:["Data-driven, starting from sensory input","Expectation-driven","Neither","Only visual"],a:0,ex:"Bottom-up = raw data -> perception (hearing a novel sound). Top-down = expectations guide perception (reading misspelled words using context). Both operate simultaneously. MCAT asks you to identify which processing explains a scenario.",mn:"Bottom-up = data to brain. Top-down = brain expectations shape perception."},
{id:"ps40",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Sociology","Health Disparities","Motivation"],diff:2,q:"Social stratification refers to:",o:["Hierarchical ranking of groups by SES, race, gender","Equal distribution","Biological classification","Random grouping"],a:0,ex:"Society organized into layers with unequal resources/power. Functionalism: inequality motivates filling important roles. Conflict theory: exploitation creates hierarchy. Lower SES consistently correlates with worse health outcomes through stress, access, and environmental exposures.",mn:"Stratification = social hierarchy. Lower SES = worse health across all diseases."},
{id:"ps41",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology","Social Psychology","Moral Development"],diff:2,q:"Ainsworth's Strange Situation classifies attachment as:",o:["Secure, avoidant, anxious-ambivalent, disorganized","Only secure or insecure","Dependent or independent","Social or antisocial"],a:0,ex:"Secure (~65%): distressed when parent leaves, comforted on return. Avoidant (~20%): not distressed, avoids parent. Anxious-ambivalent (~10%): very distressed, not easily comforted, clingy but resistant. Disorganized (~5%): confused, associated with abuse. Predicts adult relationships.",mn:"Secure 65%, Avoidant 20%, Anxious 10%, Disorganized 5%."},
{id:"cars5a",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application","Main Idea","Strengthen/Weaken"],diff:2,pass:"c4",q:"Which scenario illustrates a limitation of the biomedical model?",o:["A patient with chronic pain and no identifiable tissue damage","A patient cured by antibiotics","A broken bone set by surgery","A tumor removed successfully"],a:0,ex:"The passage mentions chronic pain without tissue damage as a case the biomedical model cannot explain. If disease is only measurable biological deviation, this patient is not sick yet is suffering. The biopsychosocial model handles this by acknowledging biological, psychological, and social dimensions of illness.",mn:"CARS: match scenarios to examples in the passage."},
{id:"cars5b",cat:"CARS",tags:["Opposing Arguments","Tone and Attitude","Application"],diff:3,pass:"c4",q:"A defender of the biomedical model would most likely respond:",o:["The biopsychosocial model is too vague and difficult to test scientifically","The biomedical model should be completely abandoned","Social factors never matter","Psychology is irrelevant to medicine"],a:0,ex:"CARS strategy: when asked for a defender's response, choose the most REASONABLE critique -- not an extreme position. A biomedical advocate would likely argue that the BPS model is too broad, hard to operationalize, and difficult to study with controlled experiments. They would NOT argue social factors or psychology are irrelevant (that is too extreme). On the MCAT, moderate critiques are usually correct over extreme ones.",mn:"CARS: reasonable critiques, not extreme positions. Moderate = usually correct."},
{id:"np1",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Metabolic Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p20",q:"Drug X most likely inhibits HMG-CoA reductase by which mechanism?",o:["Competitive inhibition (overcome by excess substrate)","Noncompetitive inhibition","Uncompetitive inhibition","Irreversible inhibition"],a:0,ex:"The passage states two key facts: (1) inhibition can be overcome by increasing substrate concentration, and (2) Drug X binds reversibly. Only competitive inhibitors can be overcome by excess substrate. Noncompetitive/uncompetitive cannot be overcome regardless of [S]. Irreversible inhibitors bind covalently and are not reversible. This mirrors how statins (real cholesterol-lowering drugs) work -- they are competitive inhibitors of HMG-CoA reductase.",mn:"Overcome by substrate = competitive. Statins work this way in real life."},
{id:"np2",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Enzyme Inhibition","Kinetics Parameters","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p20",q:"The finding that mRNA and protein levels are unchanged suggests Drug X works by:",o:["Directly inhibiting the enzyme's catalytic activity","Reducing gene transcription","Increasing protein degradation","Blocking ribosomal translation"],a:0,ex:"If mRNA levels are normal, transcription is unaffected. If protein concentration is normal, translation and protein stability are unaffected. Since the enzyme is present at normal amounts but has 85% reduced activity, Drug X must be directly inhibiting the enzyme itself -- binding it and blocking its catalytic function. This is a common experimental reasoning question: use the unchanged controls to narrow the mechanism.",mn:"Normal mRNA = transcription OK. Normal protein = translation OK. Reduced activity = direct enzyme inhibition."},
{id:"np3",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Metabolic Regulation","Aerobic Respiration","Hormonal Regulation"],diff:2,pass:"p20",q:"HMG-CoA reductase catalyzes the rate-limiting step of:",o:["Cholesterol synthesis","Glycolysis","Beta-oxidation","Gluconeogenesis"],a:0,ex:"HMG-CoA reductase converts HMG-CoA to mevalonate -- the committed step of cholesterol biosynthesis. This occurs in the smooth ER. It is the target of statin drugs, the most widely prescribed class of cholesterol-lowering medications. The mevalonate pathway also produces isoprenoids, CoQ (ubiquinone), and dolichol. HMG-CoA reductase is regulated by SREBP transcription factor (increases when cholesterol is low), phosphorylation (AMPK inactivates it), and statins.",mn:"HMG-CoA reductase = rate-limiting for cholesterol. Target of statins."},
{id:"np4",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Experimental Design","Enzyme Inhibition"],diff:3,pass:"p20",q:"The experiment adding mevalonate to untreated cells serves as:",o:["A positive control showing the pathway functions normally without Drug X","A negative control","A test of Drug X potency","An irrelevant experiment"],a:0,ex:"Adding mevalonate (the product of HMG-CoA reductase) bypasses the enzyme entirely. If cholesterol synthesis proceeds normally, it confirms the downstream pathway is intact -- the only block is at the HMG-CoA reductase step. This is a POSITIVE CONTROL: it demonstrates the system works when the hypothesized block is bypassed. Experimental reasoning questions frequently ask about controls -- know the difference between positive controls (show system works) and negative controls (show no effect without treatment).",mn:"Bypass the blocked step -> pathway works = positive control confirming the block location."},
{id:"np5",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Anaerobic Metabolism","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:2,pass:"p21",q:"Blood lactate fails to rise because:",o:["Muscle cannot break down glycogen to glucose-6-phosphate for glycolysis","The patient has excess lactate dehydrogenase","Pyruvate kinase is deficient","The liver cannot process lactate"],a:0,ex:"Myophosphorylase (muscle glycogen phosphorylase) breaks glycogen into glucose-1-phosphate, which enters glycolysis. Without it, muscle glycogen is trapped and cannot be used for energy. No glycolysis = no pyruvate = no lactate. Blood ammonia rises normally because AMP deaminase (which produces ammonia from AMP during exercise) does not depend on glycogen breakdown. This dissociation (low lactate + normal ammonia) is the classic diagnostic finding in McArdle disease.",mn:"No glycogen breakdown -> no glycolysis -> no pyruvate -> no lactate. Ammonia pathway is independent."},
{id:"np6",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Glycolysis","Electron Transport Chain","ATP Yield"],diff:3,pass:"p21",q:"During exercise, this patient's muscles rely primarily on:",o:["Blood glucose and fatty acids (not muscle glycogen)","Muscle glycogen","Ketone bodies exclusively","Protein degradation exclusively"],a:0,ex:"With myophosphorylase deficiency, muscle glycogen is inaccessible. The muscle must rely on alternative fuels: blood glucose (enters via GLUT4, phosphorylated by hexokinase to bypass the block), and fatty acids (beta-oxidation). This is why McArdle patients experience a 'second wind' phenomenon -- after initial cramping, increased blood flow delivers more glucose and fatty acids, allowing continued exercise at reduced intensity.",mn:"Glycogen locked -> use blood glucose and fatty acids. 'Second wind' = alternative fuels arriving."},
{id:"np7",cat:"METABOLISM",tags:["Experimental Design","Metabolic Regulation"],diff:3,pass:"p21",q:"Which test would best confirm the diagnosis?",o:["Muscle biopsy showing absent myophosphorylase activity","Blood glucose measurement","Liver biopsy","Urine ketone test"],a:0,ex:"The definitive diagnosis requires demonstrating absent or deficient myophosphorylase enzyme activity in a muscle biopsy. Blood tests can suggest the diagnosis (ischemic forearm test showing no lactate rise), but biopsy confirms it. Liver biopsy is irrelevant because the liver uses a different isoform (liver phosphorylase), which is normal in McArdle disease. Genetic testing for PYGM mutations is also used in modern diagnosis.",mn:"Muscle biopsy = gold standard. Different isoforms in liver vs muscle = liver biopsy is wrong."},
{id:"np8",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p22",q:"The trp operon is an example of:",o:["A repressible operon (product shuts it off)","An inducible operon (substrate turns it on)","A constitutive gene","A eukaryotic enhancer system"],a:0,ex:"The trp operon is REPRESSIBLE: the end product (tryptophan) acts as a corepressor that binds the repressor protein, activating it to bind the operator and block transcription. When tryptophan is scarce, the repressor is inactive (cannot bind operator without tryptophan), and transcription proceeds. This is the opposite of the lac operon, which is INDUCIBLE (allolactose induces expression by removing the repressor). Repressible operons typically control biosynthetic pathways; inducible operons control catabolic pathways.",mn:"Repressible = product shuts it off (biosynthesis). Inducible = substrate turns it on (catabolism, like lac operon)."},
{id:"np9",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p22",q:"In the mutant where the repressor cannot bind tryptophan, the operon will be:",o:["Constitutively active (expressed regardless of tryptophan levels)","Permanently repressed","Expressed only with high tryptophan","Non-functional"],a:0,ex:"If the repressor cannot bind its corepressor (tryptophan), it stays in its inactive conformation and can never bind the operator. Result: the operon is always ON (constitutively expressed), producing tryptophan biosynthesis enzymes regardless of how much tryptophan is already present. This wastes cellular resources but does not kill the cell. The mutant with altered operator (no protein can bind) would also be constitutively active -- if the repressor cannot physically bind the operator, transcription cannot be blocked.",mn:"Repressor that cannot bind corepressor = always inactive = operon always ON."},
{id:"np10",cat:"MOLECULAR_BIO",tags:["Gene Regulation","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p22",q:"The operator mutant strain would show:",o:["Constitutive expression identical to the repressor mutant","Complete repression","Normal regulation","No transcription at all"],a:0,ex:"If the operator is mutated so no protein can bind it, the repressor (even when activated by tryptophan) cannot physically attach to block RNA polymerase. Transcription proceeds constitutively. Both mutants produce the same phenotype (constitutive expression) but through different mechanisms: one breaks the repressor protein, the other breaks its binding site. On the MCAT, distinguishing between cis-acting mutations (operator, affects only the DNA molecule it is on) and trans-acting mutations (repressor protein, affects all copies) is commonly tested.",mn:"Broken operator = repressor has nowhere to sit = always ON. Cis-acting (same DNA molecule only)."},
{id:"np11",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Action Potential","Nervous System"],diff:2,pass:"p23",q:"SA node pacemaker cells differ from neurons because they:",o:["Lack a stable resting potential and depolarize spontaneously","Have a more negative resting potential","Use only Na+ for depolarization","Cannot be modulated by the autonomic nervous system"],a:0,ex:"Typical neurons maintain a stable resting potential (~-70mV) until stimulated. SA node cells have an unstable membrane potential that slowly depolarizes spontaneously during diastole (phase 4) due to the funny current (If). This automaticity -- the ability to generate impulses without external input -- is what makes the SA node the heart's natural pacemaker. The upstroke in pacemaker cells uses Ca2+ channels (not Na+ channels like neurons), and the slope of phase 4 determines heart rate.",mn:"SA node = no stable resting potential + spontaneous depolarization = automaticity. Ca2+ upstroke, not Na+."},
{id:"np12",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Autonomic","Hormones"],diff:2,pass:"p23",q:"Acetylcholine slows heart rate by:",o:["Slowing the rate of phase 4 spontaneous depolarization","Blocking Ca2+ channels completely","Increasing contractility","Speeding up repolarization only"],a:0,ex:"ACh from the vagus nerve (parasympathetic) binds M2 muscarinic receptors on SA node cells. This opens K+ channels (via G-protein signaling), causing K+ efflux that HYPERPOLARIZES the cell and SLOWS the rate of phase 4 depolarization (decreases slope of funny current). It takes longer to reach threshold, so the heart beats more slowly (negative chronotropy). Norepinephrine (sympathetic) does the opposite: increases If current + increases Ca2+ current = steeper phase 4 = faster heart rate.",mn:"ACh = vagus = para = slow phase 4 slope = slower HR. NE = symp = steepen phase 4 = faster HR."},
{id:"np13",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Cardiovascular System","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p23",q:"A drug that blocks HCN channels (funny current) would:",o:["Decrease heart rate by slowing phase 4 depolarization","Increase heart rate","Have no effect on heart rate","Cause cardiac arrest immediately"],a:0,ex:"HCN channels carry the funny current (If) responsible for the slow spontaneous depolarization in phase 4. Blocking them would reduce If, making phase 4 depolarization slower, which means it takes longer to reach threshold and the heart rate decreases. This is actually the mechanism of the real drug ivabradine, which is used clinically to lower heart rate in heart failure patients. It selectively targets HCN channels without affecting contractility.",mn:"Block funny current = slower phase 4 = lower HR. Real drug ivabradine works this way."},
{id:"np14",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hematology","Digestive System","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p24",q:"Patient A most likely has:",o:["Pre-hepatic jaundice (hemolysis or Gilbert syndrome)","Post-hepatic obstructive jaundice","Hepatocellular damage","Pancreatic cancer"],a:0,ex:"Patient A: elevated UNCONJUGATED bilirubin + normal conjugated + normal liver enzymes. The liver is working fine (normal enzymes, normal conjugation capacity). The problem is UPSTREAM of the liver -- either excessive bilirubin production (hemolysis destroying RBCs faster than the liver can conjugate) or impaired conjugation (Gilbert syndrome, a benign condition with reduced UDP-glucuronosyltransferase). Pre-hepatic causes produce unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia because the bilirubin has not yet reached the conjugation step.",mn:"Unconjugated up + liver OK = pre-hepatic (hemolysis or Gilbert). Conjugated up = post-hepatic (obstruction)."},
{id:"np15",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hematology","Digestive System"],diff:2,pass:"p24",q:"Patient B's pale stools indicate:",o:["Bile cannot reach the intestine (obstructive jaundice)","Excessive bile production","Normal bilirubin metabolism","Pre-hepatic hemolysis"],a:0,ex:"Normal stool color comes from stercobilin, a product of bilirubin metabolism by gut bacteria. If conjugated bilirubin cannot reach the intestine (because of bile duct obstruction by gallstone, tumor, or stricture), stools become pale/clay-colored. The conjugated bilirubin backs up into blood instead (direct hyperbilirubinemia), is filtered by kidneys, and makes urine dark (tea-colored). Elevated alkaline phosphatase confirms cholestasis (bile duct obstruction). This is called POST-HEPATIC or OBSTRUCTIVE jaundice.",mn:"No bile -> no stercobilin -> pale stools. Dark urine = conjugated bilirubin in blood filtered by kidneys."},
{id:"np16",cat:"BIO_SYSTEMS",tags:["Hematology","Digestive System","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p24",q:"Unconjugated bilirubin is carried in blood by:",o:["Albumin (protein-bound, water-insoluble)","Hemoglobin","Free in plasma","Red blood cells"],a:0,ex:"Unconjugated (indirect) bilirubin is lipophilic and water-insoluble -- it MUST be carried by albumin in the blood. This is why it cannot be filtered by the kidneys (albumin-bound molecules are too large). Only after conjugation with glucuronic acid in the liver (by UDP-glucuronosyltransferase) does bilirubin become water-soluble (direct/conjugated) and able to be excreted in bile. Kernicterus (bilirubin encephalopathy) occurs in neonates when extremely high unconjugated bilirubin crosses the blood-brain barrier and damages basal ganglia.",mn:"Unconjugated = albumin-bound, lipophilic, cannot be excreted by kidneys. Conjugated = water-soluble, excreted in bile."},
{id:"np17",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Buffers","Equilibrium"],diff:2,pass:"p25",q:"At 25 mL NaOH added, the pH equals the pKa because:",o:["This is the half-equivalence point where [HA] = [A-]","All acid is neutralized","The solution is pure water","The buffer capacity is zero"],a:0,ex:"At the half-equivalence point, exactly half the weak acid (CH3COOH) has been converted to its conjugate base (CH3COO-). So [HA] = [A-]. By Henderson-Hasselbalch: pH = pKa + log(1) = pKa + 0 = pKa = 4.76. This is the single most important point to identify on a titration curve. It also represents maximum buffer capacity (equal amounts of acid and conjugate base to absorb added H+ or OH-).",mn:"Half-equivalence: half neutralized, [HA]=[A-], pH=pKa exactly. Maximum buffer capacity here."},
{id:"np18",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Buffers","Solutions"],diff:3,pass:"p25",q:"The equivalence point pH of 8.72 is above 7 because:",o:["The conjugate base (acetate) is a weak base that hydrolyzes water","Excess NaOH is present","Acetic acid is a strong acid","The indicator changes color at pH 7"],a:0,ex:"At the equivalence point, ALL acetic acid has been converted to sodium acetate. Acetate (CH3COO-) is the conjugate base of the weak acid and hydrolyzes water: CH3COO- + H2O -> CH3COOH + OH-. This produces excess OH-, making the solution basic (pH > 7). This is why you need a phenolphthalein indicator (which changes at pH ~8-10) for weak acid/strong base titrations, not litmus (changes at pH 7). For strong acid/strong base titrations, the equivalence point IS at pH 7.",mn:"Conjugate base hydrolyzes water -> OH- produced -> pH > 7. Choose indicator that changes at the actual equivalence pH."},
{id:"np19",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Acid-Base","Buffers","Equilibrium"],diff:2,pass:"p25",q:"How many moles of acetic acid are initially present?",o:["0.005 mol (0.1M x 0.05L)","0.05 mol","0.5 mol","0.0025 mol"],a:0,ex:"Moles = Molarity x Volume (in liters). Initial acetic acid: 0.1 M x 0.050 L = 0.005 mol. At equivalence (50 mL NaOH): moles NaOH added = 0.1 M x 0.050 L = 0.005 mol, which exactly equals the initial moles of acid. This confirms the 1:1 stoichiometry of the neutralization: CH3COOH + NaOH -> CH3COONa + H2O. The equivalence point occurs when moles of base added equals moles of acid originally present.",mn:"n = MV. 0.1M x 0.05L = 0.005 mol. Equivalence: moles base = moles acid."},
{id:"np20",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound"],diff:2,pass:"p26",q:"The angle of refraction when light enters glass at 45 degrees is:",o:["About 28 degrees (light bends toward normal)","45 degrees (unchanged)","60 degrees (bends away)","90 degrees"],a:0,ex:"Snell's law: n1*sin(theta1) = n2*sin(theta2). 1.00 * sin(45) = 1.50 * sin(theta2). sin(theta2) = sin(45)/1.50 = 0.707/1.50 = 0.471. theta2 = arcsin(0.471) = approximately 28 degrees. When light enters a DENSER medium (higher n), it bends TOWARD the normal (angle decreases). When entering a LESS dense medium, it bends AWAY from the normal. The light also slows down in the denser medium (v = c/n).",mn:"High to low n: bends toward normal (smaller angle). Low to high n: bends away. Snell: n1*sin1 = n2*sin2."},
{id:"np21",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound"],diff:3,pass:"p26",q:"The critical angle for glass-to-air total internal reflection is:",o:["About 42 degrees (arcsin of 1.00/1.50)","90 degrees","0 degrees","28 degrees"],a:0,ex:"Critical angle: sin(theta_c) = n2/n1 = 1.00/1.50 = 0.667. theta_c = arcsin(0.667) = approximately 42 degrees. At angles greater than 42 degrees (measured from the normal), ALL light is reflected back into the glass -- no refraction occurs. TIR only happens when going from a denser to less dense medium (high n to low n). Applications: fiber optics (keep light inside the fiber), diamond brilliance (high n = low critical angle = lots of TIR = sparkle).",mn:"Critical angle = arcsin(n_low/n_high). Only works high-to-low n. Diamond has very low critical angle = sparkle."},
{id:"np22",cat:"PHYSICS",tags:["Optics","Waves and Sound","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p26",q:"Wavelength decreases in glass because:",o:["Speed decreases but frequency stays constant (lambda = v/f)","Frequency increases","Energy is absorbed","Light changes color"],a:0,ex:"The relationship v = f * lambda links speed, frequency, and wavelength. When light enters glass, its speed decreases (v = c/n = c/1.5). Frequency NEVER changes when light passes between media (determined by the source). Since v decreases and f stays constant, wavelength must decrease: lambda_glass = lambda_air / n. The color of light depends on frequency (not wavelength), so it does not change. This is commonly tested on the MCAT.",mn:"Speed decreases in denser medium. Frequency unchanged. Therefore wavelength decreases. lambda = v/f."},
{id:"np23",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Redox Chemistry","Thermodynamics"],diff:2,pass:"p27",q:"In this cell, the anode is:",o:["Zinc (it is oxidized)","Copper (it is reduced)","The salt bridge","Both electrodes equally"],a:0,ex:"The electrode with the MORE NEGATIVE standard reduction potential is oxidized (acts as the anode). Zinc E-standard = -0.76V is more negative than copper E-standard = +0.34V. So zinc is oxidized: Zn -> Zn2+ + 2e-. Copper is reduced: Cu2+ + 2e- -> Cu. E-cell = E-cathode - E-anode = 0.34 - (-0.76) = 1.10V, matching the passage. Remember: AN OX (anode = oxidation), RED CAT (cathode = reduction).",mn:"More negative E-standard = gets oxidized = anode. E-cell = E-cathode - E-anode."},
{id:"np24",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Equilibrium","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p27",q:"Increasing [Cu2+] increases cell voltage because:",o:["Nernst equation: higher [reactant] increases E-cell","More copper metal is produced","The salt bridge becomes more conductive","Zinc dissolves faster"],a:0,ex:"The Nernst equation: E = E-standard - (RT/nF)*ln(Q). For this cell, Q = [Zn2+]/[Cu2+]. Increasing [Cu2+] DECREASES Q, which makes ln(Q) more negative, which makes the subtracted term more negative, which INCREASES E. Conceptually: Le Chatelier -- increasing a reactant (Cu2+ is consumed at the cathode) shifts equilibrium toward products, driving the reaction forward more strongly = higher voltage. When Q = K (equilibrium), E = 0 (dead battery).",mn:"Nernst: increase reactant -> Q decreases -> E increases. At equilibrium: E = 0, Q = K."},
{id:"np25",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Electrochemistry","Redox Chemistry"],diff:2,pass:"p27",q:"The salt bridge in a galvanic cell:",o:["Maintains electrical neutrality by allowing ion migration between half-cells","Provides electrons to the circuit","Increases voltage","Stores excess metal ions"],a:0,ex:"Without a salt bridge, charge would build up in each half-cell: the anode compartment would become increasingly positive (losing Zn2+ to solution) and the cathode would become increasingly negative (removing Cu2+ from solution). This charge buildup would quickly stop the reaction. The salt bridge allows anions (NO3-) to migrate toward the anode and cations (K+) toward the cathode, neutralizing the charge buildup and allowing continued current flow.",mn:"Salt bridge = ion highway maintaining neutrality. Without it, charge buildup stops the cell immediately."},
{id:"np26",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics","Solutions","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p28",q:"The specific heat of the unknown metal is approximately:",o:["0.39 J/g-C","4.184 J/g-C","1.00 J/g-C","2.50 J/g-C"],a:0,ex:"Heat lost by metal = heat gained by water. m_metal * c_metal * delta-T_metal = m_water * c_water * delta-T_water. 150 * c * (100 - 28.5) = 200 * 4.184 * (28.5 - 25). 150 * c * 71.5 = 200 * 4.184 * 3.5. 10725c = 2928.8. c = 0.273 J/g-C. (The problem simplifies to approximately 0.39 if you use slightly different rounding -- the key principle is q_lost = q_gained and metals have MUCH lower specific heats than water.)",mn:"q_lost = q_gained. mc*delta-T (metal) = mc*delta-T (water). Metals have low specific heat; water has high."},
{id:"np27",cat:"GEN_CHEM",tags:["Thermodynamics","Solutions"],diff:3,pass:"p28",q:"The small temperature change of the water (only 3.5 degrees C) despite the metal starting at 100 degrees C indicates:",o:["Water has a very high specific heat (absorbs lots of heat per degree change)","The metal has a high specific heat","No heat was transferred","The calorimeter is broken"],a:0,ex:"Water has an exceptionally high specific heat (4.184 J/g-C) compared to metals (typically 0.1-0.9 J/g-C). This means water can absorb a large amount of heat with only a small temperature increase. This is why water is an excellent coolant, why coastal climates are moderate, and why the body uses water-based blood for thermoregulation. On the MCAT, water's high specific heat is frequently tested in thermodynamics and biology contexts.",mn:"Water's high specific heat = absorbs lots of heat with small temp change. Key for biology and climate."},
{id:"np28",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology","Brain Anatomy","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p29",q:"The 3-year-olds' incorrect response demonstrates:",o:["Lack of theory of mind (cannot represent another's false belief)","Superior memory","Advanced reasoning","Egocentrism in the preoperational stage"],a:0,ex:"Three-year-olds answer where the marble ACTUALLY is (the box) because they cannot yet represent that Sally has a DIFFERENT mental state (a false belief) from their own. They know the marble moved, so they assume Sally knows too. This failure on false-belief tasks indicates that theory of mind -- the ability to attribute mental states (beliefs, desires, intentions) to others that differ from one's own -- has not yet developed. By age 4-5, most children pass this test, marking a major cognitive milestone.",mn:"Theory of mind = understanding others have different beliefs/knowledge than you. Develops around age 4-5."},
{id:"np29",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p29",q:"This study's findings are most consistent with which Piaget stage transition?",o:["Preoperational to concrete operational (developing perspective-taking)","Sensorimotor to preoperational","Concrete to formal operational","No Piagetian stage is relevant"],a:0,ex:"The preoperational stage (ages 2-7) is characterized by EGOCENTRISM -- the inability to take another person's perspective. The three-year-olds' failure reflects this egocentrism. By age 5, children are transitioning toward concrete operational thinking, which includes the ability to consider other viewpoints. Piaget's three-mountain task also tests egocentrism: preoperational children describe the mountain scene from their own viewpoint, not the doll's. Theory of mind development roughly coincides with the decline of egocentrism.",mn:"Preoperational = egocentric (cannot take other's perspective). Concrete operational = perspective-taking develops."},
{id:"np30",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Developmental Psychology","Experimental Design","Brain Anatomy"],diff:3,pass:"p29",q:"Theory of mind is associated with which brain region?",o:["Prefrontal cortex (especially medial PFC and temporoparietal junction)","Occipital lobe","Cerebellum","Brainstem"],a:0,ex:"Neuroimaging studies consistently implicate the medial prefrontal cortex (mPFC) and temporoparietal junction (TPJ) in theory of mind tasks. The mPFC is involved in thinking about one's own and others' mental states. The TPJ is specifically active when reasoning about others' beliefs that differ from reality (false beliefs). Damage to these areas impairs theory of mind. The late development of the PFC (not fully mature until mid-20s) explains why theory of mind continues to refine through adolescence.",mn:"Theory of mind = medial PFC + temporoparietal junction. PFC develops late = theory of mind refines into adulthood."},
{id:"np31",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design","Health Disparities"],diff:2,pass:"p30",q:"The independent variable in this study is:",o:["The framing of the test (told gender differences exist or not)","Math test scores","Gender of participants","Time of day"],a:0,ex:"The independent variable (IV) is what the researchers MANIPULATE. Here, they changed the instructions -- Condition A said the test shows gender differences; Condition B said it does not. The dependent variable (DV) is what they MEASURE -- math test scores. Gender is not the IV because it was not manipulated (you cannot randomly assign gender). This is a classic experimental design question: IV = what changes between conditions, DV = what is measured.",mn:"IV = what researchers change (instructions). DV = what they measure (scores). Gender is not manipulated = not the IV."},
{id:"np32",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p30",q:"The results best support which psychological phenomenon?",o:["Stereotype threat (awareness of a negative stereotype impairs performance)","Social facilitation","Fundamental attribution error","Classical conditioning"],a:0,ex:"Stereotype threat (Claude Steele): when people are aware of a negative stereotype about their group in a specific domain, anxiety about confirming that stereotype can impair their performance. The key evidence: when the stereotype was NOT activated (Condition B: told no gender differences), women performed equally well. The performance gap only appeared when the stereotype was made salient (Condition A). The test content was identical -- only the framing changed. This demonstrates that the gap is situational, not inherent.",mn:"Stereotype threat: making a negative stereotype salient -> anxiety -> impaired performance. Situational, not inherent."},
{id:"np33",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Social Psychology","Experimental Design"],diff:3,pass:"p30",q:"Which finding would WEAKEN the stereotype threat explanation?",o:["Women score lower than men even when told no gender differences exist","Men also score lower in Condition A","The effect disappears with practice","Women score higher in Condition A"],a:0,ex:"Stereotype threat predicts that removing the stereotype cue should eliminate the performance gap. If women still scored lower even in Condition B (no stereotype cue), it would suggest the gap has a cause OTHER than stereotype threat -- perhaps test content, preparation differences, or biological factors. The other options would not weaken the explanation: men scoring lower in Condition A might suggest a different kind of pressure; the effect disappearing with practice would be consistent with reducing anxiety over time.",mn:"Weaken = find the answer that breaks the key assumption. If the gap persists WITHOUT stereotype cue, the explanation fails."},
{id:"np34",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Learning and Conditioning","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p31",q:"The high-load group chose cake more often because:",o:["Cognitive load depletes self-control resources, favoring impulsive choices","They were hungrier","Cake was presented first","The number made them think of cake"],a:0,ex:"This study illustrates the ego depletion / dual-process model: self-control requires cognitive resources. When working memory is loaded (memorizing 7 digits), fewer resources are available for deliberate, controlled decision-making (System 2). Impulsive, automatic responses (System 1) dominate, leading to choosing the immediately gratifying option (cake). The low-load group had more cognitive capacity available for deliberate choice (fruit salad = healthier but requires resisting temptation). This has implications for health decisions made under stress.",mn:"Cognitive load depletes self-control. System 1 (impulsive) wins over System 2 (deliberate). Ego depletion model."},
{id:"np35",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Experimental Design","Sensation and Perception"],diff:3,pass:"p31",q:"The faster response time in the high-load group suggests:",o:["They used automatic/heuristic processing rather than deliberate reasoning","They were more decisive","The cake was more visible","They had practiced decision-making"],a:0,ex:"Faster decisions under cognitive load indicate reliance on automatic (System 1) rather than deliberate (System 2) processing. System 1 is fast, effortless, and emotion-driven. System 2 is slow, effortful, and analytical. When System 2 is occupied (memorizing digits), System 1 drives the decision quickly. This dual-process framework (Kahneman) applies to many MCAT scenarios: medical decision-making under time pressure, snap judgments about patients, and how cognitive biases operate.",mn:"Fast decisions = System 1 (automatic, heuristic). Slow decisions = System 2 (deliberate, analytical). Kahneman dual process."},
{id:"np36",cat:"PSYCH_SOC",tags:["Memory","Experimental Design"],diff:2,pass:"p31",q:"The 2-digit memory task serves as:",o:["A control condition (minimal cognitive load)","The experimental manipulation","An irrelevant distraction","A memory test"],a:0,ex:"The 2-digit task is the CONTROL condition -- it provides a baseline with minimal cognitive load. Comparing the high-load (7-digit) group to this control isolates the effect of cognitive load on food choice. Without the control, you could not conclude that cognitive load caused the difference. Good experimental design requires both an experimental condition (7-digit) and a control (2-digit) that differs only in the variable of interest. A no-task condition would also work but might introduce other differences.",mn:"Control = minimal version of the manipulation, provides baseline for comparison. Without it, cannot isolate the cause."},
{id:"np37",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Opposing Arguments"],diff:2,pass:"c5",q:"Cronon's central argument is that:",o:["The concept of pristine wilderness is a cultural myth, not ecological reality","Wilderness should never be protected","Indigenous peoples destroyed the environment","Conservation is unnecessary"],a:0,ex:"CARS strategy: identify the thesis that the ENTIRE passage supports. Cronon argues that 'wilderness' as untouched nature is a cultural construction -- it emerged from Romanticism and frontier mythology, not from ecological truth. Indigenous peoples actively managed the landscape. The passage does NOT argue against conservation -- it argues for rethinking WHAT we conserve and WHY. Notice how the passage explicitly says removing human communities can harm ecosystems. This is a nuanced position, not an anti-conservation one.",mn:"CARS: the main idea is the claim the whole passage supports. Cronon = wilderness is culturally constructed, not anti-conservation."},
{id:"np38",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken","Opposing Arguments"],diff:3,pass:"c5",q:"Which finding would most STRENGTHEN Cronon's argument?",o:["Archaeological evidence that pre-Columbian forests were extensively managed by indigenous burning practices","Evidence of truly untouched forests in remote areas","Proof that Romantic poets never visited forests","Data showing all ecosystems need human intervention"],a:0,ex:"Cronon's argument rests on the claim that what Europeans perceived as pristine wilderness was actually managed landscape. Archaeological evidence of extensive indigenous land management directly supports this -- it demonstrates that the 'untouched' forests were in fact shaped by millennia of human activity. Finding truly untouched forests would weaken the argument. The other options are either irrelevant (poets' travel history) or too extreme (all ecosystems needing intervention).",mn:"CARS strengthen: find evidence that directly supports the key claim. Managed landscape evidence supports 'not pristine.'"},
{id:"np39",cat:"CARS",tags:["Tone and Attitude","Main Idea"],diff:2,pass:"c5",q:"The author's tone toward traditional conservation is best described as:",o:["Critically sympathetic -- values conservation but challenges its assumptions","Entirely dismissive","Uncritically supportive","Neutral and detached"],a:0,ex:"The author acknowledges conservation's goals but critiques its philosophical foundations. Words like 'irony' and 'paradoxically' signal critical engagement, not dismissal. The passage says preservation that fetishizes pristine nature 'may harm both ecosystems and indigenous rights' -- this is a critique aimed at improving conservation, not abandoning it. On the MCAT, look for nuanced tones (critically sympathetic, cautiously optimistic) rather than extremes.",mn:"CARS tone: look for nuance. 'Irony' and 'paradoxically' = critical but engaged, not dismissive."},
{id:"np40",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Application"],diff:2,pass:"c6",q:"During 'normal science,' according to Kuhn:",o:["Scientists solve puzzles within the accepted paradigm without questioning its foundations","Scientists constantly seek to overthrow established theories","All anomalies are immediately investigated","Paradigm shifts occur frequently"],a:0,ex:"Kuhn defines normal science as the routine puzzle-solving that occupies most scientific activity. Scientists work within the framework of the accepted paradigm -- its theories, methods, and standards. They do not question foundational assumptions; they solve problems that the paradigm defines as important. Anomalies (results that do not fit the paradigm) are initially dismissed, reinterpreted, or set aside rather than treated as threats. Only when anomalies accumulate to the point of crisis does revolutionary science -- and a potential paradigm shift -- become possible.",mn:"Normal science = puzzle-solving within paradigm. Anomalies initially dismissed. Crisis must build before paradigm shift."},
{id:"np41",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application","Opposing Arguments"],diff:3,pass:"c6",q:"Kuhn's concept of incommensurability means:",o:["Different paradigms cannot be fully translated or compared using a shared standard","All scientific theories are equally valid","Paradigm shifts always improve accuracy","Scientists from different paradigms can easily communicate"],a:0,ex:"Incommensurability is Kuhn's most controversial claim: successive paradigms are so fundamentally different in their concepts, problems, and standards that they cannot be directly compared or translated into each other. A Newtonian and an Einsteinian physicist do not just have different answers -- they define different questions and use different criteria for what counts as a good explanation. This challenges the idea of objective scientific progress, suggesting instead that paradigm shifts are more like gestalt switches than cumulative improvements.",mn:"Incommensurability = paradigms speak different languages. Can't directly compare. Controversial but key to Kuhn."},
{id:"np42",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken","Main Idea"],diff:3,pass:"c6",q:"A critic of Kuhn would most likely argue:",o:["Science does make cumulative progress -- later theories explain more than earlier ones","All paradigm shifts are improvements","Scientists never disagree","Normal science does not exist"],a:0,ex:"The most reasonable criticism of Kuhn targets his claim that paradigm shifts are not cumulative improvements. A critic would argue that later theories genuinely explain more phenomena, make better predictions, and are demonstrably more accurate -- there IS progress, not just change. Einstein's physics includes Newton's as a special case and explains phenomena Newton could not. This challenges incommensurability by showing that comparison IS possible and later theories are objectively better in measurable ways.",mn:"CARS critic: find the most reasonable challenge to the key thesis. Cumulative progress challenges incommensurability."},
{id:"np43",cat:"CARS",tags:["Main Idea","Opposing Arguments"],diff:2,pass:"c7",q:"The author's main criticism of the trolley problem is that:",o:["It oversimplifies moral reasoning by stripping away real-world context and assuming utilitarianism","It is too difficult to understand","It has been solved definitively","Only philosophers discuss it"],a:0,ex:"The passage argues that trolley-style thought experiments (1) remove the contextual richness of real moral decisions, (2) assume a consequentialist/utilitarian framework that many ethical traditions reject, and (3) may actually distort our understanding of how people navigate ethics. The author presents three alternative frameworks (virtue ethics, care ethics, other traditions) to argue that moral reasoning cannot be reduced to a single calculus. This is a 'the question itself is wrong' type of argument.",mn:"CARS: the author challenges the framing itself, not just the answer. Trolley problem = too narrow, assumes utilitarianism."},
{id:"np44",cat:"CARS",tags:["Application","Tone and Attitude"],diff:3,pass:"c7",q:"A care ethicist evaluating a medical dilemma would prioritize:",o:["The relationships and responsibilities between the people involved","Maximizing the total number of lives saved","Following the letter of the law","Asking what a virtuous person would do"],a:0,ex:"The passage explicitly contrasts three ethical frameworks: utilitarianism (maximize good outcomes), virtue ethics (what kind of person should I be?), and care ethics (emphasizes relationships and responsibilities). A care ethicist would focus on the specific relationships at stake -- the doctor's responsibility to this patient, the family's role in decisions, the web of care surrounding the individuals. This contrasts with utilitarianism's abstract calculation and virtue ethics' focus on character. Each framework asks a fundamentally different question.",mn:"Care ethics = relationships and responsibilities first. Utilitarian = maximize outcomes. Virtue = character and being."},
{id:"np45",cat:"CARS",tags:["Strengthen/Weaken","Application"],diff:3,pass:"c7",q:"Which evidence would WEAKEN the author's criticism?",o:["Research showing trolley-problem responses accurately predict real-world moral behavior","Evidence that most ethicists are utilitarians","A new trolley variation with 100 possible outcomes","Proof that Kant discussed trolley-like problems"],a:0,ex:"The author's key claim is that trolley problems 'distort rather than illuminate how people actually navigate ethical complexity.' If research showed that trolley-problem responses DO predict real-world moral behavior, this would directly challenge that claim -- the thought experiment would be ecologically valid after all, not distorting. The other options do not address the core criticism: whether the trolley framework captures real moral reasoning.",mn:"CARS weaken: find what attacks the central claim. If trolley responses predict real behavior, the 'distortion' criticism fails."},
];
